1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 ({Hey! Thank you so much for enrolling in the course. I am sure that if you are here, it's likely because you're seeking a reliable response to White's 1.d4 . Rest assured, you're in for a treat. Back in 2014, I was a full-fledged International Master and was hunting for my Grandmaster title. On the one hand, I was doing well by regularly employing the Caro-Kann defence against 1.e4 , while on the other hand, I was experiencing serious difficulties against 1.d4 . I used to play only the Vienna variation against 1.d4 , that is, d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {Nc3 dxc4 . Opponents consistently surprised me with new ideas, forcing me to tackle fresh problems in each game. Desperate for a new line that was solid and required less preparation, I stumbled upon this line that we are going to explore in the course. It aligned perfectly with my style as well as my intention to get a solid position out of the opening. I quickly analysed it and started employing it in my games. My first experience with this line was against GM Dejan Antic while playing a tournament in Greece in 2014. I held him to a comfortable draw with the Black Pieces. After the game, I realised how easy it was to prepare this endgame line, play it in serious tournaments and hold even Grandmasters to a comfortable draw. Since then, this line has always been a part of my Black side repertoire against 1.d4 . I did not shy away from playing this variation, even against strong opposition and in crucial games. For example, I played it against GM Nigel Short in Gibraltar 2018 and held him to a quick draw. I have been analysing and updating this line for many years now. It has not only helped me achieve good results but also helped my students get solid equality out of the opening in their crucial rounds. Since 2014, the engines became stronger as time passed, and this variation underwent many changes. It evolved with time. The only thing that remained constant is its reputation of being a solid variation against 1.d4 . Nowadays, it is fondly known as the Berlin of 1.d4 since the mainline involves the exchange of Queens on the d8 -square, quite similar to the Berlin defence, which is considered one of the most solid defences against 1.e4 . The position we study in this course arises after the initial moves d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} exd5 5. Nc3 c5 {. By playing the move} 6. dxc5 {, we show our intentions to play this solid endgame line. Learning this line can also be a great weapon for those who already play the Queen’s Gambit Declined as Black with} Be7 {, the Vienna Variation with dxc4 (as I used to play) or the Ragozin Defence with Bb4 . This line can also be a great weapon for players who play the Semi-Tarrasch variation as Black after c5 cxd5 and now either} 7. Nxd5 {or the more popular exd5 . The course is divided into 8 chapters, followed by a model games section. The first 4 chapters contain sidelines that White can employ to avoid entering the endgame line, while the last 4 chapters focus on how to play in the main line where Queens get exchanged early on in the opening. I am sure by the end of this course, you will develop a confidence within yourself that you have mastered a solid line against 1.d4 , which you can play even against strong Grandmasters! Let us embark on this journey together!}) *

