1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 {White is all set to enter the Queen's Gambit Declined, the Ragozin Defence, the Semi-Slav Defence, or the Vienna Opening, depending on how Black responds on the 4th move. But we challenge White's centre immediately and enter the Semi-Tarrasch opening.} c5 {This is the starting point of our opening repertoire. From here on, I have covered all of White's options, from the sidelines to the mainlines. With ... c5 , we directly challenge White's centre and look forward to some Pawn exchanges there.} 5. cxd5 {This has always been White's main response to ... c5 .} (5. Bf4 {and other sidelines are covered in Chapter 1.}) (5. Bg5 {is covered in Chapter 1.}) (5. g3 {is also covered in the first chapter.}) (5. e3 {is covered in Chapter 2.}) 5... cxd4 {Surprise Surprise! White may have expected us to recapture on d5 , but we give them the taste of their own medicine! It is now White who has to decide about recapturing on d4 first as his c3 -Knight is under attack.} (5... exd5 {has been played for decades now, but this is being quickly replaced by cxd4 and} 6. Nxd5 {in recent times.}) (5... Nxd5 {also aims to get a solid game. The drawback is that it hands over the centre to White, which gives them a lot of dynamic options to attack on the Kingside.} 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O {is how the game goes forward.}) 6. Qxd4 {Clearly, a much better attempt to try to get an initiative in the opening. Generally, it is advised not to bring out your Queen early on in the opening as it may be harassed by the opponent's Pieces. But here, Black does not have ... Nc6 as of yet. Also, White forces Black to recapture on d5 , which leads to an Isolated Queen Pawn, which White can then choose to play against.} (6. Nxd4 {is covered in Chapter 3.}) (6. Qa4+ {Is also a part of the 3rd chapter.}) 6... exd5 7. e4 {White's direct attempt to fight for the initiative. This is also the start of Chapter 5.} (7. g3 $6 {prepares an untimely fianchetto for the light squared Bishop. It is taken care of in Chapter 4.}) (7. Qa4+ {is more of a prophylactic move. It is also covered in Chapter 4.}) (7. e3 {is covered in Chapter 4.}) (7. Bg5 {is a huge alternative to the mainline e4 and t is covered in Chapter 4.}) 7... dxe4 {We invite White to an endgame.} 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ (10. a3 $5 {along with all sidelines on the 10th move are covered in Chapter 5.}) 10... fxe6 11. Bg5 {Pins our Knight and threatens to take on e4 . Now, we have two ways to deal with it; both lines have two separate dedicated chapters.} (11. Bc4 {Develops the Bishop while attacking the e6 -Pawn at the same time. This is covered in Chapter 6.}) 11... Nc6 {Develops the Queenside first and is covered in the final chapter of this course - Chapter 8.} (11... h6 {more or less forces White to exchange on f6 . This is covered in detail in Chapter 7.}) *

