1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bf4 {This has been recently tried by none other than the world number one Magnus Carlsen. The idea of developing the Bishop to f4 is to combine it with ideas like Nb5 creating threats on the Queenside.} cxd4 {We carry on with our plan.} 6. Nxd4 Nbd7 {This slightly unusual move is an important one to remember in this variation. Black threatens to win a Piece with ... e5 .} ({For example, cxd5? loses to} 6... e5 {winning a Piece.}) 7. Qa4 {The critical try for White. They prevent us from playing ... e5 while also vacating the d1 -square for their Rook.} Bc5 {Developing the Bishop with a tempo while also preparing ... O-O .} 8. Nb3 O-O {Done with our Kingside development, we can now focus on developing our Queenside, too.} 9. Nxc5 Nxc5 10. Qa3 b6 {White has managed to win the Bishop pair, but he lacks Kingside development. We can use this to our advantage by gaining some other form of advantage, like more control in the centre, as Narayanan did in a game against Abdusattorov.} 11. e3 Bb7 12. Rd1 ({The hasty} 12. Be2 $6 {is met by} dxc4 {when White's g2 Pawn hangs. Black also plans to play ... Nd3 +.}) 12... Qe7 {Getting away from the pin on the d -file and once again preparing ... dxc4 .} 13. Be2 e5 {Black gets control over the centre first before going for ... dxc4 .} 14. Bg5 dxc4 15. O-O {White completes his development, but we make it tough for them to regain their Pawn.} Qe6 {And it is up to White to equalise the position. Abdusattorov,N (2716)-Narayanan,S (2651) Douglas IOM 2023 ended in a draw in 33 moves.} *

