1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other alternatives. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Nxd4 e5 {This is the most challenging continuation that gives Black opportunities to seize the initiative. In most cases we would like to continue with ... d4 next, gaining more space in the centre.} 7. Nf3 {This is the most played move in this position.} d4 {Now, Bxf6 can be met by gxf6 and we transpose here.} 8. Nd5 {White pressurises the f6 -Knight while also threatening to take the e5 -Pawn next.} Be7 9. Bxf6 (9. Nxe5 $4 {is obviously a blunder due to} Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 {and we are a clear Piece up.}) 9... Bxf6 10. e3 {White quickly breaks in the centre.} dxe3 11. fxe3 e4 {Opening the a1 - h8 diagonal and gaining more space in the centre.} 12. Nd4 Nc6 ({It is better to pressurise the d4 -Knight immediately than} 12... O-O {, played in Reinecke, R (2059)-Emrich, E (2073) GER email 2013, which ended in a draw in 25 moves.}) 13. Nxf6+ {This leads to an endgame.} Qxf6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Qd4 Qxd4 16. exd4 f5 {Black enjoys slightly better chances thanks to our advanced Pawns on e4 and f5 . We have a clear passed Pawn on the e -file, while White will have to work harder to create one on the Queenside.} *

