1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. cxd5 {White exchanges Pawns on d5 before we can do it on c4 .} exd5 7. Be2 {This is the most natural move in this position. White simply develops the Bishop and prepares O-O .} Nc6 8. O-O cxd4 {I prefer to exchange on d4 first before developing our Bishop to d6 . If we develop our Bishop directly to d6 , then White can disturb it by playing dxc5 .} (8... Bd6 {is the other alternative. Black invites White to exchange on c5 , which places our Bishop on the g1 - a7 diagonal. The game would continue with} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 {This is a completely playable position for both sides. A typical situation where one side plays with an Isolated Queen's Pawn while the other side plays against it. Generally, I prefer to keep my Bishop on the h2 - a7 diagonal. Only when White plays g3 do I transfer my bishop to the g1 - a7 diagonal.}) 9. Nxd4 {This is more logical than recapturing with the Pawn. White wants to play against the typical IQP.} Bd6 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 {This is a typical position where one side plays with an IQP and one against it. Black should try to keep the exchange of Pieces to the minimum and try to create attacking chances on the kingside. White aims to transpose the game to an endgame.} Re8 {The Rook is useful along the e -file. It can also be transferred to the Kingside if required in the attack.} 12. Nxc6 {This avoids Black's equalising idea of ... Nxd4 followed by ... Be5 and then ... d4 , but it connects Black’s Pawns in the centre. However, White aims to create pressure on the c6 -Pawn next.} bxc6 13. Rc1 {It is clear White has a better Pawn structure as they have fewer Pawn islands (2 vs. 1). But we have more space thanks to our d5 -Pawn.} h5 {This is an important move. Black needs to start action on the Kingside immediately in order to create timely pressure on White's Kingside. By advancing our Pawn to h5 , we not only gain space but also gain access to the g4 -square, which we can use by playing ... Ng4 next.} 14. Na4 {White is focused on their Queenside strategy of creating pressure on our Pawn structure.} Ng4 {And we are focused on our own on the Kingside! The arrival of our Knight at g4 rings bells on White's Kingside.} 15. Bxg4 {White eliminates the dangerous Knight and aims to focus his energy on exploiting his superiority on the Queenside.} Bxg4 16. Qd4 {It is essential to provoke ... Be5 before placing the Queen on d2 .} Be5 17. Qd2 {Since the dark-squared bishops are facing each other, we don’t have enough time to execute our Kingside tricks.} Bxb2 18. Qxb2 {It seems that with the departure of the dark-squared Bishops, White's strategy to dominate the Queenside is coming to life. But despite having fewer Pieces on the board, we can create sufficient pressure on White's Kingside.} Qg5 {Defending the c6 -Pawn passively is not to our taste. Our first instinct should be to create counter-threats on the Kingside.} 19. Kh1 {White gets away from the pin on the g -file. Once again, he threatens to capture the c6 -Pawn.} Rad8 {Another surprising idea. We plan to transfer our Rook with ... Rd6 -... Rg6 . Another important idea is to push ... d5 - d4 and open up lines for our Pieces. As we'll see in the theory section, even after White captures on c6 we get enough activity to balance the game.} *

