1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Qa4 {This is an interesting prophylactic move played in a few games and also recommended by Sam Shankland in his 1.d4 Lifetime Repertoire on Chessable. White moves his Queen away from d4 before we attack it with ... Nc6 .} ({The point is that if we play Nc6 now, then he can create pressure on our Knight by playing} 9. Bb5 {.}) 9... h6 {A useful move for Black. It is clear that White is not going to exchange on f6 and will respond with Bh4 . By inserting ... h6 , Black ensures that there will be no back-rank issues in the future. We also get an option of playing ... g5 if needed.} 10. Bh4 Qb6 {We threaten the b2 -Pawn immediately, forcing White to react to it. If we delay this, then White has the option of ignoring this threat altogether, as can be seen in the 10...Be6 variation.} (10... Nc6 $6 {is inferior as after} 11. Bb5 Bd7 12. O-O a6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Ne5 {Even though objectively the position is around equal, practically, I think White has a slight edge as he can create slow and steady pressure against Black's c6 / d5 Pawns. In Vidit,S (2726) -Santos Latasa,J (2608) Tornelo INT 2021, White won in 53 moves.}) 11. Qb5 {This is the only sensible way of covering the b2 -Pawn. White also offers a trade of Queens which is generally said to favour the side playing against the Isolated Queen Pawn. But Black is quite solid, and the Queen trade is not to be feared. One of White's ideas is now to exchange on f6 and then capture the d5 -Pawn.} Be6 ({Covering the d5 -Pawn. It is, of course, possible to play the natural} 11... Nc6 {, but I prefer to keep the c -file open for the moment as it can be used by our Rook to create pressure.}) 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. Bd3 {It is better to place the Bishop on d3 in order to control the e4 -square and avoid any future ... Ne4 ideas.} Rc8 {Of course, there are other equivalent ways to proceed in this position, but exploiting the open c -file is more logical.} 14. O-O Ba3 {This is the point behind Black's previous move. We exploit the instability of White's c3 -Knight and he is forced to respond to our threat of ... Bxb2 .} 15. Nd1 {The Knight moves back to a passive square. We have managed to disturb White's Piece coordination so we can relax for a move and simply pull back our Bishop, too.} (15. Bxf6 {leads to a sequence of forced exchanges after} Bxb2 16. Nxd5 Bxa1 17. Ne7+ Kf8 18. Nxc8 Bxf6 19. Nxb6 Rxa2 {, and only Black can be better in this endgame due to the Bishop pair and an outside passed Pawn.}) 15... Be7 16. a3 {This push strengthens the a -Pawn and also covers the a3 -square. However, it weakens the b3 -square, which we can try to create pressure on with our Knight manoeuvre.} Nbd7 17. Nd4 Nc5 18. Bc2 {And now it is time to activate the other Knight:} g5 19. Bg3 Nfe4 {Both our Knights are beautiful placed. We intend to play ... Bf6 soon when all our Pieces are participating as one unit while the same cannot be said about White's army. Black has a pleasant position.} *

