1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 {This is clearly the most direct way to fight for an initiative in the opening. White challenges our d5 -Pawn and opens up his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} dxe4 ({This move started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. Earlier, the mainline was to first play} 7... Nc6 {and only then exchange on e4 with ... dxe4 .}) ({However, time has proven that it is much easier for Black to play the direct} 7... dxe4 {. The point is that it is beneficial for Black to remain flexible with the positioning of our Queenside Knight.}) 8. Qxd8+ (8. Nxe4 $4 {is out of the question due to} Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxe4 {wins a Piece for Black.}) 8... Kxd8 {This Queen exchange is comparable to the Queen exchange in the Berlin Defence. There, too, the Queens get exchanged on the d8 -square, and we quickly reach an endgame. The endgame there is more complicated than the one here. We may need to invest a few more moves to take our King to a comfortable square, but we are always on time to do it as we will study in this and upcoming chapters.} 9. Ng5 {A logical move threatening both the e4 and f7 -Pawns.} Be6 {Again, a typical way of defending the f7 -Pawn. We are not afraid of an exchange on e6 even though it ruins our Pawn structure. Next, we intend to play ... Bb4 followed by ... Ke7 .} 10. a3 {A solid prophylactic move preventing our idea of ... Bb4 . This is also a bit counter-intuitive since, when the opponent is behind in development, we tend to develop our Pieces quickly and punish our opponent for ignoring development. But here, White finds time to calm down and first prevent ... Bb4 .} Nbd7 {It is better to develop our Knight to d7 . It can later go to c5 , protecting the e4 -Pawn and also exploiting the newly created weak b3 -square. Now, White has tried four different ways to put pressure on Black.} 11. Ncxe4 {White regains the Pawn first before initiating active measures.} Nxe4 12. Nxe4 h6 {A useful move similar to White's 10.a3 . We take control of the g5 -square, closing the doors for White's Knight retreat again on g5 . Next, we can play .... Nc5 offering the exchange of Knights.} 13. Bf4 {White develops his Bishop and prepares O-O-O at the same time. Another idea behind Bf4 is to provoke Black to play ... g5 or ... f5 . This gains space for Black but also gives White targets to attack on the Kingside.} (13. Be3 {is comfortably met by} f5 14. Ng3 Bc5 {and Black is doing fine.}) 13... Rc8 {A novelty with the simple intention of preventing White from castling on the Queenside. We can also think of infiltrating White's camp with ... Rc2 at the right moment.} (13... Nc5 $2 {is a mistake now. White has the simple} 14. Rd1+ $1 {forcing us to retreat our Knight to d7 . If we don't, then we may incur material losses.}) 14. Rd1 {White immediately pins the Knight before developing his light-squared Bishop.} f5 {A typical pressure releasing move for us. We push White's Knight away from the centre and create a potential safe haven for our King on f7 .} 15. Ng3 g5 {Gaining space with a tempo and also preparing to fianchetto our Bishop to g7 .} 16. Be5 Rh7 {Threatening ... Bb3 .} 17. Bd3 ({An interesting attempt to create some complications.} 17. Bc3 Bg7 {is just plain equal.}) 17... Nxe5 18. Bxf5+ Rd7 19. Bxe6 Rxd1+ 20. Kxd1 {White has managed to win a Pawn, but we have a simple reply.} Rc6 {We are going to play either ... Nc4 or ... Nd3 , which instantly recovers our lost Pawn and maintains complete equality.} *

