[Black "Mainline - 11.Bg5 h6 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D41"]
[PlyCount "34"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 {White pins the f6 -Knight and prepares to capture the e4 -Pawn with Nxe4 . By developing his dark-squared Bishop, White also prepares to play O-O-O on the next move. Now, there are two ways for Black to proceed: 11...h6 and 11...Nc6 . Both are doing quite fine at top-level chess.} {h6 keeps the game open, and you will have to keep playing as there is no direct draw. The endgame is equal, and the game should logically end in a draw. But you may also get a few chances to outplay your opponent in case he misplays the endgame or over-pushes it. Nc6 is like killing the game to a draw. There are numerous games between top GMs where Black ends up in an opposite-coloured Bishop endgame, a Pawn down. But that endgame is quite easy to hold to a draw. In chapter 7,  we will be studying the move h6 , while in chapter 8,  we will focus on the other main alternative, Nc6 .} h6 {By playing ... h6 , we force White to make a decision with his Bishop on g5 . Once White decides how to respond to the threat to his Bishop, we can start bringing our Pieces out in the battle.} 12. O-O-O+ {It makes sense to make this useful move before deciding the fate of their dark-squared Bishop.} Ke7 {This might seem like an illogical move as it blocks the path of the f8 -Bishop. But it is important to place the King on e7 rather than on e8 . The point is that, from the e7 -square, our King defends both the e6 and f6 -Pawns (after White exchanges on f6 and Black recaptures back with ... gxf6 ). By defending our Pawns beforehand, we save an important tempo that we can utilise in developing our Pieces. Now, White has to choose a destiny for their Bishop.} 13. Bh4 {This maintains the pin on the f6 -Knight, and White still threatens to capture the e4 -Pawn. The inclusion of ... h6 and Bh4 is in Black's favour because we can play ... g5 whenever required, kicking White's Bishop further.} Kf7 {Unpinning the f6 -Knight, which also opens up our f8 -Bishop.} 14. Rd8 {This aggressive move looks a bit scary at first sight. However, Black has an easy way to neutralise White's active Rook.} g5 {This is where we see the benefit of inserting the move ... h6 . Now we get to play ... g5 and ... Bg7 with a tempo.} 15. Bg3 Bg7 {And White is forced to exchange Rooks.} 16. Rxh8 Bxh8 17. Bb5 a6 {Kicking the Bishop away before we develop our Knight with ... Nc6 . After the bishop retreats, our knight will join the action via c6 - d4 . See more here.} ({The immediate} 17... Nc6 $6 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Re1 {might give White slightly better chances because of the additional weakness of the c6 -Pawn.}) *

