1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 Nc6 {We simply develop our Knight and will decide to place our King on e7 or e8 , depending on how White responds.} 12. Bc4 {White first develops the Bishop with a threat. They still keep the suspense of which side to castle wide open.} Ke7 {We aim to transfer our King to a safer square while defending the e6 -Pawn at the same time.} 13. Nxe4 Kf7 {Our king has reached the desired safe square on f7 . Now White's e4 -Knight hangs, and we are also ready to develop our dark-squared Bishop.} 14. Bxf6 {White exchanges on f6 with their Bishop, as they value it less than their Knight. It also does not lose time, and the e4 -Knight can used to create further pressure.} gxf6 15. O-O-O {White is confident that our Pieces are not quick enough to come in action to prevent White's threats. They are right in their assessment. But the presence of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board gives us great drawing chances. First, we should exchange a pair of Rooks to relieve some pressure of the position.} Rd8 16. Rxd8 Nxd8 17. Rd1 {White has managed to push our Knight to the 8th rank and once again threatens Rd7 +, along with, of course, just hitting our Knight.} Be7 {Our knight on d8 is now rock-solid. We also prevent a check on the 7th rank.} 18. Rd7 {The Rook enters our camp with confidence and high hopes of winning decisive material. Nd6 + is the immediate threat.} f5 {Yes, we invite White to execute their idea! Our point is that we vacate the f6 -square for our King, which will help us free our Bishop from the annoying pin on the 7th Rank. We are ready to sacrifice a Pawn betting on the fact that opposite-coloured Bishops will help us hold comfortably in this endgame.} 19. Nd6+ (19. Nc5 {leads to the same thing and transposes after} Kf6 20. Nxb7 {.}) 19... Kf6 20. Nxb7 Nxb7 21. Rxb7 Bc5 {11 games out of 12 have been drawn from this endgame. White miraculously managed to squeeze water from a stone in the only game where Black lost. Such a high tendency for a draw clearly indicates that Black is safe. It is not going to be easy for White to create a passed Pawn on the Queenside. Moreover, we also have a chance to create a passed e -Pawn, which can provide sufficient counterplay. Here, White has two plans. First, they can just play f3 and save their f -Pawn. The second one is to sacrifice the f2 -Pawn in favour of attacking our e6 -Pawn. This would tie our Rook to its defence, and then White would give their best shot to quickly create a passed pawn along the b -file.} 22. Rc7 {Hitting our Bishop and aiming to go Rc6 .} Bxf2 23. Rc6 Re8 24. b4 {White lauches their Queenside pawns straight away. Now, Black has three ways to continue. 1) Place the King on e5 and manouevre the Bishop to d6 , getting rid of the pressure on the e6 -Pawn. This helps us free the Rook. See here.  2) Sacrifice the e6 -Pawn and exchange Rooks directly. See here.  3) Include ... Bg1 and h2 - h3 first, and then sacrifice the e6 -Pawn to exchange Rooks. I feel the third way is the most secure way to claim a draw and that is why I have included that one as the mainline. However, opting for the first two will draw the game as well.} (24. Kd2 {was tried in one top game by White but it did not make any difference. The game continued} Re7 25. b4 Ke5 26. Ke2 Bg1 27. h3 f4 {and now after} 28. Bb3 Kf5 {players repeated the position with} 29. Bc2+ Ke5 30. Bb3 Kf5 31. Bc2+ Ke5 32. Bb3 Kf5 {with a draw. Nguyen, T (2645)-Vidit, S (2724) Saint Louis USA 2022.}) 24... Bg1 ({Forcing White to push the Pawn to a light square, which will help us create a safe blockade on the dark squares. This is a typical theme we see in many opposite-coloured Bishop endgames. This is just a more technical subtlety. Black can very well just play} 24... Rb8 {directly and I offer it as an alternative. The theory section continues further and I have included the best continuation and two reference games here.}) *

