1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. g3 {A late attempt to transpose to the Catalan territory. This may be completely playable against any other response by Black on the 4th move. But here, we are ready to smash White's centre.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 {Snatching the first opportunity to grab space in the centre. Gaining space in the centre with a tempo is a cherry on the cake.} 7. Nf3 d4 {And we march ahead, this time attacking White's other Knight. I am sure White must be regretting bringing his Knights early on in the game.} 8. Nxe5 {An attempt to muddy the waters.} Qd6 {This is the precise refutation of White's Pawn grab. We place our Queen on a better square so that we can recapture it with our Bishop. Now, both White's Knights are under attack, and White can only save one.} 9. Qa4+ Nbd7 {Only this move guarantees that we win a Piece.} 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 {Once again, White is faced with a dual threat.} 11. Nb5 {The only move to avoid material losses. But White won’t be able to resist for long as the Knight has voluntarily entered a dangerous pin.} Qc6 12. Rg1 a6 13. Qa5 (13. Bg2 {is simply met by} Qc8 {followed by collecting the b5 -knight.}) 13... b6 {We chase away White's Queen while also preventing Nc7 +.} 14. Bg2 bxa5 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Nc7+ Kd7 17. Nxa8 Bxa8 {Our two Pieces are too strong compared to White's Rook. Black has a winning advantage.} *

