1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. dxc5 {This is a move that you are hardly going to face in your games. It also seems like a premature capture because, generally, White captures on c5 if Black has already moved his Bishop from f8 , thus wasting Black's move as we will have to recapture on c5 . Or, if White has already played a3 , then when Black plays ... Bxc5 , White gets in b4 . This gains space for White on the Queenside as well as allows them to fianchetto their Bishop on b2 .} Bxc5 6. cxd5 {This is a logical follow-up to White's previous move. White forces an IQP on d5 and intends to play against it. That being said, Black has a very comfortable version of the IQP.} exd5 7. e3 {White gets ready to develop his f1 -Bishop and O-O .} O-O 8. Be2 Nc6 9. O-O a6 {This is a typical IQP position. In fact, his position has been played numerous times with reversed colours. Black is doing fine.} *

