1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bf4 {This has been recently tried by none other than the world number one Magnus Carlsen. The idea of developing the Bishop to f4 is to combine it with ideas like Nb5 creating threats on the Queenside.} cxd4 {We carry on with our plan.} 6. Nxd4 Nbd7 {This slightly unusual move is an important one to remember in this variation. Black threatens to win a Piece with ... e5 .} ({For example, cxd5? loses to} 6... e5 {winning a Piece.}) 7. Nf3 {This dubious move was once played by GM Carlsen against GM Aronian. The idea is straightforward. White prevents ... e5 and prepares to develop his Kingside next with a move like e3 .} Bb4 {Blacks enjoys a lead in development. Also, we intend to create pressure on the pinned Knight on c3 with moves like ... Ne4 and ... Qa5 .} (7... dxc4 {was GM Aronian's choice in the game against GM Carlsen.}) 8. Qb3 {Played in the only game that reached this position.} Qa5 {It makes sense to increase the pressure on the c3 -Knight. Now, both ... d4 and ... Nc5 are huge threats.} (8... Bxc3+ {was played in Harsha, B (2593)-Dragnev, V (2556) Almaty KAZ 2022, 0-1 in 44 moves.}) 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 (10. Qxc3 $6 Qxc3+ 11. bxc3 dxc4 {gives us a clearly better position since it is not easy for White to regain the lost Pawn on c4 .}) 10... dxc4 11. Qxc4 O-O {Black has a huge lead in development. Another important aspect is White's weak pawn structure on the Queenside. These two factors guarantee Black a strong advantage.} *

