1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bf4 {This has been recently tried by none other than the world number one Magnus Carlsen. The idea of developing the Bishop to f4 is to combine it with ideas like Nb5 creating threats on the Queenside.} cxd4 {We carry on with our plan.} 6. Nxd4 Nbd7 {This slightly unusual move is an important one to remember in this variation. Black threatens to win a Piece with ... e5 .} ({For example, cxd5? loses to} 6... e5 {winning a Piece.}) 7. Nf3 {This dubious move was once played by GM Carlsen against GM Aronian. The idea is straightforward. White prevents ... e5 and prepares to develop his Kingside next with a move like e3 .} Bb4 {Blacks enjoys a lead in development. Also, we intend to create pressure on the pinned Knight on c3 with moves like ... Ne4 and ... Qa5 .} (7... dxc4 {was GM Aronian's choice in the game against GM Carlsen.}) 8. e3 {This is a novelty for White. They should ignore the pressure on the c3 -Knight and focus on completing the Kingside development.} Ne4 9. Rc1 Qa5 {Threatening both the c3 -Knight and the a2 -Pawn.} 10. Qc2 Qxa2 11. cxd5 exd5 (11... Qxd5 {may give White some compensation after} 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Nxc3 14. bxc3 Be7 15. Rfd1 {Black still needs a few moves to develop the Queenside.}) 12. Nd4 O-O 13. Be2 a6 {Covering the important b5 -square. White may have a little bit of compensation since it is not easy for Black to use our extra Pawn as of yet. But a Pawn is a Pawn and Black can slowly consolidate the extra Pawn.} *

