1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bf4 {This has been recently tried by none other than the world number one Magnus Carlsen. The idea of developing the Bishop to f4 is to combine it with ideas like Nb5 creating threats on the Queenside.} cxd4 {We carry on with our plan.} 6. Nxd4 Nbd7 {This slightly unusual move is an important one to remember in this variation. Black threatens to win a Piece with ... e5 .} ({For example, cxd5? loses to} 6... e5 {winning a Piece.}) 7. Nf3 {This dubious move was once played by GM Carlsen against GM Aronian. The idea is straightforward. White prevents ... e5 and prepares to develop his Kingside next with a move like e3 .} Bb4 {Blacks enjoys a lead in development. Also, we intend to create pressure on the pinned Knight on c3 with moves like ... Ne4 and ... Qa5 .} (7... dxc4 {was GM Aronian's choice in the game against GM Carlsen.}) 8. e3 {This is a novelty for White. They should ignore the pressure on the c3 -Knight and focus on completing the Kingside development.} O-O {This is a simpler alternative, focusing on completing the development.} 9. Be2 Nb6 10. Qb3 Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 Nxc4 12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. Qxc4 Qa5+ {Our Queen comes out with a tempo.} 14. b4 Qd5 {And in this equalish endgame, it is only Black who can play for an advantage.} *

