1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bf4 {This has been recently tried by none other than the world number one Magnus Carlsen. The idea of developing the Bishop to f4 is to combine it with ideas like Nb5 creating threats on the Queenside.} cxd4 {We carry on with our plan.} 6. Nxd4 Nbd7 {This slightly unusual move is an important one to remember in this variation. Black threatens to win a Piece with ... e5 .} ({For example, cxd5? loses to} 6... e5 {winning a Piece.}) 7. Qa4 {The critical try for White. They prevent us from playing ... e5 while also vacating the d1 -square for their Rook.} Bc5 {Developing the Bishop with a tempo while also preparing ... O-O .} 8. cxd5 O-O {Suddenly, White is faced with dual threats of ... e5 and .... Nb6 .} 9. Nb3 {Moving the vulnerable Knight out of the way.} (9. dxe6 $4 {loses a piece to} Nb6) 9... Nxd5 {It is preferable to exchange our f6 -Knight for White's c3 -Knight as it gives our Queen freedom to move to squares like f6 and h4 .} 10. Nxd5 exd5 {Black has got an Isolated Queen Pawn, but White is still far behind in development.} 11. e3 Re8 {Black's lead in development forces White to look for ways to maintain the balance in this position. We have ideas like ... Re4 and ... d4 .} *

