1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other options in this chapter. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Qxd4 {Inviting us to hit their Queen.} Nc6 7. Bxf6 {This is White's point. They want to weaken our Pawn structure. But as we will see, it is not such a big deal.} gxf6 (7... Nxd4 $2 {would be a mistake.} 8. Bxd8 Nc2+ 9. Kd2 Nxa1 10. Bh4 {and our Knight gets trapped in the corner. Lucena Cifre, R (1676) -Safont Balaguer, E ICCF email 2016 was 1-0 in 13 moves. Or Nxf3+ gxf3 Kxd8 cxd5± and Black does not have sufficient compensation for the Pawn.}) 8. Qh4 {White intends to castle long, creating pressure on the d5 -pawn. So, it makes sense to exchange Pawns on c4 quickly.} dxc4 {By opening up the d -file we prevent White from O-O-O . Next, our idea in general is to play ... f5 followed by ... Bg7 and then ... O-O .} 9. e3 {This is comfortably met.} f5 {Offering the exchange of Queens.} 10. Qxc4 Bg7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Qb6 {And Black was slightly better in this position due to the Bishop pair. Mareco,S (2581)-Peralta,F (2593) Buenos Aires 2012 ended in 0-1 in 54 moves.} *

