1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other options in this chapter. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Nxd4 e5 {This is the most challenging continuation that gives Black opportunities to seize the initiative. In most cases we would like to continue with ... d4 next, gaining more space in the centre.} 7. Ndb5 {Tried long back by GM Reshevsky! The Knight seems actively placed on b5 , but it can be easily kicked away:} a6 8. Nxd5 {Opting for tactical solutions backfires badly:} axb5 9. Nxf6+ {And now comes an unexpected reply.} Qxf6 ({This wins for Black.} 9... gxf6 $2 {is bad due to} 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bxf6+ {when White wins material.}) 10. Bxf6 Bb4+ 11. Qd2 Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2 gxf6 {Black is a clear Piece up, and White resigned on the next move.} 13. cxb5 Be6 {Fine, R-Yudovich, M Moscow 1937 ended here with 0-1.} *

