1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other options in this chapter. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Nxd4 e5 {This is the most challenging continuation that gives Black opportunities to seize the initiative. In most cases we would like to continue with ... d4 next, gaining more space in the centre.} 7. Ndb5 {Tried long back by GM Reshevsky! The Knight seems actively placed on b5 , but it can be easily kicked away:} a6 8. Na3 {Retreating the Knight is easy for Black to face. We can go ahead:} d4 {Seizing space in the centre.} 9. Nd5 Be6 {Immediately attacking the d5 -Knight so that we get the opportunity to exchange on d5 and land an annoying check on b4 .} ({Instead,} 9... Nxd5 10. Bxd8 Bb4+ 11. Qd2 Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2 {gave Black only a slight initiative in Suermann, U (1200)-Grott, P (1800) DESC email 2000, 0-1 in 27 moves.}) 10. e4 Bxd5 11. exd5 (11. cxd5 Bb4+ {forces White to play} 12. Ke2 {. With his King on e2 , White's condition is critical. He cannot block the check with} Bd2 {as he loses the e4 -Pawn.}) 11... Be7 {Threatening to win the d5 -Pawn with ... Nxd5 .} 12. Bd2 O-O {And Black has a winning advantage. White's Pieces are uncoordinated, and their Kingside is undeveloped. Black's central Pawns are a strong force to reckon with. In fact, we would like to play ... e4 next, setting our pawns in motion.} *

