[PlyCount "30"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other options in this chapter. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Nxd4 e5 {This is the most challenging continuation that gives Black opportunities to seize the initiative. In most cases we would like to continue with ... d4 next, gaining more space in the centre.} 7. Nb3 d4 {Once again, we continue with the plan of marching ahead in the centre.} 8. Nd5 Nbd7 {Ensuring that our Kingside Pawn structure remains intact if White exchanges on f6 . We would like to play ... h6 next, forcing White to make a decision.} (8... Be7 {is another alternative. You can check out the game between Ortega vs. Tal in the model games chapter.}) 9. e3 {A typical break in the centre. We nevertheless stick to our plan.} h6 10. Bxf6 Nxf6 {Now White's d5 -Knight is under pressure.} 11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {... Bb4 + is on the way, which would be annoying for White's King.} 12. c5 {White prevents it and prepares his own Bb5 +.} Bd7 {We prevent White's idea while developing our Bishop at the same time.} 13. exd4 exd4 14. Bd3 (14. Qxd4 $2 {gives Black a clearly better endgame after} Qxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxc5 {. Our Bishop pair is going to be troublesome for White.}) 14... Be7 15. O-O O-O {Only Black can be slightly better in this position. We have the Bishop pair and an advanced Pawn on d4 . If White captures our d4 -Pawn, then he loses his Pawn on c5 in return, and we can slowly press using our double Bishop advantage in the endgame. Our next moves can be ... Bc6 and then bringing our Rooks on optimal squares. Schinke,A (2473)-Walter,G (2388) ICCF email 2012 was a draw in 18 moves.} *

