1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other options in this chapter. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Nxd4 e5 {This is the most challenging continuation that gives Black opportunities to seize the initiative. In most cases we would like to continue with ... d4 next, gaining more space in the centre.} 7. Nb3 d4 {Once again, we continue with the plan of marching ahead in the centre.} 8. Bxf6 {White eliminates our Knight before making a decision for his own c3 -Knight. Now, there is no reason for us not to recapture on f6 with our Queen. This would maintain a healthy Pawn structure on the Kingside.} Qxf6 (8... gxf6 {is, of course, a good alternative as our weak Pawn structure is compensated by central control and Bishop pair.}) 9. Nd5 {Now, a Queen retreat back to the original square is the simplest.} Qd8 (9... Qd6 {was played in Schumacher, J-Holt, E Schilde 1969, 0-1 in 32 moves.}) 10. g3 {Preparing to play Bg2 next.} Bd6 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O {Both sides have castled Kingside, and it is time to develop the Queenside Pieces.} Nc6 13. e3 {White has to break in the centre sooner or later; otherwise, they remain passive.} dxe3 14. Nxe3 Be6 {We have managed to develop all our minor Pieces on optimal squares. The next step would be to connect the Rooks and bring them into the game. The position is balanced with chances for both sides. We have the Bishop pair, but White's control of the d5 -square gives them equal chances.} *

