1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other options in this chapter. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Nxd4 e5 {This is the most challenging continuation that gives Black opportunities to seize the initiative. In most cases we would like to continue with ... d4 next, gaining more space in the centre.} 7. Nf3 {This is the most played move in this position.} d4 {Now, Bxf6 can be met by gxf6 and we transpose here.} 8. Nd5 {White pressurises the f6 -Knight while also threatening to take the e5 -Pawn next.} Be7 9. Bxf6 (9. Nxe5 $4 {is obviously a blunder due to} Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 {and we are a clear Piece up.}) 9... Bxf6 10. Nd2 {This covers the e4 -square but is way too passive.} Be6 (10... Nc6 {was played in Czebe, A (2479) -Natsidis, C (2318) Budapest 2010, which ended in 1-0 in 41 moves.}) 11. e4 dxe3 12. Nxe3 Nc6 {With a clearly better position for Black. We have active Pieces. White is behind in development, and the d4 -square is a huge weakness in their camp.} *

