1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other options in this chapter. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Nxd4 e5 {This is the most challenging continuation that gives Black opportunities to seize the initiative. In most cases we would like to continue with ... d4 next, gaining more space in the centre.} 7. Nf3 {This is the most played move in this position.} d4 {Now, Bxf6 can be met by gxf6 and we transpose here.} 8. Nd5 {White pressurises the f6 -Knight while also threatening to take the e5 -Pawn next.} Be7 9. Bxf6 (9. Nxe5 $4 {is obviously a blunder due to} Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 {and we are a clear Piece up.}) 9... Bxf6 10. g3 {White prepares to fianchetto his Bishop.} Be6 {Immediately putting pressure on the d5 -Knight.} 11. Qb3 {White defends the d5 -Knight and threatens the b7 -Pawn. But the threat to the b7 -Pawn can be neglected with a simple reply.} O-O {If White does not take the Pawn now, then we can continue developing our Pieces with moves like ... Nd7 -... Nc5 . So, it makes sense for White to grab the Pawn.} (11... Bxd5 {was played in Georgiev, K (2595)-Gurevich, D (2475) Saint John 1988, which ended in 1-0 in 42 moves.}) 12. Qxb7 Qa5+ 13. Nd2 Na6 {Threatening ... Rb8 .} 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Qb5 Qxb5 16. cxb5 Nb4 {Threatening both ... Nc2 and ... Bxa2 with a clearly better position for Black.} *

