1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other options in this chapter. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Nxd4 e5 {This is the most challenging continuation that gives Black opportunities to seize the initiative. In most cases we would like to continue with ... d4 next, gaining more space in the centre.} 7. Bxf6 gxf6 {White has managed to ruin our Kingside Pawn structure, but at the same time we gain double Bishops and a nice Pawn constellation in the centre. Now White has three equally fine Knight retreats as options. No matter which option they choose, we are going forward with our d -Pawn, gaining more space in the centre.} 8. Nf3 d4 {We gain space in the centre and create a nice Pawn chain with f6 - e5 - d4 .} 9. Nd5 {White should, of course, try to post this Knight on this central square. Otherwise, his position becomes too passive.} Be6 {Quickly creating pressure on the d5 -Knight.} 10. e4 {A typical move that helps White maintain their Knight on d5 .} dxe3 11. Nxe3 {This keeps White's Kingside Pawn structure intact but hands over the d4 -square to Black.} Nc6 {Followed by ... f5 . Black is at least clearly better in this position. We have the Bishop pair in an open position plus a dominating control in the centre. White's d4 -square is quite weak.} (11... Bb4+ {was played in Feras, A (1772)-Antonsen, M (2440) Gothenburg 2017, won by Black in 26 moves.}) *

