1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other options in this chapter. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Nxd4 e5 {This is the most challenging continuation that gives Black opportunities to seize the initiative. In most cases we would like to continue with ... d4 next, gaining more space in the centre.} 7. Bxf6 gxf6 {White has managed to ruin our Kingside Pawn structure, but at the same time we gain double Bishops and a nice Pawn constellation in the centre. Now White has three equally fine Knight retreats as options. No matter which option they choose, we are going forward with our d -Pawn, gaining more space in the centre.} 8. Nc2 {White's Knight, in general, does seem well placed on c2 . The only advantage of placing the Knight on c2 is that after breaking in the centre with e2 - e3 or e2 - e4 , when Black captures on e3 , then the c2 -Knight can recapture.} d4 9. Nd5 {White is counting on his centralised d5 -Knight.} ({Other Knight moves like} 9. Ne4 $2 {are out of question because after the simple} f5 10. Ng3 Nc6 {, Black's advanced Pawns on f5 , e5 and d4 take control and dominate the position. White is far behind in development.}) 9... Be6 {A typical developing move quickly putting pressure on the d5 -Knight.} 10. e4 Nd7 {With the d4 -square unavailable for our Knight, the d7 -square is our natural choice. Our Knight can further travel to c5 . From c5 , it can influence both the e4 -Pawn and the d3 -square. Another plan for us is to simply play ... Bg7 and ... O-O .} (10... dxe3 {is possible but allows White's Knights to cooperate well after} 11. Ncxe3 {.}) 11. Bd3 Nc5 ({Our Knight is well placed on c5 . Instead,} 11... h5 $6 {was played in Harutyunian, T (2528)-Adly, A (2626) Sitges 2018, won by White in 40 moves.}) 12. O-O Bg7 {Preparing ... O-O .} 13. f4 {White needs to initiate some action on the Kingside; otherwise, his position is passive.} O-O 14. f5 Bxd5 15. cxd5 Qb6 16. Rb1 Rac8 {We have reached an unusual position. There is a presence of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board. The Pawn structure is imbalanced with both sides having a protected passed d -Pawn. But if you pay close attention, then we can establish that Black is clearly better! First of all, Black's Bishop has a bright future on the c1 - h6 diagonal after ... Bh6 . Moreover, our doubled Pawns on f -file can turn out to be good for us as we can use the open g -file by playing ... Kh8 and ... Rg8 . Also, our Knight is active compared to White's passive Knight on c2 . All these factors make Black's position preferable to play.} *

