1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {This is a rare move, but the most played one compared to the other options in this chapter. White develops his Bishop while creating an indirect pressure in the centre. Next, they simply want to play e3 when the Bishop won't be stuck on c1 . I have faced this move myself as Black against GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} cxd4 {We continue with our plan on exchanging Pawns on d4 .} 6. Nxd4 e5 {This is the most challenging continuation that gives Black opportunities to seize the initiative. In most cases we would like to continue with ... d4 next, gaining more space in the centre.} 7. Bxf6 gxf6 {White has managed to ruin our Kingside Pawn structure, but at the same time we gain double Bishops and a nice Pawn constellation in the centre. Now White has three equally fine Knight retreats as options. No matter which option they choose, we are going forward with our d -Pawn, gaining more space in the centre.} 8. Nb3 {Compared to f3 and c2 , White's Knight is best placed on b3 . Especially if Black goes for the typical Pawn advance with ... d4 .} dxc4 {We can utilize White's Knight placement on b3 and grab the c4 -pawn with a tempo. White will have to waste a few moves to win the c4 -Pawn back.} 9. Qxd8+ {This is the most logical. White would like to gain the initiative by exchanging Queens and disturbing Black's King.} Kxd8 10. O-O-O+ {It seems White has got some initiative for the Pawn. But in fact, his Kingside is undeveloped, and without it, they cannot do much. If they push too hard, then they risk falling into a worse position, as you will see in some variations.} Ke8 11. Nd5 {Going for the a8 -Rook is a mistake.} cxb3 12. Nc7+ Ke7 13. Nxa8 bxa2 {And Black's a2 -Pawn is super dangerous. Just one step away from the Queening square! Our Bishops are also ready to join the party with ... Bf5 and ... Bh6 .} *

