1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. b3 {White has two aims with this move. Firstly, supporting the c4 -Pawn, thus preparing to recapture on c4 with his Pawn rather than the Bishop. Secondly, he wants to fianchetto his Bishop to b2 . It is tough to imagine that this natural move could be an inaccuracy. However, chess is a concrete game, and in this exact position, we have the opportunity to snatch the initiative.} cxd4 {Opening up the dark-squared Bishop so that it can go to b4 and exploit the newly weakened e1 - a5 diagonal.} 7. exd4 Ne4 ({It is precise to start with this move. Otherwise, if we play} 7... Bb4 {first, then after} 8. Bd2 {, we won’t be able to play} Ne4 {since White can simply capture our Knight, which would expose our Bishop on b4 .}) 8. Nxe4 {This is bad.} dxe4 9. Ne5 f6 {This is precisely how to punish White's lack of development.} (9... Bb4+ $2 {is much more tempting since it allows us to win a Pawn. But after} 10. Bd2 $1 Qxd4 11. Bxb4 Qxe5 12. Qc1 {intending Bc3 next, White gets a little bit of compensation for the Pawn.}) 10. Ng4 e5 {The key point behind Black's previous move. Suddenly, White's position starts to shake as the d4 -Pawn and the Knight on g4 come under pressure. Black also threatens ... Bb4 +.} *

