1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. b3 {White has two aims with this move. Firstly, supporting the c4 -Pawn, thus preparing to recapture on c4 with his Pawn rather than the Bishop. Secondly, he wants to fianchetto his Bishop to b2 . It is tough to imagine that this natural move could be an inaccuracy. However, chess is a concrete game, and in this exact position, we have the opportunity to snatch the initiative.} cxd4 {Opening up the dark-squared Bishop so that it can go to b4 and exploit the newly weakened e1 - a5 diagonal.} 7. exd4 Ne4 ({It is precise to start with this move. Otherwise, if we play} 7... Bb4 {first, then after} 8. Bd2 {, we won’t be able to play} Ne4 {since White can simply capture our Knight, which would expose our Bishop on b4 .}) 8. Bb2 {An ideal way to cover the c3 -Knight, but it allows Black to win a Pawn.} Bb4 9. Rc1 Qa5 {Once again adding pressure on the Knight.} 10. Qc2 {This protects the c3 -Knight but loses the a2 -Pawn for no compensation.} Qxa2 11. Bd3 Bxc3+ {Forcing an exchange of Queens.} 12. Bxc3 Qxc2 13. Rxc2 Nxc3 14. Rxc3 Nc6 {Black's extra Pawn gives us a clearly better endgame.} *

