1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. b3 {White has two aims with this move. Firstly, supporting the c4 -Pawn, thus preparing to recapture on c4 with his Pawn rather than the Bishop. Secondly, he wants to fianchetto his Bishop to b2 . It is tough to imagine that this natural move could be an inaccuracy. However, chess is a concrete game, and in this exact position, we have the opportunity to snatch the initiative.} cxd4 {Opening up the dark-squared Bishop so that it can go to b4 and exploit the newly weakened e1 - a5 diagonal.} 7. exd4 Ne4 ({It is precise to start with this move. Otherwise, if we play} 7... Bb4 {first, then after} 8. Bd2 {, we won’t be able to play} Ne4 {since White can simply capture our Knight, which would expose our Bishop on b4 .}) 8. Bd2 {Defending the Knight on c3 this way is a sad necessity for White.} Nc6 {Developing the Knight as well as preparing to play ... Bb4 since now, the Bishop will be supported.} (8... Nxd2 {was played in Parenti, D (2037)-Voiska, M (2332) Porto San Giorgio ITA 2009, won by Black in 25 moves.}) 9. Be2 Bb4 10. Rc1 Qa5 {We turn up the pressure with every move.} 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 13. Nd2 Nxd4 {This wins a Pawn, but White gets sufficient initiative to regain it back.} 14. O-O Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2 f5 16. Qh5+ g6 17. Qh6 {Black's King is stuck in the centre, which is a huge burden.} Qf8 18. Qe3 Bd7 19. f3 Bc6 20. fxe4 O-O-O {The position is more or less balanced.} *

