1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. a3 {Now White intends to go b2 - b4 . There are various ways we can deal with it, but since you will rarely face this move, I would suggest a simple response to his idea.} dxc4 {Offering the exchange of Queens.} 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bxc4 {Black's King may seem misplaced on d8 but, with the Queens off the board, it is not a big problem. We can safely park our King on e7 . The position may look identical at first sight. However, on closer inspection, we can see that Black has not yet developed the Queenside Knight, while White has. This is in our favour since we can develop it to a more favourable square on d7 . From d7 , the Knight has a much better scope since White will sooner or later play b2 - b4 , which will weaken a few squares on the Queenside like the c4 -square. We can then transfer our Knight to b6 and try to occupy such weak squares.} b5 10. Bd3 Bb7 {Black's next plan is to develop the Knight on d7 , followed by ... Ke7 , and then bring the Rooks into the game with ... Rhd8 and ... Rac8 . White has tried a few moves here.} 11. Ng5 {White threatens the f7 -Pawn, but the main idea is to rotate the Knight back to e4 .} Ke7 {The most logical way of defending the f7 -Pawn. Now White's g2 -Pawn is under attack.} 12. Nge4 Bb6 13. Nxf6 gxf6 {Black intends to play ... f5 next taking control over the e4 -square.} 14. Be4 Bxe4 15. Nxe4 f5 16. Nc3 Nd7 {This endgame is very equalish, but Black has a slight pull since White's light squares on the Queenside are weak, and our Knight can jump on them with ... Ne5 - c4 or ... Nc5 - b3 .} *

