1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. a3 {White copies our idea.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 {This is an inferior retreat compared to Ba2 . The problem is that whenever White plays e4 in order to activate the dark-squared Bishop then, it simply shuts the Bishop on d3 .} Nbd7 {It is important to first develop our Knight to d7 as it discourages White from capturing on c5 since now, we can reply with ... Nxc5 .} 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bc2 Rc8 {The rook is useful along the c -file.} 11. Qe2 Bd6 {We are all set to castle next with a completely fine position. White still needs to solve the problem of their c1 -Bishop. Bharath,S (2517)-Le,Q (2728) chess.com INT 2023 was won by Black in 51 moves. You'll find this game in the model games chapter.} *

