1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. a3 {White copies our idea.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Ba2 {White's 6.a3 comes to use. The bishop is safe on a2 and exerts some pressure along the a2 - g8 diagonal.} Bb7 {Our Bishop is well placed on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} 9. O-O Nbd7 {We have finished developing our Queenside, and now we can focus on developing our Kingside Pieces. Another benefit of bringing out our Knight to d7 before the f8 -bishop is that when our Bishop moves, and White captures on c5 , we can recapture with our Knight instead of moving the Bishop again.} 10. d5 {This feels like a good central break, but White's Pieces are not active enough to support the opening of lines.} exd5 11. Nxd5 Bd6 {Preparing to castle next.} 12. e4 O-O 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {When Black is slightly better due to our active Pieces and space advantage on the Queenside.} *

