1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. a3 {White copies our idea.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Ba2 {White's 6.a3 comes to use. The bishop is safe on a2 and exerts some pressure along the a2 - g8 diagonal.} Bb7 {Our Bishop is well placed on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} 9. O-O Nbd7 {We have finished developing our Queenside, and now we can focus on developing our Kingside Pieces. Another benefit of bringing out our Knight to d7 before the f8 -bishop is that when our Bishop moves, and White captures on c5 , we can recapture with our Knight instead of moving the Bishop again.} 10. e4 {An important Pawn advance that gains some territory in the centre and also opens up the c1 -Bishop.} cxd4 (10... Nxe4 $6 {is possible but risky as after} 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Ng5 Bb7 13. d5 {, White gets a nice initiative, as our King is still stuck in the centre.}) 11. Nxd4 Bc5 12. Be3 O-O {Now White can force an equal endgame.} 13. f3 {It seems logical to play this, supporting the e4 -Pawn. It also restricts Black's Bishop on b7 . However, Black's Pieces are ideally placed and can exert further pressure.} Ne5 {The Knight is well placed in the centre, and it is not easy for White to kick it. On top of that, there is also a nice pressure along the g1 - a7 diagonal.} 14. Bf2 {Placing the Bishop on a safer square.} Nh5 {This is a more active move compared to ... Qd6 , which was played in the only game that reached this position. The idea is simply to go to f4 , adding further pressure.} (14... Qd6 {was played in Hoi, C (2425)-Petursson, M (2445) Reykjavik 1981, won by White in 54 moves.}) 15. Nce2 {White prevents ... Nf4 , but this is clearly a passive move.} Qf6 {We activate our Queen as well. Next, our Rooks are ready to come into play on the d and c -files.} *

