1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. a3 {White copies our idea.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Ba2 {White's 6.a3 comes to use. The bishop is safe on a2 and exerts some pressure along the a2 - g8 diagonal.} Bb7 {Our Bishop is well placed on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} 9. O-O Nbd7 {We have finished developing our Queenside, and now we can focus on developing our Kingside Pieces. Another benefit of bringing out our Knight to d7 before the f8 -bishop is that when our Bishop moves, and White captures on c5 , we can recapture with our Knight instead of moving the Bishop again.} 10. e4 {An important Pawn advance that gains some territory in the centre and also opens up the c1 -Bishop.} cxd4 (10... Nxe4 $6 {is possible but risky as after} 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Ng5 Bb7 13. d5 {, White gets a nice initiative, as our King is still stuck in the centre.}) 11. Nxd4 Bc5 12. Be3 O-O {Now White can force an equal endgame.} 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. e5 {A tough idea to spot.} Bxe3 15. exf6 {This is the point of White's combination. White has dual threats of fxe3 and Bxe6 +.} Bxf2+ 16. Rxf2 Rxf6 17. Rxf6 Nxf6 18. Bxe6+ {The dust has settled, and we have a completely equal endgame on the board.} Kf8 {Keeping our King closer to the centre (the King is an important Piece in the endgame!), this endgame is likely to end in a draw.} *

