1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. cxd5 {White exchanges Pawns on d5 before we can do it on c4 .} exd5 7. g3 {This was recently tried by some top GMs in faster time controls. The idea is simple: to play Bg2 , O-O and then dxc5 , getting a pleasant position against an IQP. But Black can immediately put an end to White's dreams.} c4 {With this simple Pawn advance, Black gains extra space on the Queenside. Also, with White's Bishop fianchettoed on g2 , it will be tough for him to break on the Queenside successfully with b3 .} 8. Bg2 Bb4 {It is important to place our Bishop on b4 . The point is to exchange the Knight on c3 to gain access to the e4 -square for our Knight in many cases. This also makes it tough for White to break with b2 - b3 as now the c3 -Knight hangs. Next, Black simply wants to play ... O-O .} 9. Qa4+ {Trying to snatch the initiative by exploiting Black's 'loose' Bishop on b4 wastes valuable time for White.} Nc6 10. Ne5 {A logical follow-up to White's previous move. White exerts immediate pressure on the c6 -Knight.} O-O {Black calmly castles. We are all set to sacrifice a Pawn for the initiative.} 11. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 bxc6 {White is welcome to capture our c6 -Pawn. Our prime intention now is to place our Bishop on f5 , from where it will securely cover the b1 -square, thus restricting White's Rooks from coming to the b -file. Once that is done, Black would like to create attacking chances on the Kingside by advancing his h -Pawn with ... h5 -... h4 . The world number 1 GM Carlsen demonstrated this beautifully in his game against young talent GM Keymer Vincent.} 13. O-O Bf5 14. Ba3 Re8 15. Qxc6 Re6 {The Rook may swing in the attack if required.} 16. Qa4 h5 {And GM Carlsen converted his attacking chances on the Kingside into a full point. The rest of the game can be found in the model games section: Keymer,V (2693)-Carlsen,M (2861) chess24.com INT 2022 was 0-1 in 41 moves.} *

