1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. cxd5 {White exchanges Pawns on d5 before we can do it on c4 .} exd5 7. g3 {This was recently tried by some top GMs in faster time controls. The idea is simple: to play Bg2 , O-O and then dxc5 , getting a pleasant position against an IQP. But Black can immediately put an end to White's dreams.} c4 {With this simple Pawn advance, Black gains extra space on the Queenside. Also, with White's Bishop fianchettoed on g2 , it will be tough for him to break on the Queenside successfully with b3 .} 8. Bg2 Bb4 {It is important to place our Bishop on b4 . The point is to exchange the Knight on c3 to gain access to the e4 -square for our Knight in many cases. This also makes it tough for White to break with b2 - b3 as now the c3 -Knight hangs. Next, Black simply wants to play ... O-O .} 9. O-O O-O 10. Ne5 {White centralises their Knight, intending to play f2 - f4 at some point in time, gaining space on the kingside.} Nc6 11. f4 {This is generally the most logical follow-up to placing the Knight on the central e5 -square. By supporting the Knight with f4 , White prepares to recapture on e5 with fxe5 . However, it is a huge mistake in this exact position as it seriously weakens the e4 -square.} (11. Bd2 {transposes here.}) 11... Bxc3 {Eliminating the key defender of the e4 -square.} 12. bxc3 Bf5 {Our Bishop arrives at the scene with the sole intention of landing on e4 .} (12... Qc7 {led to a draw in 45 moves in Stefanova, A (2458)-Alinasab, M (2373) chess.com INT 2022.}) 13. g4 Be4 {Thanks to our dominating control on the e4 -square we stand clearly better.} *

