1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. cxd5 {White exchanges Pawns on d5 before we can do it on c4 .} exd5 7. g3 {This was recently tried by some top GMs in faster time controls. The idea is simple: to play Bg2 , O-O and then dxc5 , getting a pleasant position against an IQP. But Black can immediately put an end to White's dreams.} c4 {With this simple Pawn advance, Black gains extra space on the Queenside. Also, with White's Bishop fianchettoed on g2 , it will be tough for him to break on the Queenside successfully with b3 .} 8. Bg2 Bb4 {It is important to place our Bishop on b4 . The point is to exchange the Knight on c3 to gain access to the e4 -square for our Knight in many cases. This also makes it tough for White to break with b2 - b3 as now the c3 -Knight hangs. Next, Black simply wants to play ... O-O .} 9. Bd2 {White unpins the Knight immediately and gets an additional option of breaking with b2 - b3 before O-O .} O-O 10. b3 (10. O-O Nc6 11. Ne5 Re8 {transposes here.}) 10... Bf5 {Our Bishop belongs to the b1 - h7 diagonal. It is all set to go to the juicy d3 -square.} 11. bxc4 {White can try to go for the c4 -Pawn quickly:} dxc4 12. Ne5 {We should deal with it calmly.} Nbd7 {White lacks development and has some weaknesses in his position. Therefore, we focus on snatching the initiative instead of protecting the Pawn. Now, grabbing any of our Pawns is risky for White.} 13. Nxc4 {This is a huge mistake.} Rc8 {Both White's Knights come under fire along the c -file.} 14. Qb3 Bxc3 15. Bxc3 Be6 {White is about to lose heavy material soon.} *

