1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. cxd5 {White exchanges Pawns on d5 before we can do it on c4 .} exd5 7. g3 {This was recently tried by some top GMs in faster time controls. The idea is simple: to play Bg2 , O-O and then dxc5 , getting a pleasant position against an IQP. But Black can immediately put an end to White's dreams.} c4 {With this simple Pawn advance, Black gains extra space on the Queenside. Also, with White's Bishop fianchettoed on g2 , it will be tough for him to break on the Queenside successfully with b3 .} 8. Bg2 Bb4 {It is important to place our Bishop on b4 . The point is to exchange the Knight on c3 to gain access to the e4 -square for our Knight in many cases. This also makes it tough for White to break with b2 - b3 as now the c3 -Knight hangs. Next, Black simply wants to play ... O-O .} 9. Bd2 {White unpins the Knight immediately and gets an additional option of breaking with b2 - b3 before O-O .} O-O 10. b3 (10. O-O Nc6 11. Ne5 Re8 {transposes here.}) 10... Bf5 {Our Bishop belongs to the b1 - h7 diagonal. It is all set to go to the juicy d3 -square.} 11. bxc4 {White can try to go for the c4 -Pawn quickly:} dxc4 12. Ne5 {We should deal with it calmly.} Nbd7 {White lacks development and has some weaknesses in his position. Therefore, we focus on snatching the initiative instead of protecting the Pawn. Now, grabbing any of our Pawns is risky for White.} 13. Bxb7 {This is easily met.} Rb8 14. Bg2 {White simply retreats after snatching our b7 -Pawn as if nothing has happened. But they have lost valuable time, which we can exploit.} (14. Nc6 $2 {loses to} Qb6 {and Black picks up the bishop.}) 14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qd3 {A strong resource that creates immense problems for White.} 16. Bf1 {This allows us to show our point.} Qxc3 ({A nice temporary Queen sacrifice that tears White's position apart.} 16... Bxc3 {loses to} 17. Bxc3 Qd2+ 18. Bxd2 {and Black is a clear Piece up, or Ke2} Bg4 $1 {The precise way to finish the game. We block White's King's escape to f3 before playing ... Rb2 +.} 19. f3 Rb2 {and now White is forced to give the Queen back when we are completely winning.}) ({For example, if White continues with exf6 , then Black has the strong} 16... Rfd8 $1 {going after the Bishop on d2 .} 17. Rc1 {is met by} Qxd2+ 18. Qxd2 {Bxd2+-+ when we are leading in material. After} Bxc3 {Bxc3+} 19. Ke2 {, Black has} Bg4+ {, an important check that ensures White's King does not escape with Kf3 .} 20. f3 Rb2 {White is forced to give up the Queen but even that won't stop us from checkmating White's King in a just a few more moves.}) *

