1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. cxd5 {White exchanges Pawns on d5 before we can do it on c4 .} exd5 7. g3 {This was recently tried by some top GMs in faster time controls. The idea is simple: to play Bg2 , O-O and then dxc5 , getting a pleasant position against an IQP. But Black can immediately put an end to White's dreams.} c4 {With this simple Pawn advance, Black gains extra space on the Queenside. Also, with White's Bishop fianchettoed on g2 , it will be tough for him to break on the Queenside successfully with b3 .} 8. Bg2 Bb4 {It is important to place our Bishop on b4 . The point is to exchange the Knight on c3 to gain access to the e4 -square for our Knight in many cases. This also makes it tough for White to break with b2 - b3 as now the c3 -Knight hangs. Next, Black simply wants to play ... O-O .} 9. Bd2 {White unpins the Knight immediately and gets an additional option of breaking with b2 - b3 before O-O .} O-O 10. Ne5 {A typical move that centralises the Knight, also creating some pressure on the d5 -Pawn.} Nc6 {Challenging the e5 -Knight.} 11. O-O Re8 {Turning up the pressure. Now White needs to react to the threat to their e5 -Knight.} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. b3 {A typical Pawn break that is aimed to break Black's supremacy on the Queenside.} a5 {This helps us activate our Bishop along the f1 - a6 diagonal.} 14. bxc4 Ba6 {We are all set to recover our Pawn.} 15. Qc2 Bxc4 {We have a weak Pawn on c6 , but our active Bishop on c4 compensates for it. The world number 1 GM, Magnus Carlsen, won a nice game from this position, which you can check in the model games section: Artemiev,V (2704)-Carlsen,M (2847) chess24.com INT 2021, 0-1 in 35 moves.} *

