{It is important to note that Bxh5?? is impossible once again due to Rh4-+} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. cxd5 {White exchanges Pawns on d5 before we can do it on c4 .} exd5 7. Be2 {This is the most natural move in this position. White simply develops the Bishop and prepares O-O .} Nc6 8. O-O cxd4 {I prefer to exchange on d4 first before developing our Bishop to d6 . If we develop our Bishop directly to d6 , then White can disturb it by playing dxc5 .} (8... Bd6 {is the other alternative. Black invites White to exchange on c5 , which places our Bishop on the g1 - a7 diagonal. The game would continue with} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 {This is a completely playable position for both sides. A typical situation where one side plays with an Isolated Queen's Pawn while the other side plays against it. Generally, I prefer to keep my Bishop on the h2 - a7 diagonal. Only when White plays g3 do I transfer my bishop to the g1 - a7 diagonal.}) 9. exd4 Be7 {It is better to place our Bishop on e7 so that White won’t be able to pin our f6 -Knight with Bg5 . We prepare to play ... O-O next.} (9... Bd6 $6 {is met by the annoying} 10. Bg5 $1 {when Black will have to sooner or later retreat our Bishop to e7 due to the threat to the d5 -Pawn.}) 10. Ne5 {Playing normally won't yield anything for White. So, they try to play actively.} O-O 11. Bf4 {White continues to deploy their Pieces on active squares.} Bf5 {We complete the development of our minor Pieces and now prepare to bring our Rook in action with ... Rc8 .} 12. Nxc6 {A timely exchange disturbing our Queenside Pawn structure.} bxc6 13. Rc1 {White's long-term aim is to create immense pressure on the backward c6 -Pawn. But this isn't so easy as we can create sufficient counterplay along the e -file.} Bd6 {Exchanging the annoying f4 -Bishop gives more room for our Pieces.} 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Na4 a5 {A typical move that gains some more space for us on the Queenside.} 16. Nc5 Rfe8 {Now, we focus on creating play along the e -file.} 17. Re1 h5 {A nice move that gains us more space on the Kingside as well.} 18. Qd2 (18. Bxh5 $4 {is, of course, not possible, due to} Rxe1+ 19. Qxe1 Nxh5) 18... Ne4 {And here comes a timely knight exchange which helps us release the pressure on the Queenside.} 19. Nxe4 Rxe4 {The weakness of Black's c6 -Pawn is compensated by the play along the e -file. Ding Liren (2799)-Carlsen,M (2864) chess24.com INT 2022 ended in a draw in 56 moves.} *

