their Pieces on active squares.} Bf5 {We complete the development of our minor Pieces and now prepare to bring our Rook in action with ... Rc8 .} 12. Nxc6 {A timely exchange disturbing our Queenside Pawn structure.} bxc6 13. Rc1 {White's long-term aim is to create immense pressure on the backward c6 -Pawn. But this isn't so easy as we can create sufficient counterplay along the e -file.} Bd6 {Exchanging the annoying f4 -Bishop gives more room for our Pieces.} 14. Qd2 Re8 {Now our main focus is to create play along the e -file.} 15. Bf3 Be4 {This is a typical way for black to exchange pieces on the e4 -square.} ({Instead,} 15... Rb8 {was played in Fressinet, L (2637)-Iljiushenok, I (2547) Samarkand UZB 2023, 0-1 in 31 moves.}) 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Qc2 Re6 {Our backward Pawn on c6 is compensated by the active e4 -Knight and sufficient counterplay along the e -file.} *

