1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. e3 {This move clearly shows that White aims to avoid any theoretical discussions and focus on just getting a game.} a6 {This is a very useful move. We plan to exchange Pawns on c4 and follow it up with ... b5 . This would gain space for us on the Queenside and also allow us to fianchetto our Bishop to b7 . Other options for Black are:} (5... cxd4 6. exd4 {, and now both ... Be7 and ... Bb4 are possible. This position generally arises from the Panov-Botvinnik Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence.}) (5... Nc6 {is a more popular move compared to a6 , but these days, players playing with the black Pieces prefer to play the useful move a6 instead of committing the Knight to c6 .}) 6. cxd5 {White exchanges Pawns on d5 before we can do it on c4 .} exd5 7. Be2 {This is the most natural move in this position. White simply develops the Bishop and prepares O-O .} Nc6 8. O-O cxd4 {I prefer to exchange on d4 first before developing our Bishop to d6 . If we develop our Bishop directly to d6 , then White can disturb it by playing dxc5 .} (8... Bd6 {is the other alternative. Black invites White to exchange on c5 , which places our Bishop on the g1 - a7 diagonal. The game would continue with} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 {This is a completely playable position for both sides. A typical situation where one side plays with an Isolated Queen's Pawn while the other side plays against it. Generally, I prefer to keep my Bishop on the h2 - a7 diagonal. Only when White plays g3 do I transfer my bishop to the g1 - a7 diagonal.}) 9. Nxd4 {This is more logical than recapturing with the Pawn. White wants to play against the typical IQP.} Bd6 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 {This is a typical position where one side plays with an IQP and one against it. Black should try to keep the exchange of Pieces to the minimum and try to create attacking chances on the kingside. White aims to transpose the game to an endgame.} Re8 {The Rook is useful along the e -file. It can also be transferred to the Kingside if required in the attack.} 12. Rc1 {This allows Black to simply equalise.} Nxd4 13. exd4 {This does not make sense as Bishop on b2 gets blocked and the IQP has vanished.} Bf5 {A simple developing move like this maintains a clear advantage for Black.} *

