lso be transferred to the Kingside if required in the attack.} 12. Nxc6 {This avoids Black's equalising idea of ... Nxd4 followed by ... Be5 and then ... d4 , but it connects Black’s Pawns in the centre. However, White aims to create pressure on the c6 -Pawn next.} bxc6 13. Rc1 {It is clear White has a better Pawn structure as they have fewer Pawn islands (2 vs. 1). But we have more space thanks to our d5 -Pawn.} h5 {This is an important move. Black needs to start action on the Kingside immediately in order to create timely pressure on White's Kingside. By advancing our Pawn to h5 , we not only gain space but also gain access to the g4 -square, which we can use by playing ... Ng4 next.} 14. Na4 {White is focused on their Queenside strategy of creating pressure on our Pawn structure.} Ng4 {And we are focused on our own on the Kingside! The arrival of our Knight at g4 rings bells on White's Kingside.} 15. h3 {Feels like a natural move, expecting Black to retreat our Knight from the active g4 -square, but it is strongly met.} Nh2 {The courageous Knights enters White's camp. Only march forward!} 16. Re1 ({Seems like the most logical as it defends the exchange. But it wastes valuable time, which we can quickly exploit by creating more threats. After} 16. Rxc6 Nxf1 {, we have won an exchange, but of course, White has compensation for it. This is playable for both sides.}) 16... Qg5 17. Kh1 {And now comes the ferocious follow-up.} Rxe3 {Ripping apart White's Kingside.} 18. Qd2 Nf1 {Threatening ... Rxh3 winning the d2 -Queen.} *

