lso be transferred to the Kingside if required in the attack.} 12. Nxc6 {This avoids Black's equalising idea of ... Nxd4 followed by ... Be5 and then ... d4 , but it connects Black’s Pawns in the centre. However, White aims to create pressure on the c6 -Pawn next.} bxc6 13. Rc1 {It is clear White has a better Pawn structure as they have fewer Pawn islands (2 vs. 1). But we have more space thanks to our d5 -Pawn.} h5 {This is an important move. Black needs to start action on the Kingside immediately in order to create timely pressure on White's Kingside. By advancing our Pawn to h5 , we not only gain space but also gain access to the g4 -square, which we can use by playing ... Ng4 next.} 14. Na4 {White is focused on their Queenside strategy of creating pressure on our Pawn structure.} Ng4 {And we are focused on our own on the Kingside! The arrival of our Knight at g4 rings bells on White's Kingside.} 15. g3 {This gives Black an opportunity to force a draw.} Nxh2 16. Kxh2 Qh4+ 17. Kg1 Bxg3 18. fxg3 Qxg3+ 19. Kh1 Qh3+ (19... Re6 $5 {should be met by} 20. Bxh5 $1 {covering the g6 -square and also threatening the f7 -Pawn. Now we have nothing better than to repeat with} Qh3+ 21. Kg1 Qg3+) (19... Re4 {is another tempting attempt to checkmate White's King. But again, White holds his own with} 20. Rf4 $1 {and once again, we may have to repeat with} Qxe3 21. Rxe4 Qh3+ 22. Kg1 Qg3+ 23. Kh1 Qh3+) 20. Kg1 Qg3+ ({With a perpetual. It would be a grave error to include our Rook now with} 20... Re6 $2 {because White has} 21. Bf3 $1 {which not only covers the g2 -square but also vacates the e2 -square for their King to escape to.} Rg6+ 22. Kf2 {and with White's King escaping to a safe location, he can now be ambitious enough to win the game.}) *

