lso be transferred to the Kingside if required in the attack.} 12. Nxc6 {This avoids Black's equalising idea of ... Nxd4 followed by ... Be5 and then ... d4 , but it connects Black’s Pawns in the centre. However, White aims to create pressure on the c6 -Pawn next.} bxc6 13. Rc1 {It is clear White has a better Pawn structure as they have fewer Pawn islands (2 vs. 1). But we have more space thanks to our d5 -Pawn.} h5 {This is an important move. Black needs to start action on the Kingside immediately in order to create timely pressure on White's Kingside. By advancing our Pawn to h5 , we not only gain space but also gain access to the g4 -square, which we can use by playing ... Ng4 next.} 14. Na4 {White is focused on their Queenside strategy of creating pressure on our Pawn structure.} Ng4 {And we are focused on our own on the Kingside! The arrival of our Knight at g4 rings bells on White's Kingside.} 15. Bxg4 {White eliminates the dangerous Knight and aims to focus his energy on exploiting his superiority on the Queenside.} Bxg4 16. Qd2 {This is a grave error.} Bf3 {A surprising resource that blocks White's f -Pawn and creates havoc on White's Kingside. Our Queen is ready to join the attack with a decisive effect.} 17. g3 {weakens the light squares and loses to} Qd7 {With our Queen landing on h3 , it is game over for White.} *

