1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Nxd4 {This recapture avoids Qxd4 in favour of following the principle that we should not bring our Queen too early in the opening. But this is quite easy to meet as it allows Black to recapture on d5 comfortably with our Knight.} Nxd5 {This is clearly a preferable way for us to capture on d5 , as whenever we get a chance, we should avoid playing with an isolated Pawn after exd5 . Next, we plan to exchange Knights on c3 , which ruins White's Queenside Pawn structure.} 7. Bd2 {White prepares to recapture on c3 with Bxc3 , keeping his Pawn structure intact.} Bc5 {It might be tempting to develop the Bishop with a tempo, but there's a problem.} 8. Nb3 Bb6 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Bc3 {More or less forcing an exchange of Queens, White gets some pressure in the upcoming endgame. For example:} Qxd1+ (10... Qg5 $2 {is bad due to} 11. h4 {, and our Queen gets kicked once again.}) 11. Rxd1 f6 12. Na5 {And White has some pressure on the Queenside thanks to his lead in development and active Pieces. Brodsky,M (2550)-Shevtsov,N (2311) Kharkov 2008 ended in a draw in 20 moves.} *

