1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Nxd4 {This recapture avoids Qxd4 in favour of following the principle that we should not bring our Queen too early in the opening. But this is quite easy to meet as it allows Black to recapture on d5 comfortably with our Knight.} Nxd5 {This is clearly a preferable way for us to capture on d5 , as whenever we get a chance, we should avoid playing with an isolated Pawn after exd5 . Next, we plan to exchange Knights on c3 , which ruins White's Queenside Pawn structure.} 7. Bd2 {White prepares to recapture on c3 with Bxc3 , keeping his Pawn structure intact.} Be7 {We simply develop our dark-squared Bishop and prepare to play ... O-O .} 8. e3 {This is a restrained approach. White prefers to support the d4 -Knight beforehand and prepares to develop his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} O-O 9. Be2 e5 {A typical central advance that gains space for Black in the centre and allows us to play ... Nc6 on the next move without fearing the exchange on Knights on c6 .} 10. Nxd5 {This was once tried by GM Shimanov in one of his online games.} Qxd5 11. Bf3 e4 12. Be2 {It is clear that with a Pawn on e4 , Black has more room for his Pieces. Now, it is all about developing the Queenside Pieces.} Nc6 13. Bc3 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Bxd4 Bb4+ {Forcing White's King to an uncomfortable square.} 16. Kf1 Be6 {Black is doing fine in this completely equal endgame, though Shimanov,A (2597)-Ivanov,M (2195) chess.com INT 2021 was won by White in 39 moves.} *

