1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Nxd4 {This recapture avoids Qxd4 in favour of following the principle that we should not bring our Queen too early in the opening. But this is quite easy to meet as it allows Black to recapture on d5 comfortably with our Knight.} Nxd5 {This is clearly a preferable way for us to capture on d5 , as whenever we get a chance, we should avoid playing with an isolated Pawn after exd5 . Next, we plan to exchange Knights on c3 , which ruins White's Queenside Pawn structure.} 7. Bd2 {White prepares to recapture on c3 with Bxc3 , keeping his Pawn structure intact.} Be7 {We simply develop our dark-squared Bishop and prepare to play ... O-O .} 8. e3 {This is a restrained approach. White prefers to support the d4 -Knight beforehand and prepares to develop his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} O-O 9. Be2 e5 {A typical central advance that gains space for Black in the centre and allows us to play ... Nc6 on the next move without fearing the exchange on Knights on c6 .} 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. Nxd5 {It is better for White to exchange Knights on d5 immediately if he wants to have any hopes of snatching the initiative.} (11. O-O {is met by} Be6 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Bc3 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 f6 {, with a balanced position as in Granda Zuniga, J (2628)-Beliavsky, A (2619) Leon 2008, draw in 39 moves.}) 11... Qxd5 12. Bc3 Be6 ({It feels natural to support the Queen and develop the light-squared Bishop at the same time.} 12... Qxd1+ {was played in Lutz, C (2420)-Hausner, I (2440) Germany 1990, where White won in 54 moves.}) 13. Qxd5 Bxd5 {Black is doing fine in this position and would play ... f6 next, supporting the e5 -Pawn. White may decide to capture it immediately.} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Bxg2 16. Rg1 Bb4+ {A nice intermediate move disturbing White's King.} 17. Kd1 Rfd8+ 18. Bd4 Be4 19. Rxg7+ Kf8 {Black gets sufficient compensation for the lost Pawn. White's King on d1 is a huge problem for him. Also, White's d4 -Bishop is a target. The position is equal.} *

