1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Nxd4 {This recapture avoids Qxd4 in favour of following the principle that we should not bring our Queen too early in the opening. But this is quite easy to meet as it allows Black to recapture on d5 comfortably with our Knight.} Nxd5 {This is clearly a preferable way for us to capture on d5 , as whenever we get a chance, we should avoid playing with an isolated Pawn after exd5 . Next, we plan to exchange Knights on c3 , which ruins White's Queenside Pawn structure.} 7. Bd2 {White prepares to recapture on c3 with Bxc3 , keeping his Pawn structure intact.} Be7 {We simply develop our dark-squared Bishop and prepare to play ... O-O .} 8. e4 {By pushing the e -Pawn two squares, White gains more space in the centre and invites us to exchange Knights on c3 .} Nxc3 9. Bxc3 O-O 10. Be2 {White prepares O-O .} Qb6 {It is good for Black to place his Queen optimally on b6 before developing the Queenside Pieces. Our Queen eyes the b2 -Pawn and the d4 -Knight from the b6 -square. Also, it vacates the d8 -square for our Rook, which would further enhance the pressure on the d4 -Knight.} 11. Qb3 {It makes sense to exchange Black's annoying Queen on b6 .} Rd8 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. a3 Na6 {With the idea of playing ... Nc5 , Black was doing completely fine in this position. Our c8 -Bishop can be developed to d7 when all our Pieces are playing their part in the game. Black won in 59 moves in Duda,J (2743)-So,W (2770) chess.com INT 2020, a game included in the model games chapter.} *

