1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Qa4+ {This is just a stopover before capturing the d4 -Pawn. White provokes one of Black's Pieces to land on d7 , after which he would happily regain the Pawn on d4 . The idea behind this stopover is to cut the support of Black's Queen to the d5 -Pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {Now, White has two main approaches in this position. He can either play normally with moves like e3 or Bg5 against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn as if nothing has happened. Or he can capture the d5 -Pawn and muddy the waters.} 8. e3 {We'll see a similar line in the next chapter. The only difference is that Black's Bishop is already developed on d7 , which can only be in our favour.} Nc6 9. Qd3 {This is a typical Isolated Queen Pawn position, and there are a lot of ways for Black to continue. I will demonstrate an active way to play here for Black.} Bb4 {This Bishop usually lands on d6 , but as we can see from the upcoming variations, we can also place it more actively on b4 .} 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O {Both sides have castled on the Kingside, and now it is time for us to place another Bishop actively.} Bg4 {From g4 , the Bishop always aims to exchange on f3 .} 12. Rd1 {This allows us to demonstrate our idea.} Bxf3 13. gxf3 {a sad necessity. Now White's Kingside is a bit weak.} Bxc3 14. Qxc3 d4 {a powerful Pawn sacrifice opening up lines that can be used to create a lethal attack against White's King.} 15. exd4 Re8 {White's e2 -Bishop is under attack. Black also has ideas like ... Nd5 or ... Rc8 activating our Pieces. We have nice compensation for the Pawn that can be converted into a strong attack against White's King.} *

