1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Qa4+ {This is just a stopover before capturing the d4 -Pawn. White provokes one of Black's Pieces to land on d7 , after which he would happily regain the Pawn on d4 . The idea behind this stopover is to cut the support of Black's Queen to the d5 -Pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {Now, White has two main approaches in this position. He can either play normally with moves like e3 or Bg5 against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn as if nothing has happened. Or he can capture the d5 -Pawn and muddy the waters.} 8. e3 {We'll see a similar line in the next chapter. The only difference is that Black's Bishop is already developed on d7 , which can only be in our favour.} Nc6 9. Qd1 {Now, there are a lot of ways for Black to play in this typical IQP position. I would like to recommend a unique way where we can exchange White's c3 -Knight for our Bishop and play against White's weakened Queenside Pawn structure.} Bb4 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Bxc3 {This gives up the Bishop pair but weakens White's Queenside. An interesting imbalance.} 12. bxc3 {Now White is ready to push c3 - c4 . Therefore, we need to stop it.} Na5 (12... Be6 {was played in Van Scheltinga, T-Czerniak, M Buenos Aires 1939, where Black won in 39 moves.}) 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Bc5 Qc7 15. Bd4 Ne4 {The pressure on the c3 -Pawn continues. We can play ... Nc4 and ... Rac8 further with a good game. The position is equal.} *

