1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Qa4+ {This is just a stopover before capturing the d4 -Pawn. White provokes one of Black's Pieces to land on d7 , after which he would happily regain the Pawn on d4 . The idea behind this stopover is to cut the support of Black's Queen to the d5 -Pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {Now, White has two main approaches in this position. He can either play normally with moves like e3 or Bg5 against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn as if nothing has happened. Or he can capture the d5 -Pawn and muddy the waters.} 8. Bg5 {A logical developing move. White pins the f6 -Knight, creating pressure on the d5 -Pawn.} Nc6 {Black does not care about the f6 -Knight and prefers to attack White's Queen.} 9. Bxf6 {This leads to some forced exchanges.} Nxd4 10. Bxd8 Nxf3+ ({Of course, not} 10... Nc2+ $4 11. Kd2 Nxa1 12. Bh4 {when White soon wins our cornered a1 -Knight.}) 11. exf3 Rxd8 12. O-O-O Bc6 13. Bb5 {White is all set to bring his last piece in action with Rhe1 +. White is also threatening to win the d5 -Pawn as our c6 -Bishop is pinned.} Bc5 14. Nxd5 {This leads to a forced sequence for a few moves.} Bxb5 15. Nc7+ Ke7 16. Rhe1+ Kf6 17. Nxb5 {Now, Black should have simply captured the f2 -Pawn.} Bxf2 ({Material is equal, and so is this endgame. For example, Re4} 17... Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Rd8+ 19. Ke2 Bb6 {and a draw would be a logical result from this position.}) (17... a6 $2 {was a blunder as after} 18. Nc3 {, Black was not in a position to win the f2 -Pawn anymore due to Ne4 +. White won in 53 moves in Aravindh,C (2641)-Garifullina, L (2357) lichess.org INT 2020.}) *

