1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Qa4+ {This is just a stopover before capturing the d4 -Pawn. White provokes one of Black's Pieces to land on d7 , after which he would happily regain the Pawn on d4 . The idea behind this stopover is to cut the support of Black's Queen to the d5 -Pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {Now, White has two main approaches in this position. He can either play normally with moves like e3 or Bg5 against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn as if nothing has happened. Or he can capture the d5 -Pawn and muddy the waters.} 8. Bg5 {A logical developing move. White pins the f6 -Knight, creating pressure on the d5 -Pawn.} Nc6 {Black does not care about the f6 -Knight and prefers to attack White's Queen.} 9. Qd2 Be6 10. e3 h6 11. Bh4 {This looks like a normal reaction, but it falls short here.} g5 12. Bg3 Ne4 {An energetic response. All this is possible because White wasted some moves with his Queen in the opening with Qa4 - Qxd4 and then Qd2 .} 13. Nxe4 {This is bad.} dxe4 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Nd2 Bb4 16. O-O-O {It seems that White is now completely safe and can hope for a bright future. But we continue creating threats:} Bg4 {And White is going to lose some material soon.} *

