1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Qa4+ {This is just a stopover before capturing the d4 -Pawn. White provokes one of Black's Pieces to land on d7 , after which he would happily regain the Pawn on d4 . The idea behind this stopover is to cut the support of Black's Queen to the d5 -Pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {Now, White has two main approaches in this position. He can either play normally with moves like e3 or Bg5 against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn as if nothing has happened. Or he can capture the d5 -Pawn and muddy the waters.} 8. Bg5 {A logical developing move. White pins the f6 -Knight, creating pressure on the d5 -Pawn.} Nc6 {Black does not care about the f6 -Knight and prefers to attack White's Queen.} 9. Qd2 Be6 10. e3 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. a3 {Preventing ... Bb4 . This was the choice of Firouzja when he was just a mere GM.} Be7 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Rfd8 {Preparing the ... d4 break.} 15. Rfd1 {And now Black should have nevertheless gone for ... d4 .} d4 ({This solves all Black's problems.} 15... Na5 {was Firouzja, A (2572)-Hejazipour, M (2304) Sharjah 2018, 1-0 in 64 moves.}) 16. exd4 Bb3 {I guess this is the key idea that White missed. The d1 -Rook is forced to move away, and we win the d4 -Pawn next.} 17. Re1 Nxd4 {Black is slightly better here as we have the Bishop pair and active Pieces in an open position.} *

