1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Qa4+ {This is just a stopover before capturing the d4 -Pawn. White provokes one of Black's Pieces to land on d7 , after which he would happily regain the Pawn on d4 . The idea behind this stopover is to cut the support of Black's Queen to the d5 -Pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {Now, White has two main approaches in this position. He can either play normally with moves like e3 or Bg5 against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn as if nothing has happened. Or he can capture the d5 -Pawn and muddy the waters.} 8. Bg5 {A logical developing move. White pins the f6 -Knight, creating pressure on the d5 -Pawn.} Nc6 {Black does not care about the f6 -Knight and prefers to attack White's Queen.} 9. Qd2 Be6 10. e3 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Bb5 {A logical developing move pinning the c6 -Knight at the same time.} Bb4 ({We do the same.} 12... Bc5 $6 {was played in Vaarala, E (1964)-Porte, H (2115) Helsingor 2009, a draw in 64 moves.}) 13. Rc1 O-O 14. O-O Rfd8 {We are about to break with ... d4 , so White should eliminate the c6 -Knight.} 15. Bxc6 bxc6 {This position is balanced. White can hope to put some pressure on Black's c6 -Pawn, but we have the Bishop pair as compensation for it. Both sides have chances in this position.} *

