1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Qa4+ {This is just a stopover before capturing the d4 -Pawn. White provokes one of Black's Pieces to land on d7 , after which he would happily regain the Pawn on d4 . The idea behind this stopover is to cut the support of Black's Queen to the d5 -Pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {Now, White has two main approaches in this position. He can either play normally with moves like e3 or Bg5 against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn as if nothing has happened. Or he can capture the d5 -Pawn and muddy the waters.} 8. Nxd5 {This is clearly a critical line of this chapter. White grabs the d5 -Pawn, hoping that Black won't get sufficient compensation for it.} Qa5+ {This is an important move to remember. We send White's d5 -Knight back to c3 and activate our Queen at the same time.} ({The knee-jerk reaction} 8... Nxd5 $2 {would be a mistake because after} 9. Qxd5 Nc6 10. e3 {, analysis proves that Black does not have much to chew on in this position. White is clearly better. Jobava, B (2603)-Vidit, S (2726) chess24.com INT 2021 was 1-0 in 87 moves.}) 9. Nc3 Nc6 ({Developing our Knight with a tempo as well. This is what playing for compensation looks like: developing our Pieces with threats. For example, Qe3+?!} 9... Be7 {helps Black to prepare ... O-O while White's Queen on e3 comes in the way of their own Pieces.}) 10. Qd2 {Unpins the Knight on c3 for a move., but White's Queen is exposed on d2 :} Rd8 {We can start hitting it straight away.} 11. Qc2 {Moving the Queen away backfires:} Nb4 {Followed by .... Bf5 , and Black is more or less winning.} *

