1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Qa4+ {This is just a stopover before capturing the d4 -Pawn. White provokes one of Black's Pieces to land on d7 , after which he would happily regain the Pawn on d4 . The idea behind this stopover is to cut the support of Black's Queen to the d5 -Pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {Now, White has two main approaches in this position. He can either play normally with moves like e3 or Bg5 against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn as if nothing has happened. Or he can capture the d5 -Pawn and muddy the waters.} 8. Nxd5 {This is clearly a critical line of this chapter. White grabs the d5 -Pawn, hoping that Black won't get sufficient compensation for it.} Qa5+ {This is an important move to remember. We send White's d5 -Knight back to c3 and activate our Queen at the same time.} ({The knee-jerk reaction} 8... Nxd5 $2 {would be a mistake because after} 9. Qxd5 Nc6 10. e3 {, analysis proves that Black does not have much to chew on in this position. White is clearly better. Jobava, B (2603)-Vidit, S (2726) chess24.com INT 2021 was 1-0 in 87 moves.}) 9. Nc3 Nc6 ({Developing our Knight with a tempo as well. This is what playing for compensation looks like: developing our Pieces with threats. For example, Qe3+?!} 9... Be7 {helps Black to prepare ... O-O while White's Queen on e3 comes in the way of their own Pieces.}) 10. Qd2 {Unpins the Knight on c3 for a move., but White's Queen is exposed on d2 :} Rd8 {We can start hitting it straight away.} 11. e3 Bf5 {Immediately going after White's Queen. Now White needs to play a series of only moves in order to stay in the game.} 12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. exd4 Bb4 {Our Bishop belongs to b4 , where it creates an immense pressure on the c3 -Knight.} 14. Bd3 {It is essential for White to challenge our dominating light-squared Bishop. This also helps White prevent ... Ne4 .} ({Instead,} 14. Be2 $2 {is met by} Ne4 {going after the c3 -Knight immediately.} 15. Qe3 O-O {threatening ... Nxc3 next and Black enjoys a winning initiative.}) 14... O-O {We take our King into safety and threaten to take the d4 -Pawn next.} ({The immediate} 14... Rxd4 $2 {would be too greedy due to} 15. Qe3+ {and the Rook is lost.}) 15. Qc2 {A difficult move to find and a tough one to play with your King still in the centre.} Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Ne4 {A nice idea that not only recovers our sacrificed Pawn but also wins an additional one for us.} 17. O-O Nxc3 18. bxc3 Bxc3 19. Rb1 Bxd4 {Thanks to the threat of ... Bxf2 +, White cannot win the b7 -Pawn and we remain a Pawn up.} *

