1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Qa4+ {This is just a stopover before capturing the d4 -Pawn. White provokes one of Black's Pieces to land on d7 , after which he would happily regain the Pawn on d4 . The idea behind this stopover is to cut the support of Black's Queen to the d5 -Pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {Now, White has two main approaches in this position. He can either play normally with moves like e3 or Bg5 against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn as if nothing has happened. Or he can capture the d5 -Pawn and muddy the waters.} 8. Nxd5 {This is clearly a critical line of this chapter. White grabs the d5 -Pawn, hoping that Black won't get sufficient compensation for it.} Qa5+ {This is an important move to remember. We send White's d5 -Knight back to c3 and activate our Queen at the same time.} ({The knee-jerk reaction} 8... Nxd5 $2 {would be a mistake because after} 9. Qxd5 Nc6 10. e3 {, analysis proves that Black does not have much to chew on in this position. White is clearly better. Jobava, B (2603)-Vidit, S (2726) chess24.com INT 2021 was 1-0 in 87 moves.}) 9. Nc3 Nc6 ({Developing our Knight with a tempo as well. This is what playing for compensation looks like: developing our Pieces with threats. For example, Qe3+?!} 9... Be7 {helps Black to prepare ... O-O while White's Queen on e3 comes in the way of their own Pieces.}) 10. Qd1 {Retreating all the way back to d1 is surprisingly the best square for White's Queen. The idea is that it would be less exposed there than on other squares on the board. Now, White's sole aim would be to complete his development as soon as possible and take his King to safety.} Ne4 {Again an energetic move, creating problems for the c3 -Knight.} 11. Bd2 Nxd2 {It is obviously good for us to exchange White's dark-squared Bishop. Their Knight on c3 once again becomes shaky.} 12. Qxd2 Rd8 {This is also a possibility for Black. Apart from indirectly targeting White's Queen, the d7 -Bishop is supported, which will help us to play ... O-O in the near future.} 13. e3 Bf5 {Placing the Bishop actively on f5 before White gets to play Qc2 .} (13... g6 {was GM Ju Wenjun's choice, and Black got compensation there as well. But Bf5 is better. Nyzhnyk, I (2622)-Ju, W (2559) Chicago 2016 ended in a draw in 82 moves.}) 14. Nd4 Be7 {A simple developing move preparing ... O-O next.} 15. Bb5 {White decides to eliminate the c6 -Knight before the pressure on the d4 -Knight is too much to handle.} O-O 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Qc1 (17. O-O {is met by} c5 18. Nc6 Rxd2 19. Nxa5 Rxb2 {Black's Bishop pair and the active b2 -Rook gives them slightly better chances.}) 17... Bd3 {Planting the Bishop on d3 ensures that White's King remains stuck in the centre.} 18. Nxc6 Qg5 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {Black threatens to play ... Qg5 again. We have amazing compensation for the Pawn. White's King is stuck in the centre and is going to create huge problems for himself. His two extra pawns are of little value now.} *

