1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {The mainline for White is clearly Qxd4 , which is covered in chapter 4 and chapter 5. In this chapter, we are going to take a look at two alternatives to 6.Qxd4 .} 6. Qa4+ {This is just a stopover before capturing the d4 -Pawn. White provokes one of Black's Pieces to land on d7 , after which he would happily regain the Pawn on d4 . The idea behind this stopover is to cut the support of Black's Queen to the d5 -Pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {Now, White has two main approaches in this position. He can either play normally with moves like e3 or Bg5 against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn as if nothing has happened. Or he can capture the d5 -Pawn and muddy the waters.} 8. Nxd5 {This is clearly a critical line of this chapter. White grabs the d5 -Pawn, hoping that Black won't get sufficient compensation for it.} Qa5+ {This is an important move to remember. We send White's d5 -Knight back to c3 and activate our Queen at the same time.} ({The knee-jerk reaction} 8... Nxd5 $2 {would be a mistake because after} 9. Qxd5 Nc6 10. e3 {, analysis proves that Black does not have much to chew on in this position. White is clearly better. Jobava, B (2603)-Vidit, S (2726) chess24.com INT 2021 was 1-0 in 87 moves.}) 9. Nc3 Nc6 ({Developing our Knight with a tempo as well. This is what playing for compensation looks like: developing our Pieces with threats. For example, Qe3+?!} 9... Be7 {helps Black to prepare ... O-O while White's Queen on e3 comes in the way of their own Pieces.}) 10. Qd1 {Retreating all the way back to d1 is surprisingly the best square for White's Queen. The idea is that it would be less exposed there than on other squares on the board. Now, White's sole aim would be to complete his development as soon as possible and take his King to safety.} Ne4 {Again an energetic move, creating problems for the c3 -Knight.} 11. Bd2 Nxd2 {It is obviously good for us to exchange White's dark-squared Bishop. Their Knight on c3 once again becomes shaky.} 12. Nxd2 {This was tried by GM Praggnanandhaa and then later on caught by other GMs as well. However, GM Wesley So demonstrated the perfect way to equalise right in his game against Pragg.} Bb4 {Creating pressure on the c3 -Knight is a recurring theme of this variation.} 13. Rc1 {White defends the c3 -Knight, but he is ready to give away the a2 -Pawn.} Bxc3 {GM Wesley grabs the a2 -Pawn on the first opportunity.} 14. Rxc3 Qxa2 15. Nc4 {This protects the b2 -Pawn and also limits our Queen. We should be careful not to get our Queen trapped behind the enemy lines. The next few moves are important for Black.} Be6 {Exerting quick pressure on the c4 -Knight and also opening up the d -file, which can be used to attack White's Queen.} 16. e4 {White opens up his f1 -Bishop and threatens to trap our Queen with Ra3 .} Rd8 {First, we bring our Rook on the open d -file with a tempo.} 17. Nd6+ {This is an important move ensuring Black does not get a chance to castle.} Kf8 {The King will stand better here.} 18. Qc1 {This unpins the d6 -Knight and threatens to trap our Queen with Ra3 .} Qa4 {Our Queen is safe now, and we renew the threat to the d6 -Knight.} 19. Nxb7 Qxe4+ 20. Be2 {This would be a blunder.} Nd4 {When both the e2 -Bishop and the b7 -Knight come under attack.} *

