becomes shaky.} 12. Nxd2 {This was tried by GM Praggnanandhaa and then later on caught by other GMs as well. However, GM Wesley So demonstrated the perfect way to equalise right in his game against Pragg.} Bb4 {Creating pressure on the c3 -Knight is a recurring theme of this variation.} 13. Rc1 {White defends the c3 -Knight, but he is ready to give away the a2 -Pawn.} Bxc3 {GM Wesley grabs the a2 -Pawn on the first opportunity.} 14. Rxc3 Qxa2 15. Nc4 {This protects the b2 -Pawn and also limits our Queen. We should be careful not to get our Queen trapped behind the enemy lines. The next few moves are important for Black.} Be6 {Exerting quick pressure on the c4 -Knight and also opening up the d -file, which can be used to attack White's Queen.} 16. e4 {White opens up his f1 -Bishop and threatens to trap our Queen with Ra3 .} Rd8 {First, we bring our Rook on the open d -file with a tempo.} 17. Nd6+ {This is an important move ensuring Black does not get a chance to castle.} Kf8 {The King will stand better here.} 18. Qc1 {This unpins the d6 -Knight and threatens to trap our Queen with Ra3 .} Qa4 {Our Queen is safe now, and we renew the threat to the d6 -Knight.} 19. Nxb7 Qxe4+ 20. Qe3 {The only way to block the check that does not lose material for White.} Qxe3+ 21. fxe3 Rb8 22. Rxc6 {This leads to equality.} Rxb7 23. Bc4 Bxc4 24. Rc8+ (24. Rxc4 {is an equal rook endgame.}) 24... Ke7 25. Rxh8 {This wins an exchange for White, but...} Rxb2 {Black has more than sufficient compensation for it, and in fact, White needs to be careful not to end up in a losing position.} *

