1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e3 ({This is another way for White to play and zoom in against Black's Isolated Queen pawn. Just like the mainline} 7. Bg5 {, White is not interested in opening up the centre immediately with e4 . After e3 , White would like to develop his light-squared Bishop and go for O-O . The drawback, compared to 7.Bg5 , is that White's Bishop is locked in on c1 . He will have to find other paths to develop that Bishop.}) 7... Nc6 {We develop our Knight and hit White's Queen quickly. Now, White has three logical options.} 8. Bb5 {This develops the Bishop and pins the c6 -Knight at the same time. We can ignore the pin and continue developing.} Bd6 {Our Bishop is well placed on d6 , and we prepare ... O-O .} 9. O-O O-O {This renews the threat to White's Queen.} 10. Qh4 {Transferring the Queen on the Kingside may feel good, but the Queen alone cannot scare Black. On top of that, it can be used by Black's Pieces to create additional threats on the Kingside.} Re8 {This was the best way for Black to continue. With the Queen misplaced on h4 , I find it really tough for White to come up with a comfortable way to continue.} (10... Ne7 {was played in Bogner, S (2558)-Hauge, L (2321) Zuerich 2013, and White won in 32 moves.}) 11. Rd1 {A logical move that is strongly met.} Bg4 12. Be2 {This falls short to a surprising resource.} Re4 {Using the exposed placement of the Queen on h4 . This move clearly highlights the drawback of White's Queen.} 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Nd4 Bxe2 15. Nxe2 Bxh2+ {This wins material for Black.} *

