1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e3 ({This is another way for White to play and zoom in against Black's Isolated Queen pawn. Just like the mainline} 7. Bg5 {, White is not interested in opening up the centre immediately with e4 . After e3 , White would like to develop his light-squared Bishop and go for O-O . The drawback, compared to 7.Bg5 , is that White's Bishop is locked in on c1 . He will have to find other paths to develop that Bishop.}) 7... Nc6 {We develop our Knight and hit White's Queen quickly. Now, White has three logical options.} 8. Bb5 {This develops the Bishop and pins the c6 -Knight at the same time. We can ignore the pin and continue developing.} Bd6 {Our Bishop is well placed on d6 , and we prepare ... O-O .} 9. O-O O-O {This renews the threat to White's Queen.} 10. Qh4 {Transferring the Queen on the Kingside may feel good, but the Queen alone cannot scare Black. On top of that, it can be used by Black's Pieces to create additional threats on the Kingside.} Re8 {This was the best way for Black to continue. With the Queen misplaced on h4 , I find it really tough for White to come up with a comfortable way to continue.} (10... Ne7 {was played in Bogner, S (2558)-Hauge, L (2321) Zuerich 2013, and White won in 32 moves.}) 11. b3 {Another normal-looking move preparing to develop the dark-squared Bishop.} a6 {Forcing White to make a choice with his light-squared Bishop.} 12. Bd3 {This is not a good retreat anymore as White's Queen comes under heavy pressure.} Be7 13. Bb2 Ne4 14. Qh5 g6 15. Qh6 Bf8 {The Queen gets chased away on every move.} 16. Qf4 {This loses a Piece for White.} g5 17. Nxg5 Nxg5 18. Qg3 Bg7 {And even though White seems to have some compensation for the lost Piece on the Kingside, it is in no way sufficient. Black is clearly better.} *

