1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e3 ({This is another way for White to play and zoom in against Black's Isolated Queen pawn. Just like the mainline} 7. Bg5 {, White is not interested in opening up the centre immediately with e4 . After e3 , White would like to develop his light-squared Bishop and go for O-O . The drawback, compared to 7.Bg5 , is that White's Bishop is locked in on c1 . He will have to find other paths to develop that Bishop.}) 7... Nc6 {We develop our Knight and hit White's Queen quickly. Now, White has three logical options.} 8. Bb5 {This develops the Bishop and pins the c6 -Knight at the same time. We can ignore the pin and continue developing.} Bd6 {Our Bishop is well placed on d6 , and we prepare ... O-O .} 9. Qa4 {White threatens to win a Pawn on c6 , but we could not care less.} O-O 10. O-O {This is the best for White.} Ne5 {It is usually favourable for Black to exchange White's f3 Knight as it weakens his Kingside defence a bit.} 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Rd1 Be6 {Objectively, the position is equal, but I believe that practically Black has better chances in this position because of our active Pieces. In Ivanov,M (2281)-Rodkin,F (2171) St Petersburg 2007, White won in 62 moves.} *

