1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e3 ({This is another way for White to play and zoom in against Black's Isolated Queen pawn. Just like the mainline} 7. Bg5 {, White is not interested in opening up the centre immediately with e4 . After e3 , White would like to develop his light-squared Bishop and go for O-O . The drawback, compared to 7.Bg5 , is that White's Bishop is locked in on c1 . He will have to find other paths to develop that Bishop.}) 7... Nc6 {We develop our Knight and hit White's Queen quickly. Now, White has three logical options.} 8. Bb5 {This develops the Bishop and pins the c6 -Knight at the same time. We can ignore the pin and continue developing.} Bd6 {Our Bishop is well placed on d6 , and we prepare ... O-O .} 9. Qa4 {White threatens to win a Pawn on c6 , but we could not care less.} O-O 10. Bxc6 {It is a great time waster to grab a Pawn here.} bxc6 11. Qxc6 Rb8 12. Qa4 (12. O-O {is met by} Bg4 13. Nd4 Rb6 14. Qa4 Ne4 {when Black gets amazing attacking chances on the Kingside.}) 12... Rb4 {Activating the Rook and pushing the Queen back even further.} 13. Qd1 Ba6 {White's King is stuck in the centre while his Pieces are undeveloped. Black has great compensation for just one Pawn and went on to win in 49 moves in Dong Bao Nghia (2227) -Mamedyarov,S (2770) chess.com INT 2020.} *

