1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e3 ({This is another way for White to play and zoom in against Black's Isolated Queen pawn. Just like the mainline} 7. Bg5 {, White is not interested in opening up the centre immediately with e4 . After e3 , White would like to develop his light-squared Bishop and go for O-O . The drawback, compared to 7.Bg5 , is that White's Bishop is locked in on c1 . He will have to find other paths to develop that Bishop.}) 7... Nc6 {We develop our Knight and hit White's Queen quickly. Now, White has three logical options.} 8. Qd3 ({We can continue by placing our Pieces on optimal squares. This is more or less similar to} 8. Qd1 {. Retreating the Queen all the way back to the initial square is not at all challenging. This retreat signifies that White is ready to play as Black in this game. This position occurs with reversed colours in the opening theory, so we can say that the colours are switched. This is a typical IQP position, and there are a lot of ways for Black to continue. For example:} Bd6 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O {is a position that I have played quite a lot with reversed colours. I used to arrive in this position from the Exchange Panov variation of the Caro-Kann defence with the Black Pieces.}) 8... Bd6 {Intending to castle next.} 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Re8 {Improving our Rook's placement.} 11. Rd1 Be6 {Fostering the d5 -Pawn.} 12. b3 a6 {Preventing the Nb5 - Nd4 manoeuvre.} 13. Bb2 Qe7 14. Rac1 Rad8 {Both sides have placed their Pieces on optimal squares, and this is a playable position for both sides.} *

