1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. Rd1 O-O 9. Qd2 ({This prophylactic retreat was tried by GM Giri, but it is nothing special.} 9. e3 Be6 {transposes.}) 9... Be6 10. e3 Nc6 {And now the game proceeded to an equal endgame.} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Qxd5 Bxb2 {With a draw in 50 moves in Giri,A (2768)-Sadhwani,R (2627) chess.com INT 2023.} *

