1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Bd3 {Tried by GM Duda. Placing the light-squared Bishop actively restricts his own Queen from retreating along the d -file.} h6 {A typical move before developing our Queenside.} 10. Bh4 Nc6 11. Qa4 Bd7 ({Again exploiting White's exposed Queen's position.} 11... Be6 {is an alternative. You can find it in the model game Duda vs. Vidit.}) 12. Qd1 Bg4 {A strong move using the fact that White's Bishop is absent from its usual e2 -square.} 13. h3 (13. Be2 {is met by} Bxf3 $1 14. Bxf3 d4 $1 {A desirable central break for Black.} 15. exd4 Nxd4 16. O-O Qb6 {with a completely fine position for Black. Our Knight is active on d4 , and it is White who is facing the music.}) 13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 d4 {Again, going for the typical central pawn break is the key idea for Black. We are doing fine, and you can find this game in the model games section: Duda,J (2738)-Grischuk,A (2778) Krasnaya Polyana RUS 2021, draw in 28 moves.} *

