1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Bb5 {It seems weird at first sight to develop the Bishop on b5 with our Knight still on b8 , but that is exactly White's idea. They want us to play ... Nc6 so that they can play Qa4 , which could create pressure on the c6 -Knight. So, Bb5 is more of a prophylactic move.} h6 {As usual, we play this useful move before continuing with Queenside play.} 10. Bh4 a6 {It is better to push White's Bishop to a4 before playing ... Nc6 so that White won’t have the option of Qa4 .} (10... Nc6 $6 {is a move we should avoid in this position as, after} 11. Qa4 {, play transposes to a variation that we want to avoid.}) 11. Ba4 Nc6 {Now we develop our Knight with a tempo. White can either retreat his Queen or exchange on c6 . We are OK with either of them.} 12. Qd3 Bg4 {This active Bishop sortie is the best for Black. Now, we can always think of an exchange on f3 that ruins White's Kingside Pawn structure.} (12... Nb4 {led to a draw in 46 moves in Gharibyan, M (2460)-Kantor, G (2527) Tornelo INT 2021.}) 13. O-O {This natural move is met by a strong and thematic reaction.} Bxf3 14. gxf3 d4 {Eliminating the weak d -Pawn at the first opportunity.} 15. exd4 Qxd4 16. Qxd4 Nxd4 {The position is objectively equal, but it is only Black who is pressing for more because of our better Pawn structure.} *

