prophylactic move.} h6 {As usual, we play this useful move before continuing with Queenside play.} 10. Bh4 a6 {It is better to push White's Bishop to a4 before playing ... Nc6 so that White won’t have the option of Qa4 .} (10... Nc6 $6 {is a move we should avoid in this position as, after} 11. Qa4 {, play transposes to a variation that we want to avoid.}) 11. Ba4 Nc6 {Now we develop our Knight with a tempo. White can either retreat his Queen or exchange on c6 . We are OK with either of them.} 12. Qd3 Bg4 {This active Bishop sortie is the best for Black. Now, we can always think of an exchange on f3 that ruins White's Kingside Pawn structure.} (12... Nb4 {led to a draw in 46 moves in Gharibyan, M (2460)-Kantor, G (2527) Tornelo INT 2021.}) 13. Bxc6 {This does not make sense, especially after refusing this exchange on the previous move. But here, it is a bit better as White can play Ne5 , attacking both the Bg4 and c6 -pawn.} bxc6 14. Ne5 {White creates multiple threats, but we can defend them.} Qc8 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nxg4 Qxg4 17. O-O Qb4 {Even though White's Pawn structure is slightly preferable because of fewer Pawn islands, Black's active Pieces ensure that the position remains balanced.} *

