1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Bb5 {It seems weird at first sight to develop the Bishop on b5 with our Knight still on b8 , but that is exactly White's idea. They want us to play ... Nc6 so that they can play Qa4 , which could create pressure on the c6 -Knight. So, Bb5 is more of a prophylactic move.} h6 {As usual, we play this useful move before continuing with Queenside play.} 10. Bh4 a6 {It is better to push White's Bishop to a4 before playing ... Nc6 so that White won’t have the option of Qa4 .} (10... Nc6 $6 {is a move we should avoid in this position as, after} 11. Qa4 {, play transposes to a variation that we want to avoid.}) 11. Ba4 Nc6 {Now we develop our Knight with a tempo. White can either retreat his Queen or exchange on c6 . We are OK with either of them.} 12. Qd3 Bg4 {This active Bishop sortie is the best for Black. Now, we can always think of an exchange on f3 that ruins White's Kingside Pawn structure.} (12... Nb4 {led to a draw in 46 moves in Gharibyan, M (2460)-Kantor, G (2527) Tornelo INT 2021.}) 13. Rd1 {White turns up the pressure on the d5 -Pawn.} Qa5 {We place our Queen on a nice active square, while also wait for White to go O-O so that we can comfortably exchange on f3 , weakening his Pawn structure.} 14. O-O Bxf3 15. gxf3 Rfd8 {Now our Rook comes on d8 solidifying the d5 -Pawn and threatening ... d4 as well. This highlights another benefit of moving the Queen to a5 .} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Bc2 {White tries to create something on the Kingside with this Queen-Bishop battery. But Black's King is completely safe, and we can calmly ignore it.} d4 18. Qh7+ Kf8 {Black's King is ready to escape to the e -file.} 19. Ne4 ({Unfortunately for White, the tempting} 19. exd4 $2 {makes things worse as after} Nxd4 {, Black takes over the initiative since White's Kingside is shattered. It is important to note that checks on the e -file can be confidently met by ... Ne6 .}) 19... dxe3 ({The arising endgame is completely equal. A sample line could be fxe3 Rxd1 Rxd1 Rd8 Nxf6 Rxd1+ Bxd1} 19... Qe1 20. Kg2 Qd2 21. Kg3 Qxd1 {, and our King smiles at the face of both White's Queen and Knight as both of them combined cannot harm our King in any way. This endgame is completely equal.}) *

