straight away.} ({We would love to start with h6?! as we have done in the previous variations, but note that here, White can confidently go for the d5 -Pawn with} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qxd5 Qb6 11. Qb5 {when White was better in the game Gukesh, D (2726)-Santos Latasa, J (2680) Linares ESP 2022 and went on to win in 65 moves.}) 9... Be6 {We respond to White's threat by cementing the d5 -pawn with our Bishop. We also wait for white to develop his Bishop on e2 or d3 first before we go for ... Nc6 .} (9... Nc6 10. Qa4 {is slightly annoying for us since White plays Bb5 next.}) 10. Qa4 {Once again, White plays prophylactically, waiting for us to develop our Knight to c6 so that he can go for Bb5 straight away.} Qb6 {As usual, we delay developing our Knight in favour of hitting the b2 -Pawn. This is exactly how we deal with 9.Qa4 . See here.} 11. Rd2 Nbd7 {It is better to develop the Knight on d7 than on c6 for two reasons: 1) We defend the f6 -Knight so our Bishop is free to move to b4 , from where it creates immense pressure along the e1 - a5 diagonal. 2) The Knight can also go to c5 , creating various threats.} 12. Bd3 {White hurries to castle quickly.} Bb4 {The point behind Black's previous move. Now ... Ne4 is a deadly threat.} 13. Bxf6 {It is safe for White to eliminate one of the Knights.} Nxf6 14. O-O Rac8 15. Rc1 Bxc3 {Giving up the Bishop pair in order to weaken White's Pawn structure.} 16. bxc3 Rc7 {Followed by ... Rfc8 hitting the c3 -Pawn. The position is comfortable for Black.} *

