straight away.} ({We would love to start with h6?! as we have done in the previous variations, but note that here, White can confidently go for the d5 -Pawn with} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qxd5 Qb6 11. Qb5 {when White was better in the game Gukesh, D (2726)-Santos Latasa, J (2680) Linares ESP 2022 and went on to win in 65 moves.}) 9... Be6 {We respond to White's threat by cementing the d5 -pawn with our Bishop. We also wait for white to develop his Bishop on e2 or d3 first before we go for ... Nc6 .} (9... Nc6 10. Qa4 {is slightly annoying for us since White plays Bb5 next.}) 10. Qa4 {Once again, White plays prophylactically, waiting for us to develop our Knight to c6 so that he can go for Bb5 straight away.} Qb6 {As usual, we delay developing our Knight in favour of hitting the b2 -Pawn. This is exactly how we deal with 9.Qa4 . See here.} 11. Qb5 {White defends the b2 -Pawn while offering the exchange of Queens at the same time. Exchanging Pieces, especially Queens, is a recommended medicine while playing against an IQP.} Nbd7 {Once again, we bring our Knight to d7 so that we can play ... Bb4 and pressurise the c3 -Knight. Black is doing completely fine in the resulting endgame. I have analysed a few variations for your reference.} 12. Be2 {GM Gukesh played this, clearly unaware of Black's counterplay potential on the Queenside, which his opponent GM Grischuk promptly demonstrated in the game.} (12. Bd3 {is also met by} Bb4 $1 13. O-O Bxc3 14. bxc3 Ne4 {and Black is slightly preferable in this position thanks to White's Queenside weaknesses.}) 12... Bb4 {... Ne4 is on the cards next.} 13. Rd4 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Rfc8 {And Black was all set to win the c3 -Pawn. Gukesh,D (2736)-Grischuk,A (2736) Dubai UAE 2023 ended with a win for Black in 49 moves.} *

