[ECO "D50"]
[PlyCount "40"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Rd1 {A typical move that exerts more pressure on our d5 -Pawn. Another idea behind this Rook move is to wait for Black to develop our Knight to c6 so that they can develop the Bishop directly to b5 , which would help them create pressure on the Knight straight away.} ({We would love to start with h6?! as we have done in the previous variations, but note that here, White can confidently go for the d5 -Pawn with} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qxd5 Qb6 11. Qb5 {when White was better in the game Gukesh, D (2726)-Santos Latasa, J (2680) Linares ESP 2022 and went on to win in 65 moves.}) 9... Be6 {We respond to White's threat by cementing the d5 -pawn with our Bishop. We also wait for white to develop his Bishop on e2 or d3 first before we go for ... Nc6 .} (9... Nc6 10. Qa4 {is slightly annoying for us since White plays Bb5 next.}) 10. Qa4 {Once again, White plays prophylactically, waiting for us to develop our Knight to c6 so that he can go for Bb5 straight away.} Qb6 {As usual, we delay developing our Knight in favour of hitting the b2 -Pawn. This is exactly how we deal with 9.Qa4 . See here.} 11. Qb5 {White defends the b2 -Pawn while offering the exchange of Queens at the same time. Exchanging Pieces, especially Queens, is a recommended medicine while playing against an IQP.} Nbd7 {Once again, we bring our Knight to d7 so that we can play ... Bb4 and pressurise the c3 -Knight. Black is doing completely fine in the resulting endgame. I have analysed a few variations for your reference.} 12. Bxf6 {White retorts to safety first strategy. By exchanging on f6 , they reduce our potential counterplay. However, this gives up the Bishop pair, which makes our life quite comfortable.} Nxf6 {Once again we are all set to play ... Bb4 .} 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. a3 {Covering the b4 -square.} Rfc8 {Threatening ... Bxa3 . Now White needs to play precisely not get into a bad position.} 15. Nb5 Rc2 16. Rb1 Ng4 ({This leads to a forcing continuation:} 16... Rac8 {is equally playable for Black.}) 17. Nfd4 Rxf2 18. h3 Rxf1+ 19. Kxf1 Nxe3+ 20. Kf2 Nf5 {The material is more or less balanced. This position offers mutual chances.} *

