straight away.} ({We would love to start with h6?! as we have done in the previous variations, but note that here, White can confidently go for the d5 -Pawn with} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qxd5 Qb6 11. Qb5 {when White was better in the game Gukesh, D (2726)-Santos Latasa, J (2680) Linares ESP 2022 and went on to win in 65 moves.}) 9... Be6 {We respond to White's threat by cementing the d5 -pawn with our Bishop. We also wait for white to develop his Bishop on e2 or d3 first before we go for ... Nc6 .} (9... Nc6 10. Qa4 {is slightly annoying for us since White plays Bb5 next.}) 10. Qa4 {Once again, White plays prophylactically, waiting for us to develop our Knight to c6 so that he can go for Bb5 straight away.} Qb6 {As usual, we delay developing our Knight in favour of hitting the b2 -Pawn. This is exactly how we deal with 9.Qa4 . See here.} 11. Qb5 {White defends the b2 -Pawn while offering the exchange of Queens at the same time. Exchanging Pieces, especially Queens, is a recommended medicine while playing against an IQP.} Nbd7 {Once again, we bring our Knight to d7 so that we can play ... Bb4 and pressurise the c3 -Knight. Black is doing completely fine in the resulting endgame. I have analysed a few variations for your reference.} 12. Qxb6 Nxb6 (12... axb6 {is fine too.}) 13. Bd3 h6 14. Bh4 (14. Bxf6 {gives up the bishop pair, so after} Bxf6 {, Black remains solid in this endgame.}) 14... g5 15. Bg3 Bb4 {Our typical counter-attacking move.} 16. Be5 Nfd7 17. Bd4 Na4 {Stepping up the Queenside pressure.} 18. a3 Nxc3 19. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 20. bxc3 Rfc8 {With a comfortable endgame for Black.} *

