1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Rd1 {A typical move that exerts more pressure on our d5 -Pawn. Another idea behind this Rook move is to wait for Black to develop our Knight to c6 so that they can develop the Bishop directly to b5 , which would help them create pressure on the Knight straight away.} ({We would love to start with h6?! as we have done in the previous variations, but note that here, White can confidently go for the d5 -Pawn with} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qxd5 Qb6 11. Qb5 {when White was better in the game Gukesh, D (2726)-Santos Latasa, J (2680) Linares ESP 2022 and went on to win in 65 moves.}) 9... Be6 {We respond to White's threat by cementing the d5 -pawn with our Bishop. We also wait for white to develop his Bishop on e2 or d3 first before we go for ... Nc6 .} (9... Nc6 10. Qa4 {is slightly annoying for us since White plays Bb5 next.}) 10. Bd3 {Finally, White develops his Bishop and prepares to castle next.} h6 {As usual, we insert ... h6 before initiating Queenside operations.} 11. Bh4 Qa5 {A strong prophylactic move and the number one choice of many top players in this position. The point is to cover the a4 -square before we go ... Nc6 so that White won't be able to play Qa4 as a response.} (11... Nc6 12. Qa4 Qb6 13. Rd2 {gives White a pleasant version of the IQP.}) 12. Bb1 {White vacates the d3 -square for the Queen in response to ... Nc6 . This would help White create a robust battery along the b1 - h7 diagonal.} Qa6 {Another important prophylactic move which prevents not only Qd3 but also O-O for White. Now we are all set to go ... Nc6 next.} (12... Nc6 {is surely inferior due to} 13. Qd3 {when White threatens Bxf6 and also prepares to castle next with a nice position.}) 13. Qd3 {White decides to offer a Queen exchange and get rid of the annoying Queen on a6 .} Qxd3 14. Bxd3 Nc6 {Generally, endgames against the Isolated Queen Pawn are considered to be quite pleasant for the side playing against it. But in this position, Black is super solid. One of Black many ideas is to snatch the Bishop pair by playing ... g5 followed by ... Nh5 going after the dark-squared Bishop.} 15. h3 {This vacates the h2 -square for the Bishop so that after ... g5 followed by ... Nh5 White can safeguard his Bishop pair with Bh2 .} g5 {This does not stop us from playing ... g5 nevertheless.} 16. Bg3 Ne4 {This forces a transition into a completely equal endgame.} 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Bxa2 {With a level endgame.} *

