1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Qa4 {This is an interesting prophylactic move played in a few games and also recommended by Sam Shankland in his 1.d4 Lifetime Repertoire on Chessable. White moves his Queen away from d4 before we attack it with ... Nc6 .} ({The point is that if we play Nc6 now, then he can create pressure on our Knight by playing} 9. Bb5 {.}) 9... h6 {A useful move for Black. It is clear that White is not going to exchange on f6 and will respond with Bh4 . By inserting ... h6 , Black ensures that there will be no back-rank issues in the future. We also get an option of playing ... g5 if needed.} 10. Bh4 Be6 {In some lines, we will find ourselves developing our Bishop on e6 first before going for ... Nc6 . The point is to wait for White to develop his f1 -Bishop to squares like e2 or d3 so that we can freely develop our Knight to c6 without worrying about Bb5 .} ({However, after analysing it I find it less comfortable compared to the direct} 10... Qb6 {.}) (10... Nc6 $6 {is inferior as after} 11. Bb5 Bd7 12. O-O a6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Ne5 {Even though objectively the position is around equal, practically, I think White has a slight edge as he can create slow and steady pressure against Black's c6 / d5 Pawns. In Vidit,S (2726) -Santos Latasa,J (2608) Tornelo INT 2021, White won in 53 moves.}) 11. Bd3 {This is clearly a preferable square for the Bishop than e2 .} Nc6 {Since White has already committed his Bishop to d3 , now we are free to develop our Knight.} ({Playing} 11... Qb6 {now does not make a difference as White completely ignores the threat to the b2 -Pawn and plays} 12. O-O {Now the best for Black is to develop our Knight and transpose with} Nc6 {because Qxb2? is a mistake due to} 13. Nb5 $1 Bd7 14. Rab1 {Bxb5 Bxb5 Qa3 Qxa3} Ba3 15. Bxf6 gxf6 {Rb3± Black's Pawn structure is weak and our queenside Pieces are yet to come in the game. This gives White a clearly better advantage in this endgame.}) 12. O-O Qb6 {This is a typical square for Black's Queen that you will encounter more than once in this chapter. Our Queen keeps an eye on the b2 -Pawn and the d4 -square from the b6 . The only problem is that we have played ... Qb6 a a bit too late and that gives White an opportunity to completely ignore the threat to the b2 -Pawn.} 13. Ne2 {Moving away the Knight to e2 ensures that Black cannot win the b2 -Pawn comfortably. Also by transferring his Knight to e2 White enhances the control of the key d4 -square.} (13. Qb5 {is a very tempting Queen exchange offer for White. In general it is recommended to exchange as many Pieces as possible if you are playing against the Isolated Queen Pawn. So this move is in line with this principle.} Qxb5 {There is no harm in exchanging Queens as Black is pretty solid despite having an isolated Pawn.} 14. Nxb5 g5 $1 {This is the simplest way to gain activity. Black is going to play ... Ne4 next. This will be covered here via the more precise 10...Qb6 move order. Bxb5 can also be met by the same g5 kicking the Bishop away from h4 so that we can activate our Knight in the centre. This will be covered here via the more precise 10...Qb6 move order.}) 13... Bd7 {Creating threats against White's Queen on a4 .} (13... Qxb2 $2 {is clearly inferior due to} 14. Rab1 Qa3 15. Qxa3 Bxa3 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Rxb7 {We have two weak pawns in our position, which is a huge source of trouble in the future.}) 14. Rfd1 ({This novelty could be White's best try to fight for a pleasant position in this variation.} 14. Qd1 $6 {is strongly met by} Bg4 {The Bishop exerts uncomfortable pressure along the d1 - h5 diagonal making it tough for White to maintain control of the d4 -square. Sturt, R (2434)-Prraneeth, V (2400), Novi Sad SRB 2022, was a draw in 29 moves.}) ({After} 14. Qb5 {, the simplest for Black was to exchange the Queens just like in the 13.Qb5 variation.} Nb4 {was played in Shankland, S (2691)-Vidit, S (2726) chess24.com INT 2021, and White won in 38 moves. Better is Qxb5Ν Bxb5 and activate our Knight in the centre in a typical fashion by playing g5!} 15. Bg3 Ne4 16. Rfd1 Be6 17. Ned4 Rac8 18. Rac1 {White exerts further pressure on the c6 -Knight.} Nxg3 {Black can embark on some simplifications.} 19. hxg3 {Nxd4 Nxd4} Rxc1 20. Rxc1 Rc8 {and Black is doing completely fine. A sample variation could be} 21. Rd1 {White should maintain at least one pair of Rooks in order to have some hopes of pressurizing the d5 -Pawn in the future.} Rc5 {Bd3 Bf6 Our dark-squared Bishop is ideally placed on f6 .} 22. Kf1 h5 {with a fine endgame for Black.}) 14... Nb4 {Black maintains comfortable position with various possibilities here. This is one of them.} 15. Qb3 a5 {Gaining space on the Queenside and threatening ... a4 .} ({It is tempting to exchange our Knight for the strong d3 -Bishop, but} 15... Nxd3 $6 {helps White to easily build up pressure against the d5 -Pawn.} 16. Qxd3 Qxb2 17. Rdb1 Bf5 $1 18. Qxf5 Qxe2 19. Rxb7 {Objectively, the position is still equal, but I think White has a slight initiative because of his Piece activity.}) 16. a4 {Prevents Black from further advancing on the Queenside, but now our Knight is cemented on b4 .} (16. a3 {forces us to make a decision regarding the b4 -Knight, but it also weakens a few squares on the Queenside which benefits Black.} a4 17. Qc3 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Bb5 19. Qc2 Bc4 {with the Bishop beautifully placed on c4 , Black does not need to worry about the isolated d5 -Pawn.}) 16... Rac8 17. Ned4 Rfd8 {Both our Rooks are in play now.} 18. Ne5 Be6 {This position is completely fine for Black. The Isolated pawn is compensated with stability of our Pieces on the Queenside.} *

