y Nc6 now, then he can create pressure on our Knight by playing} 9. Bb5 {.}) 9... h6 {A useful move for Black. It is clear that White is not going to exchange on f6 and will respond with Bh4 . By inserting ... h6 , Black ensures that there will be no back-rank issues in the future. We also get an option of playing ... g5 if needed.} 10. Bh4 Qb6 ({We threaten the b2 -Pawn immediately forcing White to react to it. If we delay this then White has the option of ignoring this threat altogether as can be seen here in the} 10... Be6 {variation.}) 11. Qb5 {This is the only sensible way of covering the b2 -Pawn. White also offers a trade of Queens, which is generally said to favour the side playing against the isolated Queen Pawn. But Black is quite solid, and the Queen trade is not to be feared. One of White's ideas is now to exchange on f6 and then capture the d5 -Pawn.} Be6 {Covering the d5 -Pawn.} ({It is, of course, possible to play the natural} 11... Nc6 {, but I prefer to keep the c -file open for the moment, as it can be used by our Rook to create pressure.}) 12. Bd3 ({This leads to a position that can also be reached via Be6} 12. Bd3 Nc6 13. O-O {Qb6 , where Ne2 was an extra option for White, as explained in the informational.}) 12... Qxb5 13. Nxb5 Nc6 14. O-O {We have transposed to this note without allowing the extra 13.Ne2 option for White.} g5 {This is the simplest way to gain activity. Black is going to play ... Ne4 next.} 15. Bg3 Ne4 {With our Knight strongly placed in the centre, we are ready to play ... Bf6 next.} 16. Rfd1 Nxg3 17. hxg3 Bf6 18. Rab1 Rfd8 {All the black Pieces are well placed and White is far away from creating any pressure on the d5 -Pawn. Black is fine in this endgame. In the Model Games chapter, you can see the game Duda, J (2729)-Vidit, S (2726), EU-Cup online rapid 2021, draw in 75 moves.} *

