1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Be2 h6 {Whenever we get a chance, we try to insert this useful move.} 10. Bh4 Nc6 {Finally, we bring in our Knight with a tempo.} 11. Qd1 {It is possible to retreat the Queen all the way back to d1 , but White may have to move his Queen again in order to connect the Rooks.} Qb6 {As mentioned earlier in the variations in this chapter, the b6 -square is the best square for our Queen. White's b2 -Pawn is now under attack, and he has to address this threat.} 12. a3 ({An indirect way of defending the b2 -Pawn as Qxb2?? loses the Queen to} 12. Na4 {. White also discourages us from playing the ... d4 Pawn break.}) 12... Rd8 {This is a natural follow-up to ... Qb6 . Our obvious idea behind playing ... Rd8 is to play ... d4 .} (12... Be6 {protecting the d5 -Pawn is a fine alternative and was tried in one recent game. Santos,A (2162)-Petrov,N (2592) Lisbon POR 2020 was won by Black in 53 moves.}) 13. Na4 {A prophylactic move against the ... d4 Pawn break.} Qc7 14. Bg3 Qd7 {We are, again, ready to launch the ... d4 break.} 15. Nd4 {This looks logical but is strongly met.} Ne4 {The Knight is well placed on e4 . This is the drawback of transferring the Knight on the edge of the board with Na4 .} 16. O-O Nxd4 17. exd4 Nxg3 {Black gets slightly better chances thanks to our Bishop pair.} *

