to connect the Rooks.} Qb6 {As mentioned earlier in the variations in this chapter, the b6 -square is the best square for our Queen. White's b2 -Pawn is now under attack, and he has to address this threat.} 12. Bxf6 {This was tried by GM Martirosyan.} Bxf6 13. Nxd5 Qxb2 14. Rb1 {This is the main idea. White intends to distract our Queen so that he can ruin our Kingside Pawn structure by exchanging on f6 .} Qxa2 15. Nxf6+ gxf6 16. O-O Rd8 {This move, missed by GM Tabatabaei, is Black's best. We attack White's Queen, forcing him to make an uncomfortable choice as his Queen is tied down to the e2 -Bishop.} ({The game Martirosyan, H (2632)-Tabatabaei, M (2613) Krasnaya Polyana RUS 2021 continued} 16... b6 $6 {and was a draw in 49 moves.}) 17. Nd4 (17. Qe1 $6 {is way too passive for White to hope for any compensation. After the simple} a5 {, Black is clearly hopeful about his Pawns on the Queenside.}) 17... Nxd4 18. exd4 Qd5 {Our Queen comes back in the defence, creating pressure on the d4 -Pawn at the same time. White has some compensation for the Pawn, but he should play accurately to maintain the balance.} *

