1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Be2 h6 {Whenever we get a chance, we try to insert this useful move.} 10. Bh4 Nc6 {Finally, we bring in our Knight with a tempo.} 11. Qd3 Qb6 {I find this the most logical move. By developing our Queen to b6 , we not only attack the b2 -Pawn but also vacate the d8 -square for our Rook. Our Rook coming to d8 helps us prepare for the ... d4 Pawn break.} 12. O-O Rd8 {The ... d4 break is on its way, and White needs to do something about it.} ({It is also possible to capture the b2 -Pawn directly:} 12... Qxb2 $6 {when we arrive at a similar endgame that we get in our mainline. White plays} 13. Rab1 Qa3 14. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Qxd3 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bxd3 {This is similar to the endgame that we get in the mainline starting with 12...Rd8 followed by ... Qxb2 . The only difference is that a pair of Rooks are still on the board, and this gives White a comparatively superior endgame. Despite all this, Black can play this endgame as it is objectively equal.}) 13. Nb5 ({The other way of maintaining control of the d4 -square. Now, g5?! followed by} 13. Bg3 Ne4 $4 {is obviously not possible due to} 14. Bc7 {.}) 13... Bg4 {Black develops his Bishop actively and indirectly fights for the d4 -square. This was played by GM Sergey Karjakin in the FIDE World Cup 2021. Now we are ready to bring our last piece in action with ... Rac8 .} 14. Nfd4 {This was chosen by GM Fedoseev, but this is a dubious move as it allows Black to force a better Pawn structure for himself.} Bxe2 15. Qxe2 a6 {This forces White to exchange on c6 .} 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Nc3 Qb4 {Threatening the h4 -Bishop and activating our Queen.} 18. Bg3 c5 {This would have given Black better chances. The idea is to advance in the centre with ... d4 , creating a passed Pawn on the d -file.} ({Instead,} 18... Ne4 {was played in Fedoseev, V (2696)-Karjakin, S (2757) Krasnaya Polyana RUS 2021, which ended in a draw in 69 moves.}) 19. Rad1 d4 20. Nb1 Bd6 {And Black has slightly better chances thanks to his advanced Passed Pawn on the d -file.} *

