acate the d8 -square for our Rook. Our Rook coming to d8 helps us prepare for the ... d4 Pawn break.} 12. O-O Rd8 {The ... d4 break is on its way, and White needs to do something about it.} ({It is also possible to capture the b2 -Pawn directly:} 12... Qxb2 $6 {when we arrive at a similar endgame that we get in our mainline. White plays} 13. Rab1 Qa3 14. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Qxd3 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bxd3 {This is similar to the endgame that we get in the mainline starting with 12...Rd8 followed by ... Qxb2 . The only difference is that a pair of Rooks are still on the board, and this gives White a comparatively superior endgame. Despite all this, Black can play this endgame as it is objectively equal.}) 13. Nb5 ({The other way of maintaining control of the d4 -square. Now, g5?! followed by} 13. Bg3 Ne4 $4 {is obviously not possible due to} 14. Bc7 {.}) 13... Bg4 {Black develops his Bishop actively and indirectly fights for the d4 -square. This was played by GM Sergey Karjakin in the FIDE World Cup 2021. Now we are ready to bring our last piece in action with ... Rac8 .} 14. Rfd1 {White should sooner or later bring his Rook on the d -file.} Rac8 {All our Pieces are well placed and participating in the game.} 15. Nbd4 Bxf3 {There are a lot of other equally good alternatives for Black, but this seems to be the easiest one to play. By simplifying the position, we try to create counterplay before White manages to bring the a1 -Rook into the game.} 16. Bxf3 Nxd4 17. Qxd4 Qxd4 18. Rxd4 {White has ensured that he does not let Black get away with the Isolated Queen pawn.} Rc2 {But now, our Rook is very annoying for White on the 2nd rank.} 19. Rb1 g5 20. Bg3 Bd6 {Exchanging one of the Bishops is important for Black. Our weakness of the Isolated Queen Pawn is comfortably balanced by our active c2 -Rook. For example:} ({Bd1 White immediately kicks our Rook away.} 20... Rc4 21. Rd3 {Bxg3 hxg3} Rdc8 $1 {intending to exchange one of the Rooks. This will ease future pressure on the d5 -Pawn. Bb3} 22. Rc1 {Rd1 Rxb1 Rxb1} Kf8 {Black's King is coming to the aid of the d5 -Pawn. We have the c -file under control, limiting White's options. Another problem for White is the doubled Pawns on the g -file, which limits his scope on the Kingside. We can also aim to advance on the Kingside with ... h5 and ... g4 . Long story short, Black is comfortable in this endgame despite having the isolated Queen Pawn.}) *

