acate the d8 -square for our Rook. Our Rook coming to d8 helps us prepare for the ... d4 Pawn break.} 12. O-O Rd8 {The ... d4 break is on its way, and White needs to do something about it.} ({It is also possible to capture the b2 -Pawn directly:} 12... Qxb2 $6 {when we arrive at a similar endgame that we get in our mainline. White plays} 13. Rab1 Qa3 14. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Qxd3 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bxd3 {This is similar to the endgame that we get in the mainline starting with 12...Rd8 followed by ... Qxb2 . The only difference is that a pair of Rooks are still on the board, and this gives White a comparatively superior endgame. Despite all this, Black can play this endgame as it is objectively equal.}) 13. Rfd1 {This is the most logical way to prevent ... d4 break as it also brings White's Rook into the game. Now, it is possible for us to develop our Queenside Pieces and play a normal game. But if a draw is a fine result, then we can take a quick exit to an equal endgame starting with ... Qxb2 .} Qxb2 (13... Bg4 $6 {is not that great in this position since White can respond with the simple} 14. Nd4 {offering a Bishop trade and getting a pleasant version of the IQP.}) 14. Rab1 ({Going for the d5 -Pawn directly with} 14. Bxf6 $2 {backfires due to} Bxf6 15. Nxd5 $2 Rxd5 $1 16. Qxd5 Qxe2 {and we have a winning advantage.}) 14... Qa3 {Now, before we consolidate our extra Pawn, it is wise for White to regain it.} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nxd5 Qxd3 ({We accept an inferior Pawn structure on the Kingside, relying on the fact that White cannot exploit it due to fewer Pieces remaining on the board. If you feel uncomfortable going into this endgame, then you can consider} 16... Qxa2 {.}) 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Bxd3 {This is comfortably met.} Be6 19. a3 {Now, there are many satisfactory ways to continue. The following one is simple:} Rab8 {Defending the b7 -Pawn with a completely equal endgame.} *

