[White "4) Alternatives to 7.e4"]
[Black "7.Bg5 Be7 8.e3 O-O 9.Be2 & 11"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D50"]
[PlyCount "38"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Be2 h6 {Whenever we get a chance, we try to insert this useful move.} 10. Bh4 Nc6 {Finally, we bring in our Knight with a tempo.} 11. Qd3 Qb6 {I find this the most logical move. By developing our Queen to b6 , we not only attack the b2 -Pawn but also vacate the d8 -square for our Rook. Our Rook coming to d8 helps us prepare for the ... d4 Pawn break.} 12. O-O Rd8 {The ... d4 break is on its way, and White needs to do something about it.} ({It is also possible to capture the b2 -Pawn directly:} 12... Qxb2 $6 {when we arrive at a similar endgame that we get in our mainline. White plays} 13. Rab1 Qa3 14. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Qxd3 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bxd3 {This is similar to the endgame that we get in the mainline starting with 12...Rd8 followed by ... Qxb2 . The only difference is that a pair of Rooks are still on the board, and this gives White a comparatively superior endgame. Despite all this, Black can play this endgame as it is objectively equal.}) 13. Rfd1 {This is the most logical way to prevent ... d4 break as it also brings White's Rook into the game. Now, it is possible for us to develop our Queenside Pieces and play a normal game. But if a draw is a fine result, then we can take a quick exit to an equal endgame starting with ... Qxb2 .} Qxb2 (13... Bg4 $6 {is not that great in this position since White can respond with the simple} 14. Nd4 {offering a Bishop trade and getting a pleasant version of the IQP.}) 14. Rab1 ({Going for the d5 -Pawn directly with} 14. Bxf6 $2 {backfires due to} Bxf6 15. Nxd5 $2 Rxd5 $1 16. Qxd5 Qxe2 {and we have a winning advantage.}) 14... Qa3 {Now, before we consolidate our extra Pawn, it is wise for White to regain it.} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nxd5 Qxd3 ({We accept an inferior Pawn structure on the Kingside, relying on the fact that White cannot exploit it due to fewer Pieces remaining on the board. If you feel uncomfortable going into this endgame, then you can consider} 16... Qxa2 {.}) 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Rxd3 Bf5 {Developing our Bishop and forcing White to exchange on d8 .} 19. Rxd8+ Nxd8 {It is important to recapture with our Knight in order to keep the b7 -Pawn protected. This endgame is completely equal as Black's weak Kingside structure is compensation by our Queenside Pawn majority. In Gledura,B (2645)-Deac,B (2693) chess.com INT 2023, a draw was agreed in 21 moves.} *

