1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {White is not interested in opening up the centre with e4 and decides to calmly play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn. By developing his Bishop to g5 , White pins the f6 -Knight and creates indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn. He also ensures that when he plays e3 next, his Bishop won't be locked inside on c1 .} ({Over the years,} 7. Bg5 {has turned out to be the mainline for White in top-level games. It is clear that White does not get much by challenging the centre straight away with e4 if Black knows the theory well. Thus, at top-level games, they prefer to avoid going to the endgame altogether and decide to stay in the Isolated Pawn territory.}) 7... Be7 {A logical developing move, unpinning the f6 -Knight. Of course, it is not possible to win the d5 -Pawn with Bxf6?! Bxf6 Qxd5?? as after Bxc3+ bxc3 Qxd5-+ , Black wins the Queen.} 8. e3 (8. e4 {was tried in an online game by Golubka, but this delayed Pawn break is surely ill-timed for White. Golubka, P (2452)-Svane, R (2613) lichess.org INT 2021 continued} dxe4 {and Svane won in 18 moves. However, Black should have responded with Nc6Ν It is better to hit White's Queen straight away. After} 9. Bb5+ {, a logical developing move, O-O Bxc6 bxc6⩱ , Black has got the Bishop pair and the opening up of the position after the e4 -Pawn break is going to favour Black. Black is slightly better in this position.}) 8... O-O ({We have completed our Kingside development and castled. Now, our idea is to focus on developing our Queenside Pieces. White has got a few options now.} 8... Nc6 {is possible as well, but I find it simpler to castle first and then decide whether to develop the Knight to d7 or c6 .}) 9. Be2 h6 {Whenever we get a chance, we try to insert this useful move.} 10. Bh4 Nc6 {Finally, we bring in our Knight with a tempo.} 11. Qd3 Qb6 {I find this the most logical move. By developing our Queen to b6 , we not only attack the b2 -Pawn but also vacate the d8 -square for our Rook. Our Rook coming to d8 helps us prepare for the ... d4 Pawn break.} 12. O-O Rd8 {The ... d4 break is on its way, and White needs to do something about it.} ({It is also possible to capture the b2 -Pawn directly:} 12... Qxb2 $6 {when we arrive at a similar endgame that we get in our mainline. White plays} 13. Rab1 Qa3 14. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Qxd3 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bxd3 {This is similar to the endgame that we get in the mainline starting with 12...Rd8 followed by ... Qxb2 . The only difference is that a pair of Rooks are still on the board, and this gives White a comparatively superior endgame. Despite all this, Black can play this endgame as it is objectively equal.}) 13. Rfd1 {This is the most logical way to prevent ... d4 break as it also brings White's Rook into the game. Now, it is possible for us to develop our Queenside Pieces and play a normal game. But if a draw is a fine result, then we can take a quick exit to an equal endgame starting with ... Qxb2 .} Qxb2 (13... Bg4 $6 {is not that great in this position since White can respond with the simple} 14. Nd4 {offering a Bishop trade and getting a pleasant version of the IQP.}) 14. Rab1 ({Going for the d5 -Pawn directly with} 14. Bxf6 $2 {backfires due to} Bxf6 15. Nxd5 $2 Rxd5 $1 16. Qxd5 Qxe2 {and we have a winning advantage.}) 14... Qa3 {Now, before we consolidate our extra Pawn, it is wise for White to regain it.} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nxd5 Qxa2 {This is another option that has worked out well for Black in tournament games. However, I feel it is a bit safer to exchange Queens since our Kingside structure is about to be damaged with Nxf6 +.} 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Nd4 {Blocking the d -file and threatening to play Ra1 when our Queen is in trouble.} Be6 {It is better to give up the extra Pawn and complete our development.} 19. Rxb7 Rd6 {With the obvious idea of doubling and creating pressure along the d -file. Despite Black's bad pawn structure on the Kingside, the position remains balanced due to Black's counterplay along the d -file and an outside passer. Both the games that reached this position ended in a draw. I have given a few games here as sample lines so that you can go over them and develop a feel for this endgame.} ({Rd2} 19... Qa1 {Rb1 Qa5 Rdd1 Nxd4 exd4 Rad8} 20. h4 {Qf5 Qg3+ Qg6 Qf4 Qf5 Qxh6} Rxd4 {Rbc1 Qe5 Rxd4 Rxd4} 21. Bh5 {Rd8 Bf3} a5 {Qe3 a4 Qa7} 22. Qxd4 {Qe7} Rb8 {Rd1 Qxh4} 23. Qa7 {Rb2 Qc5 Qb4 Qxb4 Rxb4} Bd5 {Bf5} 24. Rc1 {Rb1 and a draw was agreed in Mamedyarov, S (2762)-So, W (2778) chess24.com INT 2021.}) ({Bf1 Rad8 Qc3} 19... Nxd4 20. exd4 Qa4 21. Qg3+ Kf8 22. Rb8 Qd7 23. Rdb1 {Rb6 Rxd8+ Qxd8 Rd1 Rd6 Qf4 Kg7 Rd3 Rd5 h4} f5 {g3 Qb6} 24. Rd1 {Qb3 Ra1 Qb4 Rxa7} Qxd4 {Qxd4+ and a draw was agreed in Indjic, A (2621)-Asadli, V (2578) Tashkent UZB 2022.}) ({Ra1 Qxd4 Qg3+ Qg4 Qxg4+} 19... Bg4 20. Rxa7 Be6 21. Rxa8 Rxa8 {Rxa8+ Kg7} 22. Ra1 {Rb6 h4 Rd6 g3 Rb6 and a draw was agreed in Li Chao b (2658)-Wen Yang (2581) Fuling CHN 2023.}) *

