acate the d8 -square for our Rook. Our Rook coming to d8 helps us prepare for the ... d4 Pawn break.} 12. O-O Rd8 {The ... d4 break is on its way, and White needs to do something about it.} ({It is also possible to capture the b2 -Pawn directly:} 12... Qxb2 $6 {when we arrive at a similar endgame that we get in our mainline. White plays} 13. Rab1 Qa3 14. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Qxd3 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bxd3 {This is similar to the endgame that we get in the mainline starting with 12...Rd8 followed by ... Qxb2 . The only difference is that a pair of Rooks are still on the board, and this gives White a comparatively superior endgame. Despite all this, Black can play this endgame as it is objectively equal.}) 13. Rfd1 {This is the most logical way to prevent ... d4 break as it also brings White's Rook into the game. Now, it is possible for us to develop our Queenside Pieces and play a normal game. But if a draw is a fine result, then we can take a quick exit to an equal endgame starting with ... Qxb2 .} Be6 {Also playable. This is an ideal square for our light-squared Bishop. We are ready to play ... Rac8 next.} 14. Qb5 Qxb5 15. Nxb5 {Whenever White's Knight is absent from c3 , we should play,} g5 16. Bg3 Ne4 {Centralising our Knight and aiming to win the Bishop pair.} 17. Rac1 Bf6 {And this is the ideal square for our dark-squared Bishop.} 18. Nfd4 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Nxg3 20. hxg3 Rac8 {Black was doing completely fine in the game Radjabov,T (2765)-So,W (2770) chess24.com INT 2020, a draw in 95 moves.} *

