[White "5) 7.e4 - Sidelines on Move 1"]
[Black "7.e4 dxe4 8.Bb5+ Bd7 9.Ng5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D41"]
[PlyCount "20"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 {This is clearly the most direct way to fight for an initiative in the opening. White challenges our d5 -Pawn and opens up his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} dxe4 ({This move started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. Earlier, the mainline was to first play} 7... Nc6 {and only then exchange on e4 with ... dxe4 .}) ({However, time has proven that it is much easier for Black to play the direct} 7... dxe4 {. The point is that it is beneficial for Black to remain flexible with the positioning of our Queenside Knight.}) 8. Bb5+ {This was once played against me by GM Svane Rasmus.} Bd7 {Now I have analysed a few options for White.} 9. Ng5 {This is simply met.} Be7 10. Ngxe4 O-O {With equality.} *

