1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 {This is clearly the most direct way to fight for an initiative in the opening. White challenges our d5 -Pawn and opens up his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} dxe4 ({This move started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. Earlier, the mainline was to first play} 7... Nc6 {and only then exchange on e4 with ... dxe4 .}) ({However, time has proven that it is much easier for Black to play the direct} 7... dxe4 {. The point is that it is beneficial for Black to remain flexible with the positioning of our Queenside Knight.}) 8. Bb5+ {This was once played against me by GM Svane Rasmus.} Bd7 {Now I have analysed a few options for White.} 9. Bxd7+ {This leads to quick exchanges.} Qxd7 10. Qe5+ Qe7 11. Qxe7+ Bxe7 12. Ng5 Bb4 {Making it tough for White to regain the Pawn.} 13. Bd2 ({It is necessary to cover the c3 -Knight.} 13. O-O $2 {was a mistake as after} Bxc3 14. bxc3 O-O {Black was a healthy Pawn up and clearly better in Goryachkina, A (2593)-Duda, J (2729) Tornelo INT 2021, 0-1 in 55 moves.}) 13... Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Nbd7 ({Black is fine in this endgame. A sample variation could be O-O-O} 14... h6 15. Nxe4 $1 Nxe4 {Rhe1 Ndc5} 16. f3 O-O 17. fxe4 {Rac8= with a better Pawn structure. It is only Black who can press for an advantage from this position.}) *

