1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 {This is clearly the most direct way to fight for an initiative in the opening. White challenges our d5 -Pawn and opens up his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} dxe4 ({This move started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. Earlier, the mainline was to first play} 7... Nc6 {and only then exchange on e4 with ... dxe4 .}) ({However, time has proven that it is much easier for Black to play the direct} 7... dxe4 {. The point is that it is beneficial for Black to remain flexible with the positioning of our Queenside Knight.}) 8. Bb5+ {This was once played against me by GM Svane Rasmus.} Bd7 {Now I have analysed a few options for White.} 9. Ne5 {My opponent started burning a lot of time on every move, which tempted me to look for more than equality. Instead, the simplest path to equality is development.} Be7 {Preparing ... O-O is the simplest solution in this position.} (9... Bxb5 {was my choice, which led to complications after} 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Nxb5 a6 $5 {and the position was dynamic and unclear in Svane, R (2570)-Swapnil, S (2534) Moscow RUS 2017. White won in 33 moves.}) 10. Nxd7 Nbxd7 11. Bg5 {White prepares O-O-O .} O-O 12. O-O-O {White seems to have managed to create strong pressure along the d -file, but Black has an important resource that nullifies everything.} Qa5 {Pinning the Bishop on b5 and getting away from the d -file.} 13. Qa4 ({White looks for salvation.} 13. Bxd7 $4 {is met by} Qxg5+ 14. Kb1 Rad8 {and Black wins material.}) 13... Qxa4 14. Bxa4 Nc5 15. Bc2 Rfd8 {When White wins the e4 -Pawn, it will be a completely equal endgame.} *

