1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 {This is clearly the most direct way to fight for an initiative in the opening. White challenges our d5 -Pawn and opens up his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} dxe4 ({This move started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. Earlier, the mainline was to first play} 7... Nc6 {and only then exchange on e4 with ... dxe4 .}) ({However, time has proven that it is much easier for Black to play the direct} 7... dxe4 {. The point is that it is beneficial for Black to remain flexible with the positioning of our Queenside Knight.}) 8. Qxd8+ (8. Nxe4 $4 {is out of the question due to} Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxe4 {wins a Piece for Black.}) 8... Kxd8 {This Queen exchange is comparable to the Queen exchange in the Berlin Defence. There, too, the Queens get exchanged on the d8 -square, and we quickly reach an endgame. The endgame there is more complicated than the one here. We may need to invest a few more moves to take our King to a comfortable square, but we are always on time to do it as we will study in this and upcoming chapters.} 9. Ne5 {A rare move tried by GM Carlsen against GM Caruana in a rapid game. In this game, he made it work for White, but objectively, this is harmless.} Be6 {We develop our Bishop and the defend the f7 -Pawn at the same time.} 10. Bg5 {A multi-purpose move. White prepares O-O-O . Pinning the f6 -Knight also gives White an option of capturing our e4 -Pawn.} Bb4 {We follow suit. Black pins the c3 -Knight and prepares to play ... Ke7 in case White castles long.} 11. O-O-O+ Ke7 {Our King has moved away from the crossfire and feels safe on e7 .} 12. Nd5+ {This is White's only move to keep the balance.} Bxd5 13. Rxd5 {White has won the Bishop pair but is still yet to regain the Pawn.} h6 {More or less forcing White to exchange on f6 .} 14. Bxf6+ Kxf6 {We have managed to maintain our extra Pawn, but our Queenside is still undeveloped. Our next move should be to develop our b8 -Knight.} 15. Rb5 {This is comfortably met.} Rc8+ 16. Kb1 Bc5 17. Ng4+ Kg5 {Chasing the Knight.} 18. Ne5 b6 ({White's Rook is sidetracked, and Black has good chances to press for an advantage. If White tries to capture the f7 -Pawn with Nxf7+ , then after the simple} 18... Kf6 {, their Knight comes in danger, although White has a precise continuation that keeps them in the zone of equality.} 19. b4 $1 {This is the only move that keeps the game going for White. They sacrifice an exchange to safeguard their Knight.} ({(} 19. Bc4 $2 {is the first move that comes to mind, but it is strongly met by} a6 $1 20. Rb3 Ra7 {and the f7 -Knight is about to fall.} 21. Re1 {going after the e4 -pawn, but...} Re8 $1 {White's Knight is not running away. We can calmly defend the e4 -Pawn. Next, we are ready to capture the f7 -Knight when we will gain two pieces for a Rook and a winning advantage.)}) 19... a6 20. bxc5 axb5 {Nd6 threatening the Rook and the Pawn. Rd8} 21. Bxb5 {and now bxc5?! is met by Nxe4+⩱ followed by capturing the c5 -Pawn as well, so Black should play} e3 $1 {intending to ruin White's Pawn structure.} 22. fxe3 {bxc5⩱ There are a few pawns remaining on the board which gives White good chances to hold this game to a draw despite being an exchange down.}) *

