{Centralising our Knight, and we have a completely level endgame. It is important to note that White cannot win our b7 -Pawn with Rf4+ due to Ke7 Bxb7?? Nd3+-+ A simple fork that wins the game for us.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 {This is clearly the most direct way to fight for an initiative in the opening. White challenges our d5 -Pawn and opens up his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} dxe4 ({This move started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. Earlier, the mainline was to first play} 7... Nc6 {and only then exchange on e4 with ... dxe4 .}) ({However, time has proven that it is much easier for Black to play the direct} 7... dxe4 {. The point is that it is beneficial for Black to remain flexible with the positioning of our Queenside Knight.}) 8. Qxd8+ (8. Nxe4 $4 {is out of the question due to} Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxe4 {wins a Piece for Black.}) 8... Kxd8 {This Queen exchange is comparable to the Queen exchange in the Berlin Defence. There, too, the Queens get exchanged on the d8 -square, and we quickly reach an endgame. The endgame there is more complicated than the one here. We may need to invest a few more moves to take our King to a comfortable square, but we are always on time to do it as we will study in this and upcoming chapters.} 9. Ng5 {A logical move threatening both the e4 and f7 -Pawns.} Be6 {Again, a typical way of defending the f7 -Pawn. We are not afraid of an exchange on e6 even though it ruins our Pawn structure. Next, we intend to play ... Bb4 followed by ... Ke7 .} 10. g3 {A rare move and was tried in only one game by GM Nepomniachtchi.} Bb4 {We follow our plan. Next comes ... Ke7 .} 11. Bd2 Ke7 {We have improved our King's placement. Next, we need to focus on bringing our remaining pieces to the party.} 12. Bg2 {White develops his Pieces, also ensuring that the e4 -Pawn is always within their reach.} Nc6 13. Nxe6 Kxe6 14. O-O-O {This is nothing special. We can bring our Rook into play.} Rad8 15. Rhe1 {This pressurises the e4 -Pawn. But we can simplify to an equal endgame.} Bxc3 16. Bxc3 Rxd1+ 17. Kxd1 Rd8+ 18. Kc1 Kf5 {We guard our extra Pawn, more or less forcing White to give away his Bishop pair in order to regain the Pawn.} 19. Bxf6 Kxf6 20. Rxe4 {And now comes a simple move.} Ne5 *

