1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 {This is clearly the most direct way to fight for an initiative in the opening. White challenges our d5 -Pawn and opens up his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} dxe4 ({This move started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. Earlier, the mainline was to first play} 7... Nc6 {and only then exchange on e4 with ... dxe4 .}) ({However, time has proven that it is much easier for Black to play the direct} 7... dxe4 {. The point is that it is beneficial for Black to remain flexible with the positioning of our Queenside Knight.}) 8. Qxd8+ (8. Nxe4 $4 {is out of the question due to} Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxe4 {wins a Piece for Black.}) 8... Kxd8 {This Queen exchange is comparable to the Queen exchange in the Berlin Defence. There, too, the Queens get exchanged on the d8 -square, and we quickly reach an endgame. The endgame there is more complicated than the one here. We may need to invest a few more moves to take our King to a comfortable square, but we are always on time to do it as we will study in this and upcoming chapters.} 9. Ng5 {A logical move threatening both the e4 and f7 -Pawns.} Be6 {Again, a typical way of defending the f7 -Pawn. We are not afraid of an exchange on e6 even though it ruins our Pawn structure. Next, we intend to play ... Bb4 followed by ... Ke7 .} 10. Be3 {This was recently played by GM Duda. White prepares O-O-O , but that does not prevent us from executing our main plan.} Bb4 {Pinning the Knight and intending ... Ke7 next.} 11. O-O-O+ Ke7 12. Nxe6 {An inferior move by GM Duda.} fxe6 13. Nb5 {This was a big mistake that gave Black a solid advantage.} a6 ({The point is that White cannot play Nc7 due to} 13... Rc8+ {, which pins White's Knight on the c -file. Duda, J (2743)-So, W (2770) chess.com INT 2020 ended in a draw in 37 moves.}) *

