1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 {This is clearly the most direct way to fight for an initiative in the opening. White challenges our d5 -Pawn and opens up his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} dxe4 ({This move started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. Earlier, the mainline was to first play} 7... Nc6 {and only then exchange on e4 with ... dxe4 .}) ({However, time has proven that it is much easier for Black to play the direct} 7... dxe4 {. The point is that it is beneficial for Black to remain flexible with the positioning of our Queenside Knight.}) 8. Qxd8+ (8. Nxe4 $4 {is out of the question due to} Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxe4 {wins a Piece for Black.}) 8... Kxd8 {This Queen exchange is comparable to the Queen exchange in the Berlin Defence. There, too, the Queens get exchanged on the d8 -square, and we quickly reach an endgame. The endgame there is more complicated than the one here. We may need to invest a few more moves to take our King to a comfortable square, but we are always on time to do it as we will study in this and upcoming chapters.} 9. Ng5 {A logical move threatening both the e4 and f7 -Pawns.} Be6 {Again, a typical way of defending the f7 -Pawn. We are not afraid of an exchange on e6 even though it ruins our Pawn structure. Next, we intend to play ... Bb4 followed by ... Ke7 .} 10. Bb5 {White places his Bishop actively and prepares O-O .} a6 {A useful move. We simply push White's Bishop back one square before continuing to develop our Pieces.} 11. Ba4 Bb4 {We follow our typical plan of ... Bb4 and then ... Ke7 .} 12. Nxe6+ (12. Bd2 Ke7 13. Nxe6 fxe6 {transposes.}) 12... fxe6 13. Bd2 {Intending Nxe4 , but this is simply met.} Ke7 14. Nxe4 Bxd2+ 15. Nxd2 b5 16. Bb3 Nc6 {Black's little weakness on e6 can be easily guarded. This endgame is clearly equal, and the game Artemiev,V (2698)-Tomashevsky,E (2694) Moscow RUS 2023 ended in a draw soon, in move 26.} *

