1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 {This is clearly the most direct way to fight for an initiative in the opening. White challenges our d5 -Pawn and opens up his light-squared Bishop at the same time.} dxe4 ({This move started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. Earlier, the mainline was to first play} 7... Nc6 {and only then exchange on e4 with ... dxe4 .}) ({However, time has proven that it is much easier for Black to play the direct} 7... dxe4 {. The point is that it is beneficial for Black to remain flexible with the positioning of our Queenside Knight.}) 8. Qxd8+ (8. Nxe4 $4 {is out of the question due to} Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxe4 {wins a Piece for Black.}) 8... Kxd8 {This Queen exchange is comparable to the Queen exchange in the Berlin Defence. There, too, the Queens get exchanged on the d8 -square, and we quickly reach an endgame. The endgame there is more complicated than the one here. We may need to invest a few more moves to take our King to a comfortable square, but we are always on time to do it as we will study in this and upcoming chapters.} 9. Ng5 {A logical move threatening both the e4 and f7 -Pawns.} Be6 {Again, a typical way of defending the f7 -Pawn. We are not afraid of an exchange on e6 even though it ruins our Pawn structure. Next, we intend to play ... Bb4 followed by ... Ke7 .} 10. a3 {A solid prophylactic move preventing our idea of ... Bb4 . This is also a bit counter-intuitive since, when the opponent is behind in development, we tend to develop our Pieces quickly and punish our opponent for ignoring development. But here, White finds time to calm down and first prevent ... Bb4 .} Nbd7 {It is better to develop our Knight to d7 . It can later go to c5 , protecting the e4 -Pawn and also exploiting the newly created weak b3 -square. Now, White has tried four different ways to put pressure on Black.} 11. Bf4 {White develops his Bishop actively and prepares O-O-O , which would bring his Rook into action.} h6 {Forcing White to either take on e4 or e6 .} 12. Nxe6+ (12. Ngxe4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 {transposes.}) 12... fxe6 13. O-O-O {This is another possibility.} Rc8 {We can continue with this typical useful move for Black. We bring our Rook into action quickly before moving our King away from the d -file. Our threat now is to capture the a3 -Pawn.} 14. Kb1 a6 {Preventing Bb5 . It is not easy for White to recover his Pawn.} *

