to action.} h6 {Forcing White to either take on e4 or e6 .} 12. Nxe6+ (12. Ngxe4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 {transposes.}) 12... fxe6 13. O-O-O {This is another possibility.} Rc8 {We can continue with this typical useful move for Black. We bring our Rook into action quickly before moving our King away from the d -file. Our threat now is to capture the a3 -Pawn.} 14. Bb5 {White creates a quick pressure along the d -file.} a6 15. Bxd7 Nxd7 {Once again, our threat of ... Bxa3 is revived.} 16. Rd2 {An interesting move creating a counter threat against the d7 -Knight.} Ke8 ({Getting away from the dangerous d -file.} 16... Bxa3 $2 {would lose to} 17. Kc2 {threatening bxa3 and Rhd1 .}) 17. Rhd1 Nf6 {Once again, we are all set to capture the a3 -Pawn.} 18. Kb1 Be7 {With the idea to play ... Kf7 followed by ... Rhd8 . Black is fine in this endgame.} (18... Bxa3 $4 {is again not possible due to} 19. bxa3 Rxc3 20. Rd8+ {, and White wins.}) ({After} 18... Be7 {, a sample variation could be} 19. Be5 {intending to collect the e4 -Pawn.} Kf7 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Nxe4 ({(} 21. Rd7 $6 {is a mistake due to} f5 $1 {supporting the e4 -Pawn.} 22. Rxb7 Rhd8 {and Black gets better chances in this endgame thanks to the strong e4 -Pawn.)}) 21... Rhd8 $1 {offering some trades.} 22. Rxd8 Rxd8 23. Rxd8 Bxd8 24. Nd6+ {going after the Pawn.} Ke7 25. Nxb7 Bb6 {Targeting the f2 -Pawn but also trapping the Knight.} 26. f3 Kd7 27. b4 {The only move to save the Knight.} Kc6 28. Na5+ Bxa5 29. bxa5 Kd5 $1 {King activity is more important than capturing the useless Pawn on a5 .} 30. Kc2 Kd4 {and this Pawn endgame is dead equal.}) *

