A useful move similar to White's 10.a3 . We take control of the g5 -square, closing the doors for White's Knight retreat again on g5 . Next, we can play .... Nc5 offering the exchange of Knights.} 13. Bf4 {White develops his Bishop and prepares O-O-O at the same time. Another idea behind Bf4 is to provoke Black to play ... g5 or ... f5 . This gains space for Black but also gives White targets to attack on the Kingside.} (13. Be3 {is comfortably met by} f5 14. Ng3 Bc5 {and Black is doing fine.}) 13... Rc8 {A novelty with the simple intention of preventing White from castling on the Queenside. We can also think of infiltrating White's camp with ... Rc2 at the right moment.} (13... Nc5 $2 {is a mistake now. White has the simple} 14. Rd1+ $1 {forcing us to retreat our Knight to d7 . If we don't, then we may incur material losses.}) 14. Bd3 {Develops the Bishop and prevents any ... Rc2 ideas at the same time.} Nc5 {We simplify at the first chance.} 15. Rd1 {This is comfortably met.} Nxd3+ 16. Rxd3+ Ke8 {Our King is safe on e8 .} 17. Kd2 {White intends to bring his h1 -Rook quickly into the action. By placing his King on d2 , he also covers entry points along the c -file.} f5 {This forces White to make a decision with his Knight. We also create a safe square for our King on f7 .} 18. Nc3 Kf7 {Our King is safe. Next, we develop our Kingside pieces with a completely equal endgame.} *

