om the discovered check. Now if given a chance White would love to develop their light squared Bishop and equalise. But they are behind just one move which is sufficient for us to claim a winning advantage.} 16... Bb3 $1 {threatening not only ... Bxd1 but also ... Rc2 +. Now,} 17. Bd3 {prevents ... Rc2 + but loses the exchange.} Bxd1 {Rxd1 Rc6-+ Black is an exchange up and should have no problems converting our advantage into a full point. With Rc1 Rxc1 Kxc1 Re1+} 18. Kd2 {Rd1+ Kc3 , White manages to avoid losing a Piece by counter-attacking our b3 -Bishop. But after the simple} Ba4 {, we not only threaten to capture their d6 -Bishop but also to play ... Bb5 , which would win an exchange for us.}) *

