A useful move similar to White's 10.a3 . We take control of the g5 -square, closing the doors for White's Knight retreat again on g5 . Next, we can play .... Nc5 offering the exchange of Knights.} 13. Bf4 {White develops his Bishop and prepares O-O-O at the same time. Another idea behind Bf4 is to provoke Black to play ... g5 or ... f5 . This gains space for Black but also gives White targets to attack on the Kingside.} (13. Be3 {is comfortably met by} f5 14. Ng3 Bc5 {and Black is doing fine.}) 13... Rc8 {A novelty with the simple intention of preventing White from castling on the Queenside. We can also think of infiltrating White's camp with ... Rc2 at the right moment.} (13... Nc5 $2 {is a mistake now. White has the simple} 14. Rd1+ $1 {forcing us to retreat our Knight to d7 . If we don't, then we may incur material losses.}) 14. Rd1 {White immediately pins the Knight before developing his light-squared Bishop.} f5 {A typical pressure releasing move for us. We push White's Knight away from the centre and create a potential safe haven for our King on f7 .} 15. Ng3 g5 {Gaining space with a tempo and also preparing to fianchetto our Bishop to g7 .} 16. Be5 Rh7 {Threatening ... Bb3 .} 17. Bd3 ({An interesting attempt to create some complications.} 17. Bc3 Bg7 {is just plain equal.}) 17... Nxe5 18. Bxf5+ Rd7 19. Bxe6 Rxd1+ 20. Kxd1 {White has managed to win a Pawn, but we have a simple reply.} Rc6 {We are going to play either ... Nc4 or ... Nd3 , which instantly recovers our lost Pawn and maintains complete equality.} *

