1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 ({Capturing on e4 directly started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. The difference between this and} 7... Nc6 {is mainly that Black does not commit his Knight to c6 yet. As recent games have shown, this is a more flexible way for Black to play. In this variation, White does not get the opportunity to weaken our Queenside Pawn structure with Bxc6 . This point is clearly in Black's favour.}) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 {A logical move threatening both the e4 and f7 -Pawns.} Be6 {Again a typical way of defending the f7 Pawn. We are not afraid of an exchange on e6 , even though it ruins our Pawn structure. Black's plan is to play ... Bb4 followed by ... Ke7 next.} 10. Nxe6+ {This could be White's best bet to go for the initiative. They are not interested in winning the e4 -Pawn immediately. By exchanging on e6 , they first weaken Black's Pawn structure. Next, White will slowly go after the e4 -Pawn with the aim of recovering it and having a nice little edge in the endgame because of our weak structure.} fxe6 {Now, just like in the previous chapter, our idea is to play ... Bb4 and then ... Ke7 , followed by bringing our remaining Pieces in play.} 11. Bb5 {This was tried in only one game till now by GM Sarana. The idea is to play against the development of our Knight to c6 . But this allows us to develop our BIshop actively and then arrange our Pieces optimally without any problems.} Bb4 {... Ke7 is coming up next.} 12. Bd2 {White unpins the Knight and threatens to win the e4 -Pawn. However, giving back the extra Pawn does not bother us. We improve the position of our King and focus on coordinating our Pieces.} Ke7 13. Nxe4 Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 {And now, we prepare to develop our b8 -Knight by kicking White's Bishop.} a6 {A useful move that we have seen time and again in previous chapters.} 15. Bc4 Nc6 {Black's little weakness on e6 is easily manageable. We have seen such positions in previous chapters as well. There is nothing to worry about for Black in this position. We are rock-solid, and this endgame should comfortably end in a draw, as happened in 17 moves in the game (82) Sarana,A (2640)-Petrov,N (2552) Anapa RUS 2021.} *

