1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 ({Capturing on e4 directly started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. The difference between this and} 7... Nc6 {is mainly that Black does not commit his Knight to c6 yet. As recent games have shown, this is a more flexible way for Black to play. In this variation, White does not get the opportunity to weaken our Queenside Pawn structure with Bxc6 . This point is clearly in Black's favour.}) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 {A logical move threatening both the e4 and f7 -Pawns.} Be6 {Again a typical way of defending the f7 Pawn. We are not afraid of an exchange on e6 , even though it ruins our Pawn structure. Black's plan is to play ... Bb4 followed by ... Ke7 next.} 10. Nxe6+ {This could be White's best bet to go for the initiative. They are not interested in winning the e4 -Pawn immediately. By exchanging on e6 , they first weaken Black's Pawn structure. Next, White will slowly go after the e4 -Pawn with the aim of recovering it and having a nice little edge in the endgame because of our weak structure.} fxe6 {Now, just like in the previous chapter, our idea is to play ... Bb4 and then ... Ke7 , followed by bringing our remaining Pieces in play.} 11. Bd2 {A prophylactic measure against ... Bb4 . At the same time, White prepares to castle long.} Bb4 {Going for this move nevertheless is the simplest and the best for Black. We should not be worried about giving back our extra Pawn. Rather, our focus is to trade the dark-squared Bishops and bring our undeveloped pieces into play.} (11... Nc6 {was played by GM Le, but he quickly got into trouble after} 12. O-O-O Ke8 13. Bb5 Rc8 14. Rhe1 Kf7 15. Kb1 Nd4 16. Bf1 Be7 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Rxe4 {and White won in 61 moves in Giri, A (2764)-Le Quang Liem (2709) chess24.com INT 2020.}) 12. Nxe4 Bxd2+ {We dispose of White's Bishop pair.} 13. Nxd2 Nc6 {This Knight has a juicy square on d4 .} 14. Rc1 Rc8 15. Bb5 {And now, a simple move.} Nd4 {Black is fine.} *

