1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 ({Capturing on e4 directly started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. The difference between this and} 7... Nc6 {is mainly that Black does not commit his Knight to c6 yet. As recent games have shown, this is a more flexible way for Black to play. In this variation, White does not get the opportunity to weaken our Queenside Pawn structure with Bxc6 . This point is clearly in Black's favour.}) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 {A logical move threatening both the e4 and f7 -Pawns.} Be6 {Again a typical way of defending the f7 Pawn. We are not afraid of an exchange on e6 , even though it ruins our Pawn structure. Black's plan is to play ... Bb4 followed by ... Ke7 next.} 10. Nxe6+ {This could be White's best bet to go for the initiative. They are not interested in winning the e4 -Pawn immediately. By exchanging on e6 , they first weaken Black's Pawn structure. Next, White will slowly go after the e4 -Pawn with the aim of recovering it and having a nice little edge in the endgame because of our weak structure.} fxe6 {Now, just like in the previous chapter, our idea is to play ... Bb4 and then ... Ke7 , followed by bringing our remaining Pieces in play.} 11. Bc4 {White attacks the e6 -Pawn and prepares O-O .} Ke7 {We simply defend the Pawn. At this moment, our King blocks the development of the f8 -Bishop. But this is just a matter of one move. Next, we would like to play ... Kf7 and free our Bishop.} 12. Bg5 {This is also met by the same move as castling.} Kf7 13. O-O-O Nbd7 {We are prepared to recapture on f6 with our Knight, thus making it tough for White to recover the e4 -Pawn. We also intend to play ... Rc8 next.} (13... Bb4 {is a valid alternative.}) 14. Kb1 {Getting away from the c -file.} Rc8 15. Bb3 Nc5 {A typical Knight manuouvre from b8 - d7 - c5 . We chase White's light-squared Bishop while providing additional support to our e4 -Pawn.} 16. Bc2 Be7 {Finally, our Rooks are connected. The best White can do now is to regain the e4 -Pawn.} 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Rc7 {We have opposite-coloured Bishops on the board, and the position is completely equal. The game Mamedyarov,S (2770)-Paravyan,D (2647) lichess.org INT 2020 ended in a draw in 55 moves.} *

