1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 ({Capturing on e4 directly started trending when GM Wesley So tried it in some of his games. The difference between this and} 7... Nc6 {is mainly that Black does not commit his Knight to c6 yet. As recent games have shown, this is a more flexible way for Black to play. In this variation, White does not get the opportunity to weaken our Queenside Pawn structure with Bxc6 . This point is clearly in Black's favour.}) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 {A logical move threatening both the e4 and f7 -Pawns.} Be6 {Again a typical way of defending the f7 Pawn. We are not afraid of an exchange on e6 , even though it ruins our Pawn structure. Black's plan is to play ... Bb4 followed by ... Ke7 next.} 10. Nxe6+ {This could be White's best bet to go for the initiative. They are not interested in winning the e4 -Pawn immediately. By exchanging on e6 , they first weaken Black's Pawn structure. Next, White will slowly go after the e4 -Pawn with the aim of recovering it and having a nice little edge in the endgame because of our weak structure.} fxe6 {Now, just like in the previous chapter, our idea is to play ... Bb4 and then ... Ke7 , followed by bringing our remaining Pieces in play.} 11. Bc4 {White attacks the e6 -Pawn and prepares O-O .} Ke7 {We simply defend the Pawn. At this moment, our King blocks the development of the f8 -Bishop. But this is just a matter of one move. Next, we would like to play ... Kf7 and free our Bishop.} 12. O-O {White completes their Kingside development and will focus on creating pressure on our position.} Kf7 {We free the path of our Bishop to go to the b4 -square.} 13. Nb5 {White decides to create a little discomfort for us by threatening Nc7 , but we can easily parry that.} Na6 14. Be3 {Threatening the a7 -Pawn.} Bc5 {Exchanging the dark-squared Bishops is one of our strategies in this endgame. We eliminate White's Bishop pair.} 15. Bxc5 Nxc5 16. b4 Na6 17. a3 {By playing b4 and a3 , White has managed to push our Knight on the edge of the board on a6 , but we have a simple move.} Ke7 {Covering the d6 -square. Black was doing OK and he drew this endgame comfortably in 44 moves in the game Spartinos,P (2357)-Baranowski,T (2359) ICCF email 2015.} *

