[PlyCount "29"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 {White pins the f6 -Knight and prepares to capture the e4 -Pawn with Nxe4 . By developing his dark-squared Bishop, White also prepares to play O-O-O on the next move. Now, there are two ways for Black to proceed: 11...h6 and 11...Nc6 . Both are doing quite fine at top-level chess.} {h6 keeps the game open, and you will have to keep playing as there is no direct draw. The endgame is equal, and the game should logically end in a draw. But you may also get a few chances to outplay your opponent in case he misplays the endgame or over-pushes it. Nc6 is like killing the game to a draw. There are numerous games between top GMs where Black ends up in an opposite-coloured Bishop endgame, a Pawn down. But that endgame is quite easy to hold to a draw. In this chapter, we will be studying the move h6 , while in the next one,  we will focus on the other main alternative, Nc6 .} Bb4 {We would love to play this counter-pinning move as we did in some instances in previous chapters, but here, White can unpin the Knight with a check.} 12. O-O-O+ Ke8 {Now, White can execute a tactical shot:} 13. Nxe4 ({Suddenly, the initiative is on White's side as he is creating threats on every move. Surprisingly, this shot was missed by two strong grandmasters in their game.} 13. Bxf6 {was played in Sjugirov, S (2703)-Harikrishna, P (2696) Chennai IND 2023, draw in 42 moves.}) 13... Kf7 (13... Nxe4 {does not help Black due to} 14. Rd8+ Kf7 15. Rxh8 Nxg5 {and now after the simple} 16. Bd3 {, White has a winning position due to the killer pressure along the 8th Rank. The h8 -Rook ties down both the b8 -Knight and the a8 -Rook.}) 14. Nxf6 gxf6 15. Be3 {White has an almost winning advantage. First of all, White has a Bishop pair, and Black's structure is weak. Secondly, Black cannot develop his b8 -Knight because of Rd7 +. So, Black will find it tough to bring his Pieces into the game.} *

