1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 {White pins the f6 -Knight and prepares to capture the e4 -Pawn with Nxe4 . By developing his dark-squared Bishop, White also prepares to play O-O-O on the next move. Now, there are two ways for Black to proceed: 11...h6 and 11...Nc6 . Both are doing quite fine at top-level chess.} {h6 keeps the game open, and you will have to keep playing as there is no direct draw. The endgame is equal, and the game should logically end in a draw. But you may also get a few chances to outplay your opponent in case he misplays the endgame or over-pushes it. Nc6 is like killing the game to a draw. There are numerous games between top GMs where Black ends up in an opposite-coloured Bishop endgame, a Pawn down. But that endgame is quite easy to hold to a draw. In this chapter, we will be studying the move h6 , while in the next one,  we will focus on the other main alternative, Nc6 .} h6 {By playing ... h6 , we force White to make a decision with his Bishop on g5 . Once White decides how to respond to the threat to his Bishop, we can start bringing our Pieces out in the battle.} 12. O-O-O+ {It makes sense to make this useful move before deciding the fate of their dark-squared Bishop.} Ke8 ({This looks more logical but is worse than} 12... Ke7 {. Let's see why:}) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Bc4 ({White focuses on developing his Pieces hurriedly so that he can exploit Black's weak King position.} 14. Nxe4 {hitting the f6 -Pawn also works fine for White.} f5 15. Nc3 {The Knight simply retreats, and White can focus on hitting Black's weak pawns.} Nc6 16. Bc4 {hitting the e6 -pawn.} e5 17. f4 {A strong move that fixes Black's Pawn on f5 so that it can be attacked comfortably. White also aims to open up lines against our King.}) 14... Kf7 {Now comes a surprising but a powerful move.} 15. f4 {White threatens f5 winning the e6 -Pawn.} f5 (15... exf3 {is obviously met by} 16. Rhe1 {hitting the e6 -Pawn.} fxg2 $2 {loses to} 17. Bxe6+ Kg7 18. Re2 {, and Black's King is in danger of getting mated. Or} Nc6 {Rxe6 threatening Rxc6 . Kg6 gxf3+- when the material is equal, but Black's King is going to suffer.}) 16. g4 {White desperately wants to open up the position as quickly as possible!} fxg4 17. f5 Kg7 18. Bxe6 {When White has a winning advantage as Black is far behind in development and White's Pieces are dominating.} *

