1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 {White pins the f6 -Knight and prepares to capture the e4 -Pawn with Nxe4 . By developing his dark-squared Bishop, White also prepares to play O-O-O on the next move. Now, there are two ways for Black to proceed: 11...h6 and 11...Nc6 . Both are doing quite fine at top-level chess.} {h6 keeps the game open, and you will have to keep playing as there is no direct draw. The endgame is equal, and the game should logically end in a draw. But you may also get a few chances to outplay your opponent in case he misplays the endgame or over-pushes it. Nc6 is like killing the game to a draw. There are numerous games between top GMs where Black ends up in an opposite-coloured Bishop endgame, a Pawn down. But that endgame is quite easy to hold to a draw. In this chapter, we will be studying the move h6 , while in the next one,  we will focus on the other main alternative, Nc6 .} h6 {By playing ... h6 , we force White to make a decision with his Bishop on g5 . Once White decides how to respond to the threat to his Bishop, we can start bringing our Pieces out in the battle.} 12. O-O-O+ {It makes sense to make this useful move before deciding the fate of their dark-squared Bishop.} Ke7 {This might seem like an illogical move as it blocks the path of the f8 -Bishop. But it is important to place the King on e7 rather than on e8 . The point is that, from the e7 -square, our King defends both the e6 and f6 -Pawns (after White exchanges on f6 and Black recaptures back with ... gxf6 ). By defending our Pawns beforehand, we save an important tempo that we can utilise in developing our Pieces. Now, White has to choose a destiny for their Bishop.} 13. Be3 {White can preserve the Bishop, but now we get time to develop our Pieces. We start with our Knight.} Nc6 {We would like to play ... Kf7 and open up our Bishop next.} 14. g3 {An interesting idea that was tried by GM Radjabov against GM So. White intends to fianchetto his Bishop and regain the e4 -Pawn.} Ng4 {This knight jump guarantees an exchange of White's Bishop for our Knight. This way, we ensure that White does not keep the Bishop pair, which is one main trump in this endgame.} (14... Rc8 {was played by GM So in his game against GM Radjabov. It is also a playable alternative, but it might give White some minute chances after} 15. Kb1 Ng4 16. Bh3 {with pressure on the h3 - c8 diagonal.} Nxe3 17. fxe3 {, and the Rook on c8 is actually misplaced as White has additional options like Nd5 +.}) 15. Re1 {White prepares to recapture on e3 with his Rook, keeping his pawn structure intact.} g5 {A typical move that we have witnessed in previous variations. We intend to play ... Bg7 .} 16. Nxe4 Nxe3 17. Rxe3 Rc8 18. Kb1 Bg7 {Black's Pawn structure is slightly weak because the e6 -Pawn is isolated. But our Knight has a firm outpost on d4 from where it comfortably defends the e6 -Pawn. The presence of opposite-coloured Bishops gives this endgame a highly drawish nature.} *

