1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 {White pins the f6 -Knight and prepares to capture the e4 -Pawn with Nxe4 . By developing his dark-squared Bishop, White also prepares to play O-O-O on the next move. Now, there are two ways for Black to proceed: 11...h6 and 11...Nc6 . Both are doing quite fine at top-level chess.} {h6 keeps the game open, and you will have to keep playing as there is no direct draw. The endgame is equal, and the game should logically end in a draw. But you may also get a few chances to outplay your opponent in case he misplays the endgame or over-pushes it. Nc6 is like killing the game to a draw. There are numerous games between top GMs where Black ends up in an opposite-coloured Bishop endgame, a Pawn down. But that endgame is quite easy to hold to a draw. In this chapter, we will be studying the move h6 , while in the next one,  we will focus on the other main alternative, Nc6 .} h6 {By playing ... h6 , we force White to make a decision with his Bishop on g5 . Once White decides how to respond to the threat to his Bishop, we can start bringing our Pieces out in the battle.} 12. O-O-O+ {It makes sense to make this useful move before deciding the fate of their dark-squared Bishop.} Ke7 {This might seem like an illogical move as it blocks the path of the f8 -Bishop. But it is important to place the King on e7 rather than on e8 . The point is that, from the e7 -square, our King defends both the e6 and f6 -Pawns (after White exchanges on f6 and Black recaptures back with ... gxf6 ). By defending our Pawns beforehand, we save an important tempo that we can utilise in developing our Pieces. Now, White has to choose a destiny for their Bishop.} 13. Bh4 {This maintains the pin on the f6 -Knight, and White still threatens to capture the e4 -Pawn. The inclusion of ... h6 and Bh4 is in Black's favour because we can play ... g5 whenever required, kicking White's Bishop further.} Kf7 {Unpinning the f6 -Knight, which also opens up our f8 -Bishop.} 14. a3 {Prevents ... Bb4 , but this move is easy to meet.} Be7 15. Bc4 {This is bad:} Rc8 16. Ba2 g5 17. Bg3 Bxa3 {Black wins another Pawn. Instead of finding ways to gain the initiative, White should first find ways to maintain balance in this position.} *

