of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board, which creates high probabilities for a draw. Our first priority is to focus on developing our minor Pieces.} Bg7 {Black develops his Bishop and intends to play ... f5 next. This would drive White's Knight away from the centre and further open up our Bishop.} 15. Nd6 {With this, White attacks our b7 -Pawn. But unlike 14...f5 , we are better equipped to meet this move as our Bishop has already been developed on g7 .} Rd8 {Inviting White to capture the b7 -Pawn.} 16. Nxb7 Rxd1+ 17. Kxd1 Nc6 {White has won a Pawn, but surprisingly it is they who are behind in development. Their Rook and Bishop have yet to participate in the game, while the King is oddly placed on d1 . Black simply threatens to play ... Rb8 and win the b2 -Pawn.} 18. Nc5 Rb8 19. b3 f5 {We are all set to activate the Bishop with ... Bd4 .} 20. Bc4 {Targeting the e6 -Pawn.} Ne5 {An energetic move counter-attacking White's Bishop.} 21. Re1 Nxc4 {Exchanging on c4 also opens up the b -file.} 22. bxc4 Rb1+ 23. Ke2 Rb2+ 24. Kf3 e5 {Our e -Pawn is now safe, and we look forward to winning the a2 -Pawn.} 25. Re2 {This is a blunder.} e4+ 26. Ke3 f4+ {And Black wins the Rook.} *

