1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 {White pins the f6 -Knight and prepares to capture the e4 -Pawn with Nxe4 . By developing his dark-squared Bishop, White also prepares to play O-O-O on the next move. Now, there are two ways for Black to proceed: 11...h6 and 11...Nc6 . Both are doing quite fine at top-level chess.} {h6 keeps the game open, and you will have to keep playing as there is no direct draw. The endgame is equal, and the game should logically end in a draw. But you may also get a few chances to outplay your opponent in case he misplays the endgame or over-pushes it. Nc6 is like killing the game to a draw. There are numerous games between top GMs where Black ends up in an opposite-coloured Bishop endgame, a Pawn down. But that endgame is quite easy to hold to a draw. In this chapter, we will be studying the move h6 , while in the next one,  we will focus on the other main alternative, Nc6 .} h6 {By playing ... h6 , we force White to make a decision with his Bishop on g5 . Once White decides how to respond to the threat to his Bishop, we can start bringing our Pieces out in the battle.} 12. O-O-O+ {It makes sense to make this useful move before deciding the fate of their dark-squared Bishop.} Ke7 {This might seem like an illogical move as it blocks the path of the f8 -Bishop. But it is important to place the King on e7 rather than on e8 . The point is that, from the e7 -square, our King defends both the e6 and f6 -Pawns (after White exchanges on f6 and Black recaptures back with ... gxf6 ). By defending our Pawns beforehand, we save an important tempo that we can utilise in developing our Pieces. Now, White has to choose a destiny for their Bishop.} 13. Bxf6+ {White eliminates the f6 -Knight and decides to regain his Pawn immediately.} gxf6 14. Nxe4 {Finally, White regains his Pawn. Black's Kingside structure is a bit weak, but it is inconsequential. There is a presence of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board, which creates high probabilities for a draw. Our first priority is to focus on developing our minor Pieces.} Bg7 {Black develops his Bishop and intends to play ... f5 next. This would drive White's Knight away from the centre and further open up our Bishop.} 15. Nd6 {With this, White attacks our b7 -Pawn. But unlike 14...f5 , we are better equipped to meet this move as our Bishop has already been developed on g7 .} Rd8 {Inviting White to capture the b7 -Pawn.} 16. Nxb7 Rxd1+ 17. Kxd1 Nc6 {White has won a Pawn, but surprisingly it is they who are behind in development. Their Rook and Bishop have yet to participate in the game, while the King is oddly placed on d1 . Black simply threatens to play ... Rb8 and win the b2 -Pawn.} 18. Nc5 Rb8 19. b3 f5 {We are all set to activate the Bishop with ... Bd4 .} 20. Bc4 {Targeting the e6 -Pawn.} Ne5 {An energetic move counter-attacking White's Bishop.} 21. Bxe6 {White wins a Pawn but gives us an opportunity to repeat.} Kd6 (21... Rb5 $6 {is slightly inferior because of} 22. b4 $1 Rxb4 23. Bxf5 {White is two pawns up at the moment, though this endgame would most probably end in a draw as White's Pieces are uncoordinated, and Black will win the a2 -Pawn.}) 22. Na6 Rb6 23. Bc8 {Now, we can force a repetition.} Rc6 24. Bb7 Rb6 25. Bc8 Rc6 {With a draw.} *

