1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 {White pins the f6 -Knight and prepares to capture the e4 -Pawn with Nxe4 . By developing his dark-squared Bishop, White also prepares to play O-O-O on the next move. Now, there are two ways for Black to proceed: 11...h6 and 11...Nc6 . Both are doing quite fine at top-level chess.} {h6 keeps the game open, and you will have to keep playing as there is no direct draw. The endgame is equal, and the game should logically end in a draw. But you may also get a few chances to outplay your opponent in case he misplays the endgame or over-pushes it. Nc6 is like killing the game to a draw. There are numerous games between top GMs where Black ends up in an opposite-coloured Bishop endgame, a Pawn down. But that endgame is quite easy to hold to a draw. In this chapter, we will be studying the move h6 , while in the next one,  we will focus on the other main alternative, Nc6 .} h6 {By playing ... h6 , we force White to make a decision with his Bishop on g5 . Once White decides how to respond to the threat to his Bishop, we can start bringing our Pieces out in the battle.} 12. O-O-O+ {It makes sense to make this useful move before deciding the fate of their dark-squared Bishop.} Ke7 {This might seem like an illogical move as it blocks the path of the f8 -Bishop. But it is important to place the King on e7 rather than on e8 . The point is that, from the e7 -square, our King defends both the e6 and f6 -Pawns (after White exchanges on f6 and Black recaptures back with ... gxf6 ). By defending our Pawns beforehand, we save an important tempo that we can utilise in developing our Pieces. Now, White has to choose a destiny for their Bishop.} 13. Bxf6+ {White eliminates the f6 -Knight and decides to regain his Pawn immediately.} gxf6 14. Nxe4 {Finally, White regains his Pawn. Black's Kingside structure is a bit weak, but it is inconsequential. There is a presence of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board, which creates high probabilities for a draw. Our first priority is to focus on developing our minor Pieces.} Bg7 {Black develops his Bishop and intends to play ... f5 next. This would drive White's Knight away from the centre and further open up our Bishop.} 15. Bd3 Nc6 ({It is better to bring our Pieces quickly into the game.} 15... f5 {is quite possible as well. After} 16. Ng3 Nc6 {, we arrive at a position which was played in 4 games. Black managed to draw in all 4 of them, but I prefer not to enter the endgame that we get in this line since it may be uncomfortable for some. Also, Black needs to dodge many bullets to get to that. I have analysed and presented it in the following informational section starting here for your reference, though. You can check it out, and if you are fine with this line, then you can surely play it in your games.}) 16. Rhe1 Rhd8 ({We bring our Rook on the open file, keeping the c8 -square free for the other Rook. Once again, we are delaying ...f5 since} 16... f5 17. Ng3 {transposes to a variation analysed in the informational.}) 17. Nc5 {Threatening the e6 -Pawn can be met as follows:} Rac8 {We bring our last piece in action creating counter-threats on the c -file.} 18. Nxe6 {This loses immediately.} Nd4+ 19. Kb1 Nxe6 {We are a clean Piece up.} *

