of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board, which creates high probabilities for a draw. Our first priority is to focus on developing our minor Pieces.} Bg7 {Black develops his Bishop and intends to play ... f5 next. This would drive White's Knight away from the centre and further open up our Bishop.} 15. Bd3 Nc6 ({It is better to bring our Pieces quickly into the game.} 15... f5 {is quite possible as well. After} 16. Ng3 Nc6 {, we arrive at a position which was played in 4 games. Black managed to draw in all 4 of them, but I prefer not to enter the endgame that we get in this line since it may be uncomfortable for some. Also, Black needs to dodge many bullets to get to that. I have analysed and presented it in the following informational section starting here for your reference, though. You can check it out, and if you are fine with this line, then you can surely play it in your games.}) 16. Rhe1 Rhd8 ({We bring our Rook on the open file, keeping the c8 -square free for the other Rook. Once again, we are delaying ...f5 since} 16... f5 17. Ng3 {transposes to a variation analysed in the informational.}) 17. Nc5 {Threatening the e6 -Pawn can be met as follows:} Rac8 {We bring our last piece in action creating counter-threats on the c -file.} 18. Rxe6+ {This is bad, too, but gives White a chance to escape in the end.} Kf8 ({Not} 18... Kf7 $2 {due to} 19. Bc4 $1) 19. Bc2 {The only way to face the threats along the c -file.} Rxd1+ 20. Kxd1 Nd4 {It seems we are winning material, but White has a chance to escape.} 21. Re4 f5 {Defending as well as attacking!} 22. Rxd4 Bxd4 23. Ne6+ Ke7 24. Nxd4 Rd8 25. Bxf5 Rxd4+ {We are an exchange up, but White has two Pawns and a Bishop for it. The material is balanced, but White's Pawns are far behind at the moment, and the Rook might prove to be slightly stronger.} *

