of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board, which creates high probabilities for a draw. Our first priority is to focus on developing our minor Pieces.} Bg7 {Black develops his Bishop and intends to play ... f5 next. This would drive White's Knight away from the centre and further open up our Bishop.} 15. Bd3 Nc6 ({It is better to bring our Pieces quickly into the game.} 15... f5 {is quite possible as well. After} 16. Ng3 Nc6 {, we arrive at a position which was played in 4 games. Black managed to draw in all 4 of them, but I prefer not to enter the endgame that we get in this line since it may be uncomfortable for some. Also, Black needs to dodge many bullets to get to that. I have analysed and presented it in the following informational section starting here for your reference, though. You can check it out, and if you are fine with this line, then you can surely play it in your games.}) 16. Rhe1 Rhd8 ({We bring our Rook on the open file, keeping the c8 -square free for the other Rook. Once again, we are delaying ...f5 since} 16... f5 17. Ng3 {transposes to a variation analysed in the informational.}) 17. Nc5 {Threatening the e6 -Pawn can be met as follows:} Rac8 {We bring our last piece in action creating counter-threats on the c -file.} 18. Kb1 {Getting away from the threats along the c -file.} Ne5 {We block the threat to the e6 -Pawn while creating threats of our own.} 19. Nxe6 Kxe6 20. f4 {This allows White to regain their Piece.} Ke7 {Simple, getting away from potential checks.} 21. fxe5 fxe5 {The material is balanced and the presence of opposite-coloured Bishops means the game will likely end in a draw.} *

