1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 {White pins the f6 -Knight and prepares to capture the e4 -Pawn with Nxe4 . By developing his dark-squared Bishop, White also prepares to play O-O-O on the next move. Now, there are two ways for Black to proceed: 11...h6 and 11...Nc6 . Both are doing quite fine at top-level chess.} {h6 keeps the game open, and you will have to keep playing as there is no direct draw. The endgame is equal, and the game should logically end in a draw. But you may also get a few chances to outplay your opponent in case he misplays the endgame or over-pushes it. Nc6 is like killing the game to a draw. There are numerous games between top GMs where Black ends up in an opposite-coloured Bishop endgame, a Pawn down. But that endgame is quite easy to hold to a draw. In this chapter, we will be studying the move h6 , while in the next one,  we will focus on the other main alternative, Nc6 .} h6 {By playing ... h6 , we force White to make a decision with his Bishop on g5 . Once White decides how to respond to the threat to his Bishop, we can start bringing our Pieces out in the battle.} 12. O-O-O+ {It makes sense to make this useful move before deciding the fate of their dark-squared Bishop.} Ke7 {This might seem like an illogical move as it blocks the path of the f8 -Bishop. But it is important to place the King on e7 rather than on e8 . The point is that, from the e7 -square, our King defends both the e6 and f6 -Pawns (after White exchanges on f6 and Black recaptures back with ... gxf6 ). By defending our Pawns beforehand, we save an important tempo that we can utilise in developing our Pieces. Now, White has to choose a destiny for their Bishop.} 13. Bxf6+ {White eliminates the f6 -Knight and decides to regain his Pawn immediately.} gxf6 14. Nxe4 {Finally, White regains his Pawn. Black's Kingside structure is a bit weak, but it is inconsequential. There is a presence of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board, which creates high probabilities for a draw. Our first priority is to focus on developing our minor Pieces.} Bg7 {Black develops his Bishop and intends to play ... f5 next. This would drive White's Knight away from the centre and further open up our Bishop.} 15. Bd3 f5 {This is quite possible as well.} 16. Ng3 Nc6 {We arrive at a position which was played in 4 games. Black managed to draw in all 4 of them, but I prefer not to enter the endgame that we get in this line since it may be uncomfortable for some. Also, Black needs to dodge many bullets to get to that. I have analysed and presented it here for your reference, though. You can check it out, and if you are fine with this line, then you can surely play it in your games.} 17. Rhe1 {White creates pressure on our Pawns. White's obvious threat is to gobble up the f5 -Pawn, so we should address it.} Be5 ({Blocking the e -file. A simple defensive move like} 17... Kf7 $2 {does not work due to} 18. Bc4 $1 {targeting the e6 -Pawn.} Ne5 19. Nxf5 $1 {is crushing, and Nd4 is met by Bxe6! White gets these tactical opportunities as he is clearly ahead in development. Nxe6 Rd7+} Kf6 {Nh5+ Kg6 Rxe6+ Kxh5 Rxg7+- , and White is winning in this double Rook endgame.}) 18. Nxf5+ {A nice tactical idea that opens up the e -file.} exf5 19. f4 Rad8 ({Finally, our Rooks join the action! Black's most logical move would be} 19... Kf6 $2 {, but, unfortunately, it falls short to} 20. fxe5+ Nxe5 21. Bc2 $1 {threatening Rd6 +. If we try to stop it with} Rad8 {, then White goes after the f5 -Pawn with} 22. Rf1 {and wins it.}) 20. fxe5 (20. Bxf5 $4 {is too greedy and loses to} Kf6 $1 {unpinning and hitting the Bishop.}) 20... Rhf8 {We have managed to bring both our Rooks into the game. Now, it is all about pressurising the e5 -Pawn.} 21. Bc4 ({This prevents Black from playing ...Rd5 , so it is definitely worth considering. We can respond with} 21. Bc2 {has the same idea of preventing ... Rd5 as 21.Bc4 .} Rxd1+ 22. Kxd1 Rg8 {Provoking White to play g3 .} 23. g3 Rd8+ 24. Kc1 {, and now we can activate our Knight with} Nd4 {The Knight protects the f5 -Pawn.} 25. Bd3 Rc8+ $1 {It is essential to cover the c4 -square before playing ... Ke6 so that White does not have the option of playing Bc4 +.} 26. Kd1 Ke6 {with the idea of ... Rc5 and ... Rxe5 . Black is doing completely fine in this endgame.}) 21... Rxd1+ 22. Kxd1 Rd8+ 23. Kc2 {And now comes an important move.} b5 {Kicking the Bishop from its active c4 -square.} 24. Bf1 a6 {Protecting the b5 -pawn in advance.} 25. Re3 Ke6 {The e5 -Pawn is clearly within reach now, and White has not gained anything tangible in the meantime. The position is equal.} *

