of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board, which creates high probabilities for a draw. Our first priority is to focus on developing our minor Pieces.} Bg7 {Black develops his Bishop and intends to play ... f5 next. This would drive White's Knight away from the centre and further open up our Bishop.} 15. Bd3 f5 {This is quite possible as well.} 16. Ng3 Nc6 {We arrive at a position which was played in 4 games. Black managed to draw in all 4 of them, but I prefer not to enter the endgame that we get in this line since it may be uncomfortable for some. Also, Black needs to dodge many bullets to get to that. I have analysed and presented it here for your reference, though. You can check it out, and if you are fine with this line, then you can surely play it in your games.} 17. Rhe1 {White creates pressure on our Pawns. White's obvious threat is to gobble up the f5 -Pawn, so we should address it.} Be5 ({Blocking the e -file. A simple defensive move like} 17... Kf7 $2 {does not work due to} 18. Bc4 $1 {targeting the e6 -Pawn.} Ne5 19. Nxf5 $1 {is crushing, and Nd4 is met by Bxe6! White gets these tactical opportunities as he is clearly ahead in development. Nxe6 Rd7+} Kf6 {Nh5+ Kg6 Rxe6+ Kxh5 Rxg7+- , and White is winning in this double Rook endgame.}) 18. Nxf5+ {A nice tactical idea that opens up the e -file.} exf5 19. f4 Rad8 ({Finally, our Rooks join the action! Black's most logical move would be} 19... Kf6 $2 {, but, unfortunately, it falls short to} 20. fxe5+ Nxe5 21. Bc2 $1 {threatening Rd6 +. If we try to stop it with} Rad8 {, then White goes after the f5 -Pawn with} 22. Rf1 {and wins it.}) 20. fxe5 (20. Bxf5 $4 {is too greedy and loses to} Kf6 $1 {unpinning and hitting the Bishop.}) 20... Rhf8 {We have managed to bring both our Rooks into the game. Now, it is all about pressurising the e5 -Pawn.} 21. Re3 {A logical move. White decides to keep his Rook active so that it can swing on either side of the board.} Rd5 {We quickly target the e5 -Pawn. White's Pieces are not healthy enough to maintain the extra Pawn.} (21... Rd4 $6 {was Magnus's choice, but it was inferior, and he was worse in his game against GM Radjabov. But maybe he intended to play ... Rd5 and ... Rd4 was a result of a mouse slip? We'll never know! Radjabov,T (2765)-Carlsen,M (2847) chess24.com INT 2021 was a draw in 57 moves.}) 22. Rh3 Rfd8 {Tying White's Rooks to the defence of the d3 -Bishop. Black also threatens ... Nb4 next winning material.} ({This seems even simpler than} 22... Nxe5 {, which was GM Wesley's choice. Black is completely fine, and Radjabov, T (2765)-So, W (2770) chess24.com INT 2020 ended in a draw in 32 moves.}) 23. Bc2 {The most challenging move, getting away from the d3 -square on the first chance.} (23. Be2 {is met by} Rc5+ {pushing White's King further away before capturing the e5 -Pawn.} 24. Kb1 Rxe5 25. Rxd8 Kxd8 26. Bf3 {Now we can force a transition to a Rook endgame with} Re1+ $1 27. Kc2 Nd4+ 28. Kd2 Nxf3+ 29. Rxf3 Rg1 {or gxf3 Rb1} 30. Kc2 Rf1 {with a clearly equal Rook endgame thanks to our counterplay against White's weak Pawns.}) 23... Nd4 {Threatening ... Ne2 +.} 24. Kb1 Nxc2 25. Rxd5 Rxd5 26. Kxc2 {Now, we regain our sacrificed Pawn.} Rxe5 {We threaten ... Re2 +, which counterbalances the threat to our h6 -Pawn. If White defends against ... Re2 +, then we can simply play ... Re6 defending our h6 -Pawn. Black is doing completely fine in this endgame.} *

