of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board, which creates high probabilities for a draw. Our first priority is to focus on developing our minor Pieces.} Bg7 {Black develops his Bishop and intends to play ... f5 next. This would drive White's Knight away from the centre and further open up our Bishop.} 15. Kb1 {White moves his King away from the vulnerable c -file. Their idea is to play Bc4 next when they no longer need to worry about a pin along the c -file. After Bc4 , White can play Rhe1 , creating tremendous pressure on our pawns.} f5 {It is better to dislodge the e4 -Knight instantly. This also opens up our Bishop.} 16. Ng3 {We have a simple reply to this.} Nc6 {Finally, we complete the development of our minor pieces. It is time to bring out our Rooks next.} 17. Bc4 Rhd8 {We are looking forward to exchanging both the Rooks on the d -file.} 18. Rde1 {Threatens our Pawns while at the same time avoiding the exchange of Rooks. But it can be easily parried.} Nd4 19. Ne2 Rd6 {Our e6 -Pawn is comfortably guarded, and the endgame is completely equal.} *

