1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 {White pins the f6 -Knight and prepares to capture the e4 -Pawn with Nxe4 . By developing his dark-squared Bishop, White also prepares to play O-O-O on the next move. Now, there are two ways for Black to proceed: 11...h6 and 11...Nc6 . Both are doing quite fine at top-level chess.} {h6 keeps the game open, and you will have to keep playing as there is no direct draw. The endgame is equal, and the game should logically end in a draw. But you may also get a few chances to outplay your opponent in case he misplays the endgame or over-pushes it. Nc6 is like killing the game to a draw. There are numerous games between top GMs where Black ends up in an opposite-coloured Bishop endgame, a Pawn down. But that endgame is quite easy to hold to a draw. In this chapter, we will be studying the move h6 , while in the next one,  we will focus on the other main alternative, Nc6 .} h6 {By playing ... h6 , we force White to make a decision with his Bishop on g5 . Once White decides how to respond to the threat to his Bishop, we can start bringing our Pieces out in the battle.} 12. O-O-O+ {It makes sense to make this useful move before deciding the fate of their dark-squared Bishop.} Ke7 {This might seem like an illogical move as it blocks the path of the f8 -Bishop. But it is important to place the King on e7 rather than on e8 . The point is that, from the e7 -square, our King defends both the e6 and f6 -Pawns (after White exchanges on f6 and Black recaptures back with ... gxf6 ). By defending our Pawns beforehand, we save an important tempo that we can utilise in developing our Pieces. Now, White has to choose a destiny for their Bishop.} 13. Bxf6+ {White eliminates the f6 -Knight and decides to regain his Pawn immediately.} gxf6 14. Nxe4 {Finally, White regains his Pawn. Black's Kingside structure is a bit weak, but it is inconsequential. There is a presence of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board, which creates high probabilities for a draw. Our first priority is to focus on developing our minor Pieces.} Bg7 {Black develops his Bishop and intends to play ... f5 next. This would drive White's Knight away from the centre and further open up our Bishop.} 15. Ng3 {A nice prophylactic move. Black will sooner or later play ... f5 , kicking the Knight away from the centre. So White decides to move it beforehand. Secondly, White intends to play Nh5 creating some pressure.} h5 {Taking the h5 -square away from White's Knight. We also intend to play ... h4 next.} ({It may also be possible to play} 15... Nc6 $6 {, but we can come under pressure after} 16. Nh5 Rhg8 17. Bc4 {, and suddenly, White starts creating threats with their active Pieces.}) (15... f5 {is possible as well, but after} 16. Bd3 {, we transpose to the variation analysed in this informational. I think it is better if we can avoid entering the endgame from that variation whenever we have a better option.}) 16. h4 {White prevents our Kingside expansion and fixes our Pawn on h5 , which they will soon use as a target.} Nc6 17. Be2 Rad8 {We don't care about the h5 -Pawn. Rather, we focus on improving the quality of our Pieces. Now, our plan is to centralise our Knight on the attractive d4 -square.} 18. Bxh5 {This is calmly met.} f5 {Threatening to win a Piece with ... f4 next.} 19. Rxd8 Nxd8 {We can also recapture on d8 with our King or Rook, but recapturing with our Knight is fine, too. Once again, White needs to address our threat of ... f4 .} 20. Be2 (20. Bf3 {is a logical Bishop retreat, but now we can simply regain our Pawn with} Bd4 {.}) 20... Bd4 {Hitting the weak f2 -Pawn.} 21. f3 {White desperately tries to maintain his extra Pawn.} Rg8 {We will win the g2 -Pawn with a clearly better position due to the activity of our Pieces.} *

