1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 Nc6 {We simply develop our Knight and will decide to place our King on e7 or e8 , depending on how White responds.} 12. O-O-O+ {White castles and intends to develop his Kingside Pieces next. This is a critical line, as later, White sacrifices an exchange for initiative.} Ke8 {Keeping the f8 -Bishop open. Now, White has multiple ways to continue. Let's check them one by one.} ({Not} 12... Ke7 $6 {because of} 13. Nxe4 {when White enjoys a solid edge thanks to this better Pawn structure and Bishop pair.}) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Nxe4 {White wins their Pawn back but, as usual, after the exchanges on f6 we can relax since much pressure has evaporated.} Ke7 {Defending the f6 -Pawn and preparing to develop our Bishop from h6 , which will connect our Rooks.} (14... f5 {is possible as well. Aronian, L (2785)-Nepomniachtchi, I (2773) chess.com INT 2022 was a draw in 45 moves.}) 15. Kb1 (15. Nc5 {transposes after} Bh6+ 16. Kb1 Rhd8 {.}) 15... Bh6 {Our minor pieces are developed, and now it is time to bring our Rooks in action.} 16. Nc5 {The final attempt to create some threats.} Rhd8 {A typical idea. We look forward to exchanging both pairs of Rooks on the d -file.} 17. Bc4 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Rd8 19. Rxd8 {White is more or less forced to exchange Rooks. Otherwise, our Rook enters on d2 , creating a lot of pressure on the 2nd rank.} Nxd8 {Both our pawns on e6 and b7 are safe and this endgame is dead equal. Maghsoodloo,P (2719)-Suleymanli,A (2586) Baku AZE 2023 ended in a draw in 32 moves.} *

