1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 Nc6 {We simply develop our Knight and will decide to place our King on e7 or e8 , depending on how White responds.} 12. O-O-O+ {White castles and intends to develop his Kingside Pieces next. This is a critical line, as later, White sacrifices an exchange for initiative.} Ke8 {Keeping the f8 -Bishop open. Now, White has multiple ways to continue. Let's check them one by one.} ({Not} 12... Ke7 $6 {because of} 13. Nxe4 {when White enjoys a solid edge thanks to this better Pawn structure and Bishop pair.}) 13. Kb1 {White plays a useful preparatory move we have seen many times in previous variations. As usual, we develop our Bishop actively.} Bb4 14. Bxf6 {White goes for the e4 -Pawn before it is too late.} gxf6 15. Nxe4 Ke7 {Now our f6 -Pawn is safe and Rooks connected. Our plan is to bring our Rooks into action, but White will try to make it tough for us to do so by creating continuous threats.} 16. a3 Ba5 17. Nc5 {This is the critical attempt for White to play for an advantage. They threaten to capture our b7 -Pawn while also pressurising the pawn on e6 .} Rad8 ({We are looking forward to quickly exchanging Rooks, which releases a lot of pressure from our position.} 17... Rhd8 {would transpose after} 18. Bc4 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8 {.}) 18. Rc1 {Avoids exchanges but allows us to activate our Rook further.} Rd2 {Creating nice pressure along the 2nd rank.} 19. Nxb7 Rb8 20. Rxc6 Rxb7 21. Rc2 Rbd7 {Only Black could be slightly better in this endgame due to the activity of our Rooks.} *

