1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 Nc6 {We simply develop our Knight and will decide to place our King on e7 or e8 , depending on how White responds.} 12. O-O-O+ {White castles and intends to develop his Kingside Pieces next. This is a critical line, as later, White sacrifices an exchange for initiative.} Ke8 {Keeping the f8 -Bishop open. Now, White has multiple ways to continue. Let's check them one by one.} ({Not} 12... Ke7 $6 {because of} 13. Nxe4 {when White enjoys a solid edge thanks to this better Pawn structure and Bishop pair.}) 13. Bc4 {This is White's critical try for an advantage. They attack our e6 -Pawn and also intend to bring the Rook to e1 .} Ne5 {A nice counter-attacking move. We attack White's Bishop and intend to land on Knight on d3 with a check.} ({The 'logical'} 13... Kf7 $6 {is met by} 14. Rhe1 Be7 $6 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Rxe4 {when the e6 -Pawn comes under tremendous pressure.}) 14. Bb5+ {This is harmless.} Kf7 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Nxe4 {And now, a simple move.} Be7 {Connecting our Rooks. Black is doing completely fine in this endgame and drew in 22 moves in Artemiev,V (2701)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2793) Almaty KAZ 2022.} *

