1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 Nc6 {We simply develop our Knight and will decide to place our King on e7 or e8 , depending on how White responds.} 12. O-O-O+ {White castles and intends to develop his Kingside Pieces next. This is a critical line, as later, White sacrifices an exchange for initiative.} Ke8 {Keeping the f8 -Bishop open. Now, White has multiple ways to continue. Let's check them one by one.} ({Not} 12... Ke7 $6 {because of} 13. Nxe4 {when White enjoys a solid edge thanks to this better Pawn structure and Bishop pair.}) 13. Bc4 {This is White's critical try for an advantage. They attack our e6 -Pawn and also intend to bring the Rook to e1 .} Ne5 {A nice counter-attacking move. We attack White's Bishop and intend to land on Knight on d3 with a check.} ({The 'logical'} 13... Kf7 $6 {is met by} 14. Rhe1 Be7 $6 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Rxe4 {when the e6 -Pawn comes under tremendous pressure.}) 14. Bxe6 {White sacrifices the exchange to generate some initiative.} Nd3+ 15. Kc2 Nxf2 {We are all set to eliminate one of White's Rooks from the board. Mostly the Rook on d1 .} 16. Bxf6 {White needs to play energetically in order to prove compensation for the exchange. First, they get rid of the f6 -knight, which performed an important defensive role by covering some key squares in Black's camp.} Nxd1 {It is necessary to remember this move. Other captures are risky for us:} (16... Nxh1 $4 {is an outright blunder due to} 17. Nd5 $3 {shooting straight for our King. White is already winning, for example,} gxf6 18. Nc7+ Ke7 19. Rd7#) (16... gxf6 $2 {is also a grave error due to} 17. Rd7 $1 {the duo of Be6 and Rd7 are too powerful. They will soon be joined by their Knight as well.} Nxh1 18. Nd5 {with mating threats looming over Black's King, White claims a winning advantage.}) 17. Rxd1 gxf6 18. Nd5 {Jumping with the Knight before the Rook is a mistake.} Rd8 19. Nxf6+ Ke7 {White is forced to exchange Rooks, which gives us a winning endgame.} *

