1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 Nc6 {We simply develop our Knight and will decide to place our King on e7 or e8 , depending on how White responds.} 12. O-O-O+ {White castles and intends to develop his Kingside Pieces next. This is a critical line, as later, White sacrifices an exchange for initiative.} Ke8 {Keeping the f8 -Bishop open. Now, White has multiple ways to continue. Let's check them one by one.} ({Not} 12... Ke7 $6 {because of} 13. Nxe4 {when White enjoys a solid edge thanks to this better Pawn structure and Bishop pair.}) 13. Bc4 {This is White's critical try for an advantage. They attack our e6 -Pawn and also intend to bring the Rook to e1 .} Ne5 {A nice counter-attacking move. We attack White's Bishop and intend to land on Knight on d3 with a check.} ({The 'logical'} 13... Kf7 $6 {is met by} 14. Rhe1 Be7 $6 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Rxe4 {when the e6 -Pawn comes under tremendous pressure.}) 14. Bxe6 {White sacrifices the exchange to generate some initiative.} Nd3+ 15. Kc2 Nxf2 {We are all set to eliminate one of White's Rooks from the board. Mostly the Rook on d1 .} 16. Bxf6 {White needs to play energetically in order to prove compensation for the exchange. First, they get rid of the f6 -knight, which performed an important defensive role by covering some key squares in Black's camp.} Nxd1 {It is necessary to remember this move. Other captures are risky for us:} (16... Nxh1 $4 {is an outright blunder due to} 17. Nd5 $3 {shooting straight for our King. White is already winning, for example,} gxf6 18. Nc7+ Ke7 19. Rd7#) (16... gxf6 $2 {is also a grave error due to} 17. Rd7 $1 {the duo of Be6 and Rd7 are too powerful. They will soon be joined by their Knight as well.} Nxh1 18. Nd5 {with mating threats looming over Black's King, White claims a winning advantage.}) 17. Rxd1 gxf6 18. Rd7 {Black is an exchange up along with an extra Pawn. But our Pieces are scattered and White's active Pieces provide them with sufficient compensation. White threatens the deadly Nd5 next.} Rd8 {It is essential to immediately challenge White's active Rook and bring our Rook into action at the same time.} 19. Rxb7 ({White threatens Checkmate in 1 with} 19. Z0 {Bf7+ .}) 19... Rd6 {Another important move that kicks White's Bishop from the annoying e6 -square. We also vacate the e8 -square for our King.} 20. Bc4 {It is preferable to place the Bishop on c4 than b3 , since after capturing the a7 -Pawn, White would love to push his Queenside Pawns quickly with b2 - b4 and a2 - a4 . Now our e4 and a7 -Pawns are hanging.} (20. Bb3 $6 {is an inferior retreat as it blocks White's Queenside Pawns. Also, our e3 -Pawn can be a worry for White. For example,} e3 $1 {White needs to take care that the Pawn does not run away. Though he can try the aggressive} 21. Nd5 $5 {threatening the sneaky Ba4 +.} e2 $4 {loses to} 22. Ba4+ Kd8 23. Rb8#) ({The correct move is Bh6! defending our pawn while creating more room for our King. Now, White can liquidate to a drawn endgame after Nxf6+! Rxf6} 20. Rb8+ Ke7 {Rxh8 e2 Rxh7+ Kd6 Rxh6! Rxh6 Kd2 Rxh2 Kxe2 Rxg2+ Kd3 and now after Rxb2 Kd4= , this endgame is a theoretical draw. Though you can surely choose to torture your opponent for the next 50 moves :)}) 20... Rd4 {First, we defend the e4 -Pawn with a tempo.} 21. Bb5+ (21. Be6 {leads to a repetition after} Rd6 {.}) 21... Kd8 22. Rxa7 {White has two strong Queenside passed Pawns, but our Pawn on e3 counterbalances them.} Rg8 {Time to activate our sleeping Rook.} 23. g3 Rg5 {The position remains complex, but Black is doing fine. You can check this game in the model games section for further reference. Holt,C (2539)-Vitiugov,N (2719) Tromso NOR 2013 was 0-1 in 31 moves.} *

