1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 Nc6 {We simply develop our Knight and will decide to place our King on e7 or e8 , depending on how White responds.} 12. Bc4 {White first develops the Bishop with a threat. They still keep the suspense of which side to castle wide open.} Ke7 {We aim to transfer our King to a safer square while defending the e6 -Pawn at the same time.} 13. O-O-O {This is toothless.} Ne5 {A typical move that serves the dual purpose of attacking the c4 -Bishop and centralising our Knight.} ({We are accustomed to moving the King quickly to f7 in order to release our d8 -Bishop. But this is one of the rare situations where it backfires due to} 13... Kf7 $6 14. Rhe1 $1 {White intends to exchange on f6 followed by Rxe4 , which would pressurise the e6 -Pawn. For example,} Ne5 15. Bxf6 $1 gxf6 16. Rxe4 {, and White maintains a nice pressure thanks to their active Pieces.}) 14. Be2 Kf7 {With our centralised Knight on e5 , we don't need to worry about the infiltration of White's Rook on d7 . Next, we are all set to develop our Bishop.} 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Nxe4 f5 {Black immediately kicks the Knight away from the centre and enjoys a complete equality. The game Koneru,H (2553)-Ju,W (2568) Kolkata IND 2023 ended in a draw in 26 moves.} *

