anaged to squeeze water from a stone in the only game where Black lost. Such a high tendency for a draw clearly indicates that Black is safe. It is not going to be easy for White to create a passed Pawn on the Queenside. Moreover, we also have a chance to create a passed e -Pawn, which can provide sufficient counterplay. Here, White has two plans. First, they can just play f3 and save their f -Pawn. The second one is to sacrifice the f2 -Pawn in favour of attacking our e6 -Pawn. This would tie our Rook to its defence, and then White would give their best shot to quickly create a passed pawn along the b -file.} 22. f3 {It is evident from the games played that White does not value playing slowly like this.} h5 {Tthis frees our Rook to go to g8 .} 23. Rc7 Bg1 24. Rc6 {White decides to attack to the e6 -Pawn, intending to tie our Rook down to its defence. But here we can simply let them capture it.} Bxh2 25. Rxe6+ Kg5 {With fewer Pawns remaining on the board, the presence of opposite-coloured Bishops and the weakness of the g2 -Pawn, it would be a waste of time for White to hope to win this drawish endgame. Radjabov,T (2747)-Dominguez Perez,L (2739) Dubai UAE 2023 ended in a draw in 36 moves.} *

