anaged to squeeze water from a stone in the only game where Black lost. Such a high tendency for a draw clearly indicates that Black is safe. It is not going to be easy for White to create a passed Pawn on the Queenside. Moreover, we also have a chance to create a passed e -Pawn, which can provide sufficient counterplay. Here, White has two plans. First, they can just play f3 and save their f -Pawn. The second one is to sacrifice the f2 -Pawn in favour of attacking our e6 -Pawn. This would tie our Rook to its defence, and then White would give their best shot to quickly create a passed pawn along the b -file.} 22. Rc7 {Hitting our Bishop and aiming to go Rc6 .} Bxf2 23. Rc6 Re8 24. b4 {White lauches their Queenside pawns straight away. Now, Black has three ways to continue. 1) Place the King on e5 and manouevre the Bishop to d6 , getting rid of the pressure on the e6 -Pawn. This helps us free the Rook. See here.  2) Sacrifice the e6 -Pawn and exchange Rooks directly. See here.  3) Include ... Bg1 and h2 - h3 first, and then sacrifice the e6 -Pawn to exchange Rooks. I feel the third way is the most secure way to claim a draw and that is why I have included that one as the mainline. However, opting for the first two will draw the game as well.} (24. Kd2 {was tried in one top game by White but it did not make any difference. The game continued} Re7 25. b4 Ke5 26. Ke2 Bg1 27. h3 f4 {and now after} 28. Bb3 Kf5 {players repeated the position with} 29. Bc2+ Ke5 30. Bb3 Kf5 31. Bc2+ Ke5 32. Bb3 Kf5 {with a draw. Nguyen, T (2645)-Vidit, S (2724) Saint Louis USA 2022.}) 24... Bg1 ({Forcing White to push the Pawn to a light square, which will help us create a safe blockade on the dark squares. This is a typical theme we see in many opposite-coloured Bishop endgames. This is just a more technical subtlety. Black can very well just play} 24... Rb8 {directly and I offer it as an alternative.}) 25. h3 {Now, we sacrifice the e6 -Pawn in order to force an exchange of Rooks.} Rb8 {We