1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 Nc6 {We simply develop our Knight and will decide to place our King on e7 or e8 , depending on how White responds.} 12. Bc4 {White first develops the Bishop with a threat. They still keep the suspense of which side to castle wide open.} Ke7 {We aim to transfer our King to a safer square while defending the e6 -Pawn at the same time.} 13. Nxe4 Kf7 {Our king has reached the desired safe square on f7 . Now White's e4 -Knight hangs, and we are also ready to develop our dark-squared Bishop.} 14. Bxf6 {White exchanges on f6 with their Bishop, as they value it less than their Knight. It also does not lose time, and the e4 -Knight can used to create further pressure.} gxf6 15. O-O-O {White is confident that our Pieces are not quick enough to come in action to prevent White's threats. They are right in their assessment. But the presence of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board gives us great drawing chances. First, we should exchange a pair of Rooks to relieve some pressure of the position.} Rd8 16. Rxd8 Nxd8 17. Rd1 {White has managed to push our Knight to the 8th rank and once again threatens Rd7 +, along with, of course, just hitting our Knight.} Be7 {Our knight on d8 is now rock-solid. We also prevent a check on the 7th rank.} 18. Rd7 {The Rook enters our camp with confidence and high hopes of winning decisive material. Nd6 + is the immediate threat.} f5 {Yes, we invite White to execute their idea! Our point is that we vacate the f6 -square for our King, which will help us free our Bishop from the annoying pin on the 7th Rank. We are ready to sacrifice a Pawn betting on the fact that opposite-coloured Bishops will help us hold comfortably in this endgame.} 19. Nd6+ (19. Nc5 {leads to the same thing and transposes after} Kf6 20. Nxb7 {.}) 19... Kf6 20. Nxb7 Nxb7 21. Rxb7 Bc5 {11 games out of 12 have been drawn from this endgame. White miraculously managed to squeeze water from a stone in the only game where Black lost. Such a high tendency for a draw clearly indicates that Black is safe. It is not going to be easy for White to create a passed Pawn on the Queenside. Moreover, we also have a chance to create a passed e -Pawn, which can provide sufficient counterplay. Here, White has two plans. First, they can just play f3 and save their f -Pawn. The second one is to sacrifice the f2 -Pawn in favour of attacking our e6 -Pawn. This would tie our Rook to its defence, and then White would give their best shot to quickly create a passed pawn along the b -file.} 22. Rc7 {Hitting our Bishop and aiming to go Rc6 .} Bxf2 23. Rc6 Re8 24. b4 {White lauches their Queenside pawns straight away. Now, Black has three ways to continue. 1) Place the King on e5 and manouevre the Bishop to d6 , getting rid of the pressure on the e6 -Pawn. This helps us free the Rook. 2) Sacrifice the e6 -Pawn and exchange Rooks directly. 3) Include ... Bg1 and h2 - h3 first, and then sacrifice the e6 -Pawn to exchange Rooks. I feel the third way is the most secure way to claim a draw and that is why I have included that one as the mainline. However, opting for the first two will draw the game as well.} (24. Kd2 {was tried in one top game by White but it did not make any difference. The game continued} Re7 25. b4 Ke5 26. Ke2 Bg1 27. h3 f4 {and now after} 28. Bb3 Kf5 {players repeated the position with} 29. Bc2+ Ke5 30. Bb3 Kf5 31. Bc2+ Ke5 32. Bb3 Kf5 {with a draw. Nguyen, T (2645)-Vidit, S (2724) Saint Louis USA 2022.}) 24... Rb8 {This sacrifices the e6 -Pawn and more or less forces an exchange of Rooks. If White declines the sacrifice then we can simply play ... Rb6 next, kicking White's Rook away from the 6th Rank.} 25. Rxe6+ (25. a3 {is met by} Rb6 {.}) 25... Kg5 {Now we not only threaten to win the b4 -Pawn but also the c4 -Bishop with ... Rc8 .} 26. b5 {the only move that saves both of them.} Rc8 27. Rc6 Rxc6 28. bxc6 Bb6 {And this opposite-coloured Bishops endgame is a dead draw, as was proved by the games played here. I have added all of them for your reference.} ({h3} 28... f4 29. Bd5 h6 30. Kc2 Kf5 31. Bf3 Ke5 32. Be2 a5 33. Bf3 {Bc7 Kd3} Bb6 34. Be2 Kd5 35. Bf3+ Ke5 36. Be2 Kd5 37. Bf3+ Ke5 {and a draw was agreed in Xu, X (2571)-Wei Yi (2727) Fuling CHN 2022.}) ({Kc2} 28... Kf6 29. Be2 Ke5 {Kd3 Kd6 Kc4 Bg1} 30. Bd3 {Bxh2 Bxf5} h6 31. Be4 {Kc7 and a draw was agreed in Xu, X (2596)-Wen Yang (2581) Fuling CHN 2023.}) ({Bc7 Kb3} 28... f4 29. Ba6 Kf6 {Kc4 h6 Kd5 Ke7} 30. a4 {Kf6 h3} Ke7 {Kc5 Kf6} 31. a5 {Ke7 Kb5 Bd8 Bc8} Kd6 {Bd7 Bc7 Ka6 Bd8 Kxa7 Bxa5 Kb7 Bd8 Bg4 Ba5 Bf3 Bd8 Bg4 and a draw was agreed in Ding Liren (2799)-Wei Yi (2729) Hangzhou CHN 2022.}) *

