1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. Bg5 {A rare line that was the topic of our first chapter. I was caught off guard when Aravindh played this against me during the game.} cxd4 {It is essential to eliminate the central d4 -Pawn in order to try and seize control of the centre.} 6. Nxd4 Be7 {I decided to play it safe and avoid entering my opponent's preparation. I unpin the f6 -Knight and prepare to play ... O-O .} (6... e5 $5 {is the correct move for Black as we studied in Chapter 1. With ... e5 , we seize control of the centre. One of our main ideas is to march forward in the centre with ... d4 next.}) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {White has got a pleasant version of the IQP since his Bishop is already out on g5 . But of course, this is still quite a playable position for Black.} Be6 11. Qd2 Rc8 12. Rfd1 {White exerts indirect pressure on the d5 -Pawn.} Ne5 {I intended to activate my Knight with ... Nc4 hoping to create some counterplay on the Queenside.} 13. Rac1 Nc4 14. Qc2 Qb6 15. b3 (15. Na4 {would have been a better try for White to exert pressure on Black's Position.} Qa5 16. Qb3 {Now White threatens to capture the b7 -Pawn when the e7 -Bishop will come under attack. It is tough for Black to deal with so much pressure. If I try to liquidate to an endgame with} Nb6 17. Nxb6 Qxb6 {, then White could embrace the endgame with open arms with} 18. Qxb6 axb6 19. Bb5 {when the weaknesses in Black's Pawn structure give White a clear upper hand in this endgame.}) 15... Nd6 16. Qb2 Rfd8 17. h3 ({This was a bit slow.} 17. Na4 $1 {was energetic and strong. After} Qa5 18. Nc5 $1 {most probably the trick missed by my opponent; White starts creating one threat after the other. Now, the e6 -Bishop is under attack.} Rxc5 $2 {obviously loses to} 19. b4 {, so} Bd7 {b4 cementing the c5 -Knight. Qb6 Nxd7 Rxd7 Rxc8+ Nxc8} 20. Nf5 {The threats are coming on each and every move. White's Pieces are gradually becoming more active, which may soon turn into a material advantage.}) 17... a6 (17... Nf5 {exchanging the d4 -Knight would have released a lot of pressure.}) 18. Rc2 ({Once again, the Knight sortie} 18. Na4 {was quite strong.}) 18... h6 19. Bh4 Nf5 {Finally, I found the idea that more or less equalises the position.} 20. Nxf5 Bxf5 21. Bd3 Bxd3 22. Rxd3 {Generally, exchanges are considered to be good for White. But here, exchanging White's active Pieces gives Black a sigh of relief.} d4 {Another important move, getting rid of our isolated Pawn at the first opportunity. Now the position is completely equal.} 23. Nd1 Rxc2 24. Qxc2 dxe3 25. Nxe3 Rxd3 26. Qxd3 g6 {Covering the f5 -square and making some more room for the King.} 27. Qc3 Qe6 {Black's Queen is rock solid on e6 , covering a lot of important squares.} 28. Qc7 b5 29. Qb7 g5 30. Bg3 Ne4 31. Bb8 Bc5 {Threatening the deadly ... Nxf2 .} 32. Ba7 Bxa7 33. Qxa7 Nc3 34. Qc5 Ne2+ 35. Kh2 Nf4 36. Ng4 Kg7 37. g3 Nd5 38. Qd4+ f6 39. Kg2 Qc6 40. Kg1 Qe6 {maintaining the status quo.} 41. Nh2 Ne7 42. Qc5 Nf5 43. Nf3 Qe4 44. Nd2 Qe1+ 45. Nf1 Qe4 46. Qc7+ Kg6 47. Qc8 Kg7 48. Qd7+ Kg6 49. Qd8 Kg7 50. g4 Nh4 51. Ne3 Qf3 52. Qd7+ Kg6 53. Qe8+ Kg7 54. Qd7+ Kg6 55. Qd5 {Finally, White decides to exchange Queens, but there is no hope for White in the Knight endgame.} Qxd5 56. Nxd5 Nf3+ 57. Kg2 Nd4 58. b4 Nc6 59. Kf3 f5 60. Ke3 h5 61. f3 fxg4 62. fxg4 hxg4 63. hxg4 Ne5 64. Nc7 Nxg4+ 65. Kf3 Kf5 66. Nxa6 Ne5+ 67. Kg3 Nc6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
