[White "Model Games"]
[Black "2) Lexy Ortega - Mikhail Tal, Petrosian Memorial "]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D50"]
[PlyCount "54"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 {Yes, we reach our familiar position from a completely different move order.} 3. Nf3 (3. d5 b5 {enters the Benko Gambit, one of my favourite chess openings! It is sharp, dynamic, and gives a great chance to throw your opponent off-balance right at the start. I have created a Lifetime Repertoire on the Benko here on Chessable. If you are interested in learning this interesting opening, then you can surely check out my course on the Benko too.}) 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 d5 6. Bg5 {Finally, we arrive at the position we discussed in the first chapter.} e5 {This is the mainline of our chapter. The genius Mikhail Tal knew how to deal with such sidelines back in 1986 when people did not use engines to analyse openings!} 7. Nb3 (7. Bxf6 {as we analysed in Chapter 1, exchanging on f6 first before playing Nb3 makes more sense since there White forces us to recapture with the Pawn.}) 7... d4 {Tal seizes control of the centre.} 8. Nd5 Be7 (8... Nbd7 {was our mainline. We intend to play ... h6 next.}) 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 {White needs to watch out for ideas like ... Qb4 +.} 10. e3 Nc6 11. Be2 (11. Bxf6 {it was better to exchange on f6 immediately so that White does not have to worry about ... Qb4 +.} Qxf6 12. exd4 exd4 13. Bd3 {although after} O-O {, Black is slightly better thanks to the passed d4 -Pawn.}) 11... h6 (11... Qb4+ $1 {would have given Black a huge initiative in the endgame arising after} 12. Nd2 ({(} 12. Qd2 {loses to} Ne4 $1 13. Qxb4 Nxb4 {)}) 12... Ne4 $1 {hitting the Bishop.} 13. a3 Qxd2+ 14. Qxd2 Nxd2 15. Kxd2 f6 16. Bh4 Bf5 {followed by ... O-O-O . White's Pieces are uncoordinated, and his King is badly placed in the centre of the board. But Tal preferred to crush his opponents in the middlegame.}) 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. exd4 exd4 14. O-O O-O {White always has to watch out for the d4 -Pawn, which gives Black a slightly preferable position.} 15. Nc5 {It is a good strategy to blockade the passed pawn with a Knight.} Bf5 16. Nd3 Rfe8 17. Re1 Qg6 {Threatening ... Rxe2 .} 18. Nf4 Qg5 19. Nd5 {White forgets his original intention and lets the d4 -Pawn loose!} (19. Nd3 {was required.} Qg6 20. Nf4 Qd6 21. Nd3 Ne5 {Black still maintains a clear edge, although it would be tough to convert this into a win.}) 19... d3 {The Pawn marches forward at the first opportunity.} 20. Bf1 (20. Bxd3 $2 {loses to} Rxe1+ 21. Qxe1 Bxd3) 20... Nd4 {Threatening ... Rxe1 + followed by ... Nf3 +.} 21. h4 Qxh4 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Ne3 (23. Bxd3 {loses to} Bxd3 24. Qxd3 Ne2+) 23... Qg5 24. Nxf5 {White was all set to win the d3 -Pawn on the next move. But here comes...} Ne2+ {A strong intermediate move that ends the game in Black's favour.} 25. Bxe2 dxe2 26. Nxh6+ Qxh6 27. Qe1 Re5 {The Rooks swings over to the h -file, forcing White to resign.} *

