1. c4 {Once again, the game starts with a completely different opening, finally arriving at our known position from the course.} c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nc3 d5 5. d4 a6 {The mainline that we studied in Chapter 2. We intend to exchange pawns on c4 , followed by ... b5 .} 6. a3 (6. cxd5 {was the mainline in Chapter 2.}) 6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 (8. Ba2 {was a better retreat for White's Bishop as mentioned in the notes of Chapter 2.}) 8... Nbd7 {Developing the Knight first gives us an additional option of re-capturing on c5 with our Knight in case White takes on c5 .} 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bc2 Rc8 {Black mobilised his Queenside completely. Now, the focus is to develop the dark-squared Bishop to prepare ... O-O .} 11. Qe2 Bd6 12. Rd1 Qc7 {Getting away from the d -file and exerting pressure on the h2 -Pawn at the same time.} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Bd2 O-O 15. Rac1 Qb8 {Once again, retreating due to the potential threats along the c -file.} 16. h3 Rfd8 {Finally, all of Black's Pieces participate in the game. GM Le's Pieces are active compared to White's, which gives him a slightly better position.} 17. e4 {This is always a double-edged Pawn advance. On the one hand, it gains space in the centre for White. On the other hand, it leaves a few weak squares in White's camp.} h6 {A useful prophylactic move covering the g5 -square.} 18. Be3 {It is quite tempting to challenge the annoying c5 -Bishop. But here, Black has a nice tactical trick that wins a Pawn!} Bxa3 19. bxa3 Rxc3 20. Qd2 Rdc8 {The pressure along the c -file is increasing with every move.} 21. Bd4 Nxe4 22. Qe2 (22. Bxe4 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 24. Qxc1 Bxe4 {and Black is two Pawns up.}) 22... Ndf6 23. Ne1 R3c4 24. Qe3 Qc7 25. Bxe4 Nxe4 26. Rxc4 bxc4 {Black is two Pawns up and has got a nice passed c -Pawn, which gave him a clearly winning endgame.} 27. f3 Ng3 28. Be5 Nf5 29. Qc3 Qc5+ 30. Kh1 f6 31. Bh2 Bd5 32. Nc2 h5 33. Bf4 e5 34. Bh2 Be6 35. Bg1 Qc7 36. Bf2 Rd8 37. Re1 Rd3 {Kicking the blockading Queen.} 38. Qb4 a5 39. Qb5 Bd7 40. Qb1 Rd2 41. Kg1 c3 42. Qb3+ Kh7 43. Rc1 Qc6 44. Qf7 Be8 45. Qa7 Bg6 46. Be1 Qa4 47. Ne3 Qxa3 48. Nxf5 Bxf5 49. Bxd2 cxd2 50. Rf1 Qd3 51. Rd1 Qe2 *

