1. c4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. e3 d5 5. d4 a6 6. cxd5 {White clears his intentions that he wants to play against Black's Isolated Queen Pawn.} exd5 7. g3 {White's recent try to play for an advantage. They fianchetto the Bishop with the intention to get an optimal setup against our potential isolated d5 -Pawn.} c4 {Black deprives White of that opportunity. With ... c4 , we claim a Queenside Pawn majority.} 8. Bg2 Bb4 {Developing the Bishop actively and preparing to castle.} 9. Qa4+ {This is an attempt to weaken Black's Pawn structure but, as it turns out, Black is the one who comes out on top because of this.} Nc6 10. Ne5 O-O 11. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 bxc6 {Black has got doubled Pawns on the c -file, which White aimed to exploit. However, Black does not care much about the Pawn structure. His main trump is the weakness of the light squares in White's position. GM Carlsen played a model game dominating the weak light squares in White's camp.} 13. O-O Bf5 {Carlsen does not waste time defending the c6 -Pawn but rather starts his operations on the light squares. Now, the b1 -square is also covered, which bans entry for White's Rooks on the b -file.} 14. Ba3 (14. Qxc6 {can be met by} Bd3 $1 15. Re1 Qa5 16. Bd2 Rac8 17. Qd6 Ne4 18. Bxe4 dxe4 {the difference between the quality of both Bishops and the holes on White's Kingside are enough to ensure a winning advantage for Black.}) 14... Re8 15. Qxc6 {White grabs a Pawn, but now Black unleashes his evil intentions on the Kingside.} Re6 {This Rook is looking forward to swinging on the kingside if required.} 16. Qa4 h5 17. h3 {Preparing to play g4 in case Black plays ... h4 .} Bd3 18. Rfc1 Ne4 {Threats like ... Nxf2 are always hanging in the air.} 19. Qd1 Qg5 20. Qe1 Rae8 {Black's last Piece comes in the battle.} 21. Kh2 Rg6 {Black threatens ... Nxg3 crushing White's King's shelter.} 22. Rab1 {White sacrifices an exchange in a desperate attempt to search for counterplay.} Bxb1 23. Rxb1 Qd8 24. Bb4 Rb6 25. Rc1 Qb8 26. h4 a5 27. Ba3 Ree6 28. Rd1 Qe8 29. Bc1 Rb1 30. f3 Nd6 31. Bd2 Rb2 32. Rb1 Rxa2 33. Qc1 Nf5 34. e4 dxe4 35. fxe4 Rxe4 {Finally, White's fortress crumbles.} 36. Bf4 Ree2 37. Rb8 Rxg2+ 38. Kh1 Qxb8 39. Bxb8 Rh2+ 40. Kg1 Rag2+ 41. Kf1 Rh1+ {And White resigned.} *

