1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 c5 4. e3 Nf6 5. Nf3 a6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. g3 c4 8. Bg2 Bb4 9. Bd2 {White protects the c3 -Knight preparing b3 next.} O-O 10. b3 Bf5 {A typical move for our light-squared Bishop.} 11. O-O Bd3 12. Re1 Nc6 {We covered this in Chapter 2.} 13. Ne5 Nxe5 {It is essential to eliminate the e5 -Knight in order to ensure that our d3 -Bishop stays alive.} 14. dxe5 Bxc3 {This gets Black's Knight access to the e4 -square.} 15. Bxc3 Ne4 16. Bb4 Re8 17. f3 a5 (17... Qb6 $5 {could be a better try.} 18. fxe4 Qxb4 19. exd5 b5 $1 {an important supporting move that guarantees our Bishop is stable on d3 . Next, Black wants to take on e5 .} 20. bxc4 bxc4 21. Bf1 Bxf1 22. Rxf1 Rxe5 {Black is slightly better due to a better pawn structure.}) 18. Ba3 (18. fxe4 {is met by} axb4 19. exd5 b5) 18... Nc3 19. Qd2 Nb5 20. Bb2 a4 21. f4 a3 22. Bc3 Qb6 23. Bb4 Red8 24. Rac1 Be4 25. Be7 Re8 (25... c3 $1 {was an interesting try.} 26. Rxc3 Nxc3 27. Bxd8 Rxd8 28. Qxc3 {and now} d4 $1 29. exd4 Rxd4 30. Qe3 Bf5 {Black's active Pieces gives him a nice compensation for the Pawn.}) 26. Bxe4 dxe4 27. bxc4 Rxe7 28. Qb4 Rc7 29. Qxb5 Qxb5 30. cxb5 Rac8 31. Rxc7 Rxc7 {White was a pawn up, but Black had sufficient counterplay. This topsy-turvy Rook endgame finally ended in a draw.} 32. Rd1 g5 33. b6 Rc6 34. Rd8+ Kg7 35. Ra8 Rc1+ 36. Kg2 Rc2+ 37. Kh3 gxf4 38. gxf4 Rxa2 39. Kg4 Rxh2 40. Rxa3 Rb2 41. f5 Rg2+ 42. Kf4 h5 43. Kxe4 h4 44. Ra1 h3 45. Kf3 Rb2 46. Rh1 h2 47. Kg3 Rb5 48. Kf4 Rb2 49. Kf3 Kh6 50. Kf4 Rf2+ 51. Kg4 Re2 52. Kf3 Rb2 53. Kg3 Kg5 54. e6 fxe6 55. fxe6 Rxb6 56. Rxh2 Rxe6 *

