1. c4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 c5 5. d4 a6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. g3 c4 8. Bg2 Bb4 9. O-O O-O 10. Ne5 Re8 11. Bd2 {As usual, with this, White prepares to break on the Queenside with b2 - b3 .} Nc6 {Black immediately challenges the e5 -Knight. One of the ideas is to provoke f2 - f4 , which supports the e5 -Knight but terribly weakens the light squares in White's camp.} 12. a3 Ba5 13. b4 cxb3 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Qxb3 {White aims to exploit Black's backward c6 -Pawn. However, GM Carlsen demonstrates that his attacking potential on the kingside is much stronger.} h5 {The h -Pawn marches forward in the direction of White's King. A typical strategy to gain space and squeeze the opponent's Pieces.} 16. Qc2 h4 17. Rfc1 h3 {Black voluntarily closes the kingside. The point is that the h3 -Pawn is like a thorn in the flesh. This does not necessarily mean that it has to pay off in the middlegame. In fact, as you will see, Carlsen exploited the power of the h3 -Pawn in the endgame.} 18. Bh1 Bg4 19. Nb1 Bb6 {Magnus avoids exchanges as White's Pieces struggle to coordinate.} 20. Bb4 Ne4 {It is all about the light squares.} 21. Bxe4 (21. f3 $2 {is strongly met by} Qg5 $1 22. fxg4 Qxe3+ 23. Kf1 Bxd4 {and a checkmate is near.}) 21... Rxe4 22. Nd2 Re6 23. Qd3 Qf6 24. Qf1 Ree8 {Carlsen realises that breaking through on the kingside is not easy. So, he switches his attention to the Queenside and plans to break through along the b -file.} 25. Rab1 Reb8 26. Bc5 Ba5 {Once again, not interested in exchanges.} 27. Bb4 Bc7 28. Bc3 a5 29. f3 Bf5 30. e4 {Black is happy to provoke such pawn advances as they create potential weaknesses in White's camp.} Be6 31. e5 Qe7 32. Ra1 {White defends the a3 -Pawn. All the entry points on the b -file are covered, so White does not give away the b -file to Black at the moment.} c5 33. Qf2 c4 {Black has created a nice passed Pawn on the c -file.} 34. g4 f6 {An important pawn break that opens up diagonals for Black's Bishops.} 35. Kh1 fxe5 36. dxe5 Bb6 37. Bd4 Bxd4 38. Qxd4 Qa7 {Removing the blockade of Black's central pawns.} 39. Qxa7 Rxa7 40. Rc2 d4 {Time to march forward and sweep away opponent's territory.} 41. Nxc4 {This allows Magnus to showcase his calculating skills and finish the game off by force.} Rc8 42. Rac1 d3 43. Rc3 Rxc4 44. Rxc4 Bxc4 45. Rxc4 d2 46. Rd4 Rc7 47. Rxd2 Rc1+ 48. Rd1 Rxd1# {Remember the thorn in the flesh! The h3 -Pawn is the man of the match.} *

