1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Nxd4 (6. Qxd4 {is by far White's main response.}) 6... Nxd5 7. Bd2 Be7 8. e4 Nxc3 9. Bxc3 O-O 10. Be2 Qb6 {Intending ... Rd8 creating pressure on the d4 -Knight. Only after ... Rd8 would Black play ... Nc6 adding fuel to the fire.} 11. Qb3 {White immediately evacuates the Queen from the d -file.} Rd8 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. a3 {Freeing the Rook on a1 .} Na6 {Our trainable ended here. The Knight arriving on c5 could be dangerous since it attacks the e4 -Pawn while also intending ... Na4 pressurising the Queenside.} 14. Bxa6 {White gets rid of the Knight, but hands over the Bishop pair to Black.} Rxa6 {The position is only slightly better for Black due to the Bishop pair. But White is quite solid. GM Wesley uses his Bishop pair masterfully, gradually outplaying his esteemed opponent.} 15. O-O Bd7 16. Rfd1 Raa8 17. f3 e5 {Time to claim some space in the centre. This not only kicks the d4 -Knight but also limits the c3 -Bishop.} 18. Nf5 Bc5+ 19. Kf1 g6 20. Ng3 f6 {In just a few moves, Black managed to activate his dark-squared Bishop to c5 while destabilising White's minor Pieces.} 21. Ke1 Ba4 {Snatching the control of the d -file.} 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Nf1 Kf7 24. Nd2 Ke6 25. b3 Bc6 (25... Rd3 $1 {was a stronger move that would have won a pawn.} 26. Bb4 Bxb3 27. Bxc5 bxc5) 26. a4 ({It was necessary to play} 26. Ke2 {covering the d3 -square.} Bb5+ 27. Nc4 {Black is only slightly better.}) 26... Rd3 {GM Wesley does not miss another chance to activate his Rook.} 27. Rc1 f5 (27... Be3 {was a better try.} 28. Ke2 Bxd2 29. Bxd2 Rxb3 {Black wins a Pawn, although White keeps drawing chances because of the presence of opposite-coloured Bishops.}) 28. exf5+ (28. b4 $1 {would have kicked both Black's Bishops one by one and equalised for White. For example:  A)} Be3 {is met by} 29. b5 Be8 30. Ke2 Bxd2 31. Bxd2 Ra3 32. Rc7 {.  B) Bg1 b5! Be8 Ke2} Re3+ 33. Kd1 {Bxh2 Black wins a pawn, but now White generates counterplay with Nc4} Rd3 34. Kc2 fxe4 35. fxe4 Rg3 {Kb3 Rxg2 Rd1⇆}) 28... gxf5 29. Nc4 (29. b4 {does not work now due to} Bg1 30. b5 Bd5 {this the drawback of not having the e4 -Pawn.}) 29... e4 30. Ke2 b5 31. Na5 Re3+ 32. Kd2 Bd5 33. axb5 exf3 34. gxf3 Bxf3 {Black has got a strong passed f -Pawn plus active Pieces. GM So converted his winning advantage to a full point.} 35. b4 Re2+ 36. Kd3 Be3 37. Re1 Rxe1 38. Bxe1 Bg1 39. Bg3 b6 40. Nc4 Be4+ 41. Kd2 Bd4 42. Bf4 Bd5 43. Na3 Be5 44. Ke3 Bc3 45. Nc2 Be4 46. Nd4+ Kd5 47. Nf3 Bxb4 48. Ng5 Bc5+ 49. Kd2 h5 50. Nh7 Bd4 51. h4 Kc4 52. Be3 Bc3+ 53. Ke2 Kxb5 54. Bh6 Kc4 55. Ng5 b5 56. Bf8 b4 57. Nxe4 fxe4 58. Bxb4 Bxb4 59. Ke3 Kd5 *

