1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qa4+ Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 8. Nxd5 {White's most challenging attempt to play for an advantage. This is the mainline of the third chapter.} Qa5+ {Forcing White's Knight to retreat.} 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Qd1 Ne4 {Immediately exerting pressure on White's position before he is able to consolidate.} 11. Bd2 Nxd2 12. Nxd2 Bb4 {Another threat.} 13. Rc1 {White sacrifices the a2 -Pawn in order to wrap up Black's initiative.} Bxc3 14. Rxc3 Qxa2 15. Nc4 {A multipurpose move. White prevents Black from castling short, since now the d7 -Bishop hangs. Nc4 also protects the b2 -Pawn and locks Black's Queen on a2 . Black needs to be careful not to get his Queen trapped on a2 .} Be6 {Moving the Bishop to a better square.} 16. e4 Rd8 17. Nd6+ Kf8 18. Qc1 {An important move for White that we studied in Chapter 3. White threatens to trap our Queen with Ra3 .} Qa4 (18... Rxd6 $4 {loses to} 19. Ra3 {winning Black's Queen.}) 19. Nxb7 Qxe4+ 20. Qe3 Qxe3+ 21. fxe3 Rb8 22. Nc5 Nd8 23. Bd3 g6 {Vacating the g7 -square for the King.} 24. O-O Rxb2 {Eliminating the last pawn on the Queenside. Now, all Black needs to do is hold the Kingside together, and Wesley So held it comfortably.} 25. Ra3 Kg7 26. Nxe6+ Nxe6 27. Rxa7 Rf8 28. Bc4 Rb6 29. Bd5 g5 {Placing pawns on the dark squares.} 30. Re7 Rd6 31. Rf5 (31. Bxe6 {wins a pawn but after} Rxe6 32. Rfxf7+ Rxf7 33. Rxe6 Ra7 {, this Rook endgame is a draw.}) 31... h6 32. g4 Nc5 {Black sacrifices the f7 -Pawn to generate sufficient counterplay.} 33. Rexf7+ Rxf7 34. Rxf7+ Kg6 35. Rf5 Nd7 36. Bf7+ Kg7 37. Bc4 Nf6 38. h3 {Black can easily hold his own on the dark squares.} Rc6 39. Bb5 Re6 40. Rf3 h5 {Trading a pair of Pawns. The fewer pawns on the board, the easier it is to draw.} 41. gxh5 Nxh5 42. Bd7 Rf6 43. Bf5 Nf4 44. e4 Ne2+ 45. Kg2 Nd4 {Now White cannot avoid the trades.} 46. Rf2 Nxf5 47. exf5 Ra6 {With ... Kf6 coming up next, there is nothing better for White than to accept a draw.} 48. f6+ Rxf6 49. Rxf6 Kxf6 50. Kg3 Kf5 51. h4 gxh4+ 52. Kxh4 *

