1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {The mainline of Chapter 4. White develops his Bishop out to g5 before he plays e3 . This Bishop also helps create some pressure on the d5 -Pawn.} Be7 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd3 {The Bishop is actively placed on this square compared to e2 , but it also blocks White's Queen from retreating along the d -file.} h6 {As we already know it is useful to insert ... h6 before continuing to develop the Queenside Pieces. The point is that we can play ... g5 whenever required in the future} 10. Bh4 Nc6 11. Qa4 Be6 {Vidit decides to develop his Pieces instead of chasing White's Queen further. The Bishop is well placed on e6 , defending the d5 -Pawn. This frees his Queen to move to a better square.} (11... Bd7 12. Qd1 Bg4 {was our line from chapter 4.}) 12. O-O Qb6 13. Qb5 {White offers to exchange Queens, which is generally recommended when playing against an IQP.} Qxb5 14. Nxb5 g5 {A typical pawn advance that we have seen many times in Chapter 4.} 15. Bg3 Ne4 {Black aims to win the Bishop pair by exchanging on g3 . Another idea behind ... Ne4 is to vacate the f6 -square for the Bishop.} 16. Rfd1 Nxg3 17. hxg3 Bf6 {Black's isolated Pawn is compensated by the Bishop pair. Next, Vidit brings his Rooks into play.} 18. Rab1 Rfd8 {We covered this in Chapter 4.} 19. Nbd4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Rac8 21. Be2 {GM Duda transfers his Bishop to f3 , which adds some pressure on the d5 -Pawn. But the d5 -Pawn is rock-solid, so Black does not have to worry about it.} Kf8 {With all the Pieces participating in the battle, it is time to centralise the King.} 22. Rd2 Ke7 23. Rbd1 {White still dreams of creating pressure on the d5 -Pawn. However, as it turns out, Black has more than sufficient counterplay elsewhere, which GM Vidit aptly demonstrates in this game.} Bxd4 {An instructive exchange that equalises the game on the spot.} 24. Rxd4 {This is the recapture that one would blindly make while playing against an IQP. But here, Black has an interesting way of generating counterplay.} ({White had to settle for} 24. exd4 {when both players can be happy to agree for a draw.}) 24... Rc2 25. Bf3 {White tries to complicate things instead of accepting a slightly inferior position after Rd2 . But this backfires for him.} (25. R1d2 {This could be Duda's initial intention. But here, Black has the amazing resource -} Rxd2 26. Rxd2 d4 $1 27. exd4 Bxa2 {and the possibility of creating an outside passed Pawn gives Black at least a slightly better endgame.}) 25... Rxb2 26. a3 (26. Bxd5 {is out of the question because of} Bxd5 27. Rxd5 Rxd5 28. Rxd5 Rxa2 {When Blacks two passed Pawns decides the game in his favour.}) 26... Ra2 27. Ra4 a6 28. Rb1 Rd7 (28... g4 $5 {could have been stronger. For example,} 29. Bxg4 b5 30. Rd4 Bxg4 31. Rxg4 Rxa3 {Once again, Black's passed Pawn duo gives him a winning position.}) ({Rxb7+ is met by} 28... Rd7 $1 {Rxd7+ Bxd7} 29. Rxa6 {gxf3 gxf3 Bb5-+ Black has an extra Bishop. Although it is not at all easy to win this endgame with such a limited number of pawns remaining on the board.}) 29. g4 Rc7 30. Ra5 Rac2 31. Rb6 (31. Bxd5 {loses a Piece to} Rc1+ 32. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 33. Kh2 b6) 31... Rd2 32. Rb4 Kf6 33. Rb6 Kg7 34. Ra4 Bd7 {Transferring the Bishop to c6 where it holds tightly both the d5 and b7 pawns.} 35. Rab4 Rc1+ 36. Kh2 Bc6 {Black creates an unbreakable wall along the diagonal.} 37. Kg3 Rc3 38. a4 Ra3 39. Rxb7 {Finally, Duda decides to break it by sacrificing the exchange.} Bxb7 40. Rxb7 Rxa4 41. Rd7 d4 42. Bd5 dxe3 43. fxe3 Ra3 44. Kf3 Rdd3 45. Ke4 {A great attempt to complicate things that ultimately paid off. White activates his King to create additional threats.} Rxe3+ 46. Kf5 Ra5 {A fateful blunder by Vidit that allows White to escape with a draw.} ({It would be nice to evacuate the King quickly with} 46... Kf8 $1 47. Rxf7+ Ke8 {and the King gets far away from enemy Pieces. Black's extra exchange and a pawn will decide the game in his favour.}) 47. Rxf7+ Kg8 48. Rd7+ Kf8 49. Kf6 {Now the KIng cannot run away.} Re1 50. Be6 Rxe6+ 51. Kxe6 Ra4 {It still feels that Black may have some chances in this Rook endgame. But with such few pawns on the board, it is tough to create anything.} 52. Rf7+ Kg8 53. Ra7 Rxg4 54. Kf6 Rf4+ 55. Kg6 Kf8 56. Rxa6 Rg4 57. Ra2 Rh4 58. Rf2+ Ke7 59. Re2+ Kd6 60. g3 Rh3 61. Re3 Kd5 62. Kf5 Kd4 63. Ra3 Rh1 64. Kg4 Ke4 65. Ra6 Ke5 66. Rb6 Rh2 67. Rb1 Kf6 68. Rb6+ Kg7 69. Re6 Kf7 70. Rb6 Rh1 71. Ra6 Kg7 72. Ra7+ Kg6 73. Ra6+ Kg7 74. Ra7+ Kg6 75. Ra6+ Kg7 *

