1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 Be7 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd3 h6 10. Bh4 Nc6 11. Qa4 Bd7 {Black keeps chasing the Queen, more or less forcing it to retreat to its initial square.} 12. Qd1 Bg4 {Exploiting the drawback of having the Bishop on d3 and not on e2 . Pinning the f3 -Knight also makes it easier for Black to get in the much desired ... d4 break.} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 d4 {Our trainable ends here. Generally, the side playing with an isolated Queen pawn does great whenever they manage to achieve this central break.} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nd5 {White intends to ruin the pawn structure on the kingside with Nxf6 +.} Bg5 {Black plans to exchange pawns on e3 .} (16... dxe3 {was also possible and leads to a very much playable endgame for both sides after} 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Qxf6 gxf6 19. fxe3) 17. e4 {This prevents further opening of lines and cements the d5 -Knight.} Qa5+ {Denying White the right to castle.} 18. Kf1 {White's Pieces are uncoordinated at the moment. His King still needs some time to arrive at a comfortable destination, and his Rooks have yet to come into the game. Considering these factors, GM Grischuk rightly launched an operation against White's position.} Ne5 19. Qe2 f5 {Quickly opening up lines for the Pieces. The ... f5 break also weakens the d5 -Knight. Next, Black wants to include his last Piece in the game with ... Rae8 when he will gain a decisive initiative.} 20. h4 fxe4 {Black goes all out against White's King.} (20... Bf6 {allows White to liquidate to an equal endgame after} 21. Nxf6+ Rxf6 22. exf5 Nxd3 23. Qxd3 Rxf5 {White can win a Pawn now by} 24. Qxd4 {although after} Rd8 {Black has a nice compensation for the pawn since White's army is yet to coordinate.}) 21. hxg5 Nxd3 {The f2 -Pawn comes under severe pressure. Unfortunately, White has the resources to escape from this mess.} 22. Qxe4 {A strong idea that creates sufficient counter chances for White.} (22. Nf6+ {is also possible. But after} Rxf6 23. gxf6 Qf5 {, Black gets a huge compensation for the exchange and White needs to find ways to keep it to a minimum.}) 22... Qd2 {Black's Queen enters the party with a checkmating threat on f2 . White is forced to find a continuation that guarantees a draw.} (22... Nxf2 $4 {would be a fateful error due to} 23. Qe6+ $1 Kh8 24. Rxh6+ $1 {demolishing Black's Kingside.} gxh6 25. Qxh6+ Kg8 26. Nf6+ {breaking the support between Black's Rook and the f2 -Knight.} Rxf6 27. gxf6 {White threatens checkmate on g7 and also the f2 -Knight.}) 23. Qe6+ (23. Ne7+ {also leads to a draw:} Kh8 $4 {loses quickly to} 24. Rxh6+ $1 gxh6 25. Qxd4+ Kh7 26. g6# {. However, after Kf7 g6+ Kf6 Nd5+ Kg5 , surprisingly, Black’s KIng is safe on g5 , and White is the one who needs to find the correct moves to draw the game.  A) Qe7+? allows Black to escape the checks with Rf6! Rh5+ Kxh5 Nxf6+ gxf6 Qxf6 now White threatens Qf5 +, which can be comfortably met by Qf4-+ and an extra Pieces gives Black a winning advantage.  B) Qh4+ Kxg6 Qe4+ Kf7 Qf5+ Kg8 Ne7+ Kh8 Ng6+ Kg8 and the position repeats after Ne7+= .}) 23... Rf7 {This led to a repetition:} 24. Ne7+ Kf8 25. Ng6+ Kg8 26. Ne7+ Kf8 27. Ng6+ Kg8 28. Ne7+ *

