1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 Be7 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 h6 10. Bh4 Nc6 11. Qd3 Qb6 {Black vacates the d8 -square for the Rook and intends to capture the b2 -Pawn at the right moment.} 12. O-O Rd8 ({It is incorrect to capture the b2 -Pawn immediately with} 12... Qxb2 $6 {because after} 13. Rab1 Qa3 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Qxd3 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bxd3 {, we get an inferior version of the mainline we discussed in the 4th chapter.}) 13. Nb5 {This prevents Black from capturing the b2 -Pawn while adding more control on the d4 -square. But the Knight going away to b5 allows Black's Knight to jump on e4 , which GM Cheparinov promptly exploits in this game.} a6 {First, it is necessary to kick the Knight; otherwise, it could create additional threats from the active b5 -square.} (13... Bg4 {is a good alternative which was given as the main response to 13.Nb5 in Chapter 4.}) 14. Nbd4 g5 {Our typical idea that we have seen time and again. By pushing the Bishop back to g3 to prepare to play ... Ne4 next.} 15. Bg3 Ne4 {As usual, this Knight jump comes with two ideas. Firstly, to win the Bishop pair by exchanging on g3 and secondly, to play ... Bf6 from where the Bishop can exert pressure along the a1 - h8 diagonal.} 16. Rac1 Bf6 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Be5 {White managed to avoid losing the Bishop pair. But this also means that Black's active Knight is still alive on e4 .} c5 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 {Black's active Pieces give him a minute initiative.} 20. Nd2 {White decides to eliminate the annoying e4 -Knight.} Bf5 {It is time to replace the Knight with the Bishop.} 21. Nxe4 Bxe4 22. Qa3 Rab8 23. Rxc5 (23. b3 {can be met by} c4 $1 24. bxc4 Rb2 {activating the Rook along the 2nd rank.} 25. Bf3 {now Black has the option to force a draw with} Bxf3 26. gxf3 Qxf3 27. Qxb2 Qg4+ 28. Kh1 Qf3+) (23. Rfe1 $4 {would lose to dxc4-+ when the c4 -Pawn is immune and the pressure along the 2nd rank is decisive.}) 23... Rxb2 24. Qxa6 Rd6 25. Qc8+ Kg7 26. Bh5 {It makes a lot of sense to place the Bishop on h5 so that White can create threats against the f7 -Pawn. But as it turns out, leaving the f1 - a6 diagonal is a fatal mistake which GM Cheparinov could not exploit in the game.} (26. Bb5 {was a much safer choice.}) 26... Bd3 (26... Bf5 $3 {moving the Bishop backwards before going forward to d3 would have forced White to resign. The point is to push White's Queen away from the c -file so that when we play ... Bd3 , we create a double threat of ... Qxf2 + and ... Bxf1 .} 27. Qa8 Bd3 {and White is forced to give away the exchange. For example} 28. Rc7 $2 {now leads to a mate after} Qxf2+ $3 29. Rxf2 Rb1+ 30. Rf1 Rxf1#) 27. Rc7 Rd7 (27... Bxf1 $2 {is bad due to} 28. Rxf7+ Qxf7 29. Bxf7 Kxf7 30. Qc7+ Ke6 31. Kxf1) 28. Rc6 (28. Qxd7 $4 {loses to the same trick:} Qxf2+ 29. Rxf2 Rb1+ 30. Rf1 Rxf1#) 28... Rd6 29. Rc7 Rd7 30. Rc6 Rd6 *

