1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 {White pins the Knight and prepares to play O-O-O next.} h6 ({This was the line covered in Chapter 7. while in Chapter 8,  we studied} 11... Nc6 {.}) 12. O-O-O+ Ke7 {The KIng is better placed on e7 as it protects the e6 and f6 -Pawns beforehand.} 13. Bxf6+ gxf6 {Since both the e6 and d6 -Pawns are covered by the King, we can get some time to develop our remaining forces.} 14. Nxe4 {White has regained his Pawn. If Black manages to develop his remaining Pieces in time, then White's initiative will be comfortably liquidated.} f5 {Carlsen kicks the e4 -Knight immediately. I consider this to be slightly inferior as it creates unnecessary complications for Black.} (14... Bg7 {was our mainline from Chapter 7. The next model game deals with this move.}) 15. Nc5 {This is the correct move for White to create some pressure. The b7 -Pawn is under attack, but most importantly, the e6 pawn can quickly come under immense pressure.} Kf6 {It is essential to attack the c5 -Knight quickly before White gets a chance to create pressure on the e6 -Pawn.} (15... b6 $2 {seems like the most logical way to attack the Knight, but in fact is a mistake due to the surprising} 16. Bc4 $1 bxc5 17. Rhe1 {White sacrifices his Knight and gains a killer initiative in return for it. Black's King is alone in this battle vs three white Pieces as all of Black's Pieces are still sleeping on their initial squares.}) 16. Rd8 (16. Nxb7 {gives Black decent counterplay after} Nc6 17. Bb5 Ne5 18. f4 Ng6 19. g3 Rb8 20. Ba6 Rh7 {and Black connects his forces to create regular threats.} 21. Na5 h5 $1 {looking for play on the kingside.} 22. h4 Rg7 {with pressure against the g3 -Pawn. Black has decent compensation for the Pawn.}) 16... Bg7 {Immediately challenging the d8 -Rook in order to be able to develop the Queenside Pieces quickly.} 17. Rxh8 Bxh8 18. Bc4 ({Once again,} 18. Nxb7 Nc6 {gives Black good compensation.}) 18... Nc6 {It is better to sacrifice a Pawn and favour Piece development.} 19. Nxe6 (19. Bxe6 $2 {is a mistake due to} Nd4 $1 20. Bd7 Rd8 $1 {and White is in trouble. For example, if} 21. Ba4 {then Black has} Rc8 {winning the Knight.}) 19... Ne5 20. Bd5 Nd3+ 21. Kd2 Nb4 {This complicated the struggle quite a lot.} ({Simpler was} 21... Nxf2 22. Rf1 {and now} Ne4+ $1 23. Bxe4 Kxe6 24. Bxf5+ Ke7 {White still maintains his pawn lead, but due to the presence of opposite-coloured Bishops on the board and the small number of Pawns remaining in the game, Black can easily hold this ending to a draw.}) 22. Bxb7 {White does not shy away from grabbing a free Pawn.} Rb8 23. Nc5 {Protecting both Pieces at the same time. White stands clearly better thanks to his extra Pawns, although his Pieces are in disarray, and it won't be easy for him to consolidate.} Rd8+ (23... Kg6 {threatening the b2 -Pawn as well as ... Bd4 .}) 24. Kc3 a5 25. a3 Kg6+ 26. Kb3 ({It was better to activate the King with} 26. Kc4 $1 {For example, after} Rd4+ 27. Kb5 Nd3 28. Na4 $1 {protecting the b2 -Pawn. Maintaining a pair of Knights is beneficial for White, as it will help him on the Queenside.} Nxf2 {Black recovers one of the two lost pawns. Although after} 29. Re1 {, with ideas like Re6 + and Kxa5 , White has great chances to score a full point.}) 26... Nd3 {Forcing the exchange of Knights, which drastically increases Black's drawing chances.} 27. Nxd3 Rxd3+ 28. Kc4 Rd7 {Black is all set to recover one of the lost Pawns.} 29. Bc6 Rc7 30. Kb5 Bxb2 31. a4 Rc8 ({This prevents any tactical tricks along the c -file, which can be seen in this variation:} 31... Bc3 $4 {It is important to note that it is a mistake to try to place the Bishop on the ideal b4 -square immediately.} 32. Rc1 $1 Bb4 33. Be8+ {and Black loses the Rook.}) 32. Rd1 Bc3 33. f4 Rb8+ 34. Kc4 Bb4 35. Rd5 {White still maintains good winning chances but, with a few pawns remaining on the board, it has become quite difficult for White to make progress. Especially when you are playing the world number 1!} Rf8 {Black overprotects the f5 -Pawn and stays solid. The next few moves are more about just moving the pieces around.} 36. Bd7 h5 37. g3 Be1 38. Rd6+ Kg7 39. Rd1 Bb4 40. Rd5 Kg6 41. Kd4 Be1 {Black intends to exchange more pawns with ... h4 .} 42. Rd6+ Kg7 43. Re6 Bb4 44. Be8 h4 {Finally, GM Carlsen gets a chance to use tactics to liquidate on the Kingside.} 45. gxh4 Rf6 ({The direct} 45... Bd2 {was also enough to claim an equality.}) 46. Kd5 Bd2 {And White has to surrender the f4 -Pawn, after which it is an easy draw.} 47. Rxf6 Kxf6 48. Bh5 Bxf4 49. Bf3 Bxh2 50. Be2 Bg3 51. h5 Be1 52. Bf3 Bb4 53. Bd1 Bd2 54. Bf3 Bb4 55. Bd1 Bd2 56. Bf3 Bb4 *

