1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 h6 12. O-O-O+ Ke7 13. Bxf6+ gxf6 14. Nxe4 Bg7 {This is our mainline from Chapter 8. We develop our Bishop first and then look forward to playing ... f5 .} 15. Ng3 {A sensible prophylactic Knight retreat. One of the intentions is to go to h5 .} h5 {Gaining space on the Kingside and also covering the h5 -square.} 16. h4 Nc6 17. Be2 Rad8 {We can’t defend the h5 -Pawn (sacrificing it was the idea all along!), but our main focus is to activate our Knight to the central d4 -square.} 18. Nxh5 Nd4 19. Ng3 f5 {This was the end of our Chapter 7. Black has nice compensation because of the active d4 -Knight and well-placed Bg7 . We threaten ... f4 next winning a Piece.} 20. Bd3 {White takes care of the threat of ... f4 .} Rd6 {Neither side has a clear plan of play. It is all about keeping our Pieces active and on good squares. So, when the time comes, we can deliver with our better-placed Pieces. As you will see in the game, White lost only because he voluntarily pushed his pawns forward in search of a plan and the price for it since a lot of squares in his camp were seriously weakened.} 21. Kb1 Be5 22. Nf1 Bf6 23. h5 Bg5 (23... Rhd8 {was a good option. For example, after} 24. Ne3 Nc6 25. Bc2 Rd2 {our Rook enters the 2nd rank, and Black has ideas like ... Nb4 , which creates further pressure on White's position.}) 24. Ne3 Nc6 25. Be2 Nd4 26. Bf1 Rdd8 {Black stays solid, keeps his Pieces active and waits for White to make the first mistake.} 27. Bc4 Kf6 28. Rde1 b5 {This is a safe pawn advance. It gains some space for Black on the Queenside.} 29. Bf1 a6 30. Rh3 Bh6 {Till now, both sides played their moves cautiously. But now White makes a small step in the wrong direction.} 31. a3 {This seems like a logical move, creating room for his King. But this weakens the b3 -square, which Black promptly exploits in the game.} Rhg8 32. Rh1 Nb3 {This Knight is quite annoying on b3 .} 33. Kc2 Nc5 {Time to go to e4 and create havoc on the Kingside.} 34. f3 {This covers the e4 -square but creates more weaknesses in White's camp. One mistake leads to another.} Rd7 {Black uses his Rooks effectively.} 35. g4 Rc8 36. Kb1 Na4 {Black has finalised his target. He is going to bomb the b2 -Pawn.} 37. gxf5 Bxe3 {Our Bishop was staring at the Knight for many, many moves. But this is the right time to exchange it as it provides penetration for our Rooks into White's territory.} 38. Rxe3 Rd1+ 39. Ka2 Rc2 {With just a few Pieces remaining on the board, Black manages to weave a mating net around White's King.} 40. Rxe6+ (40. Rb3 {is met by} Rcc1 41. Re3 Nc5 $1 42. b4 Rc2#) 40... Kf7 {There is no way to prevent ... Rxb2 without losing heavy material. So White resigns.} *

