1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 10. Nxe6+ fxe6 11. Bg5 Ke8 {This is also playable, but remember that we first develop our Knight to c6 and only then decide where to place our King, on e7 or e8 .} (11... Nc6 {is the correct move order for us as we studied in Chapter 8.}) 12. O-O-O (12. Bb5+ Kf7 13. O-O-O {would have led to something completely different that we do not wish to enter.}) 12... Nc6 {Finally, we are back in the familiar terrain.} 13. Bc4 {This was one of the most critical variations of Chapter 8. It gives White a chance to muddy the waters by sacrificing an exchange.} Ne5 {An important move to remember. Instead of protecting the e6 -Pawn as we usually do, this rare counterattacking move available to us.} 14. Bxe6 {White does not shy away from sacrificing an exchange. He intends to play against our exposed King.} Nd3+ 15. Kc2 Nxf2 16. Bxf6 Nxd1 {It is essential to eliminate the d1 -Rook before recapturing on f6 . This slows down White's initiative.} 17. Rxd1 gxf6 18. Rd7 {White wants to play Nd5 next.} Rd8 19. Rxb7 Rd6 {Another important move. Black kicks the active e6 -Bishop, also creating some room for his KIng.} 20. Bc4 Rd4 {Once again, chasing the Bishop and defending the e4 -Pawn at the same time.} 21. Bb5+ (21. Be6 {leads to a repetition after} Rd6 22. Bc4 Rd4 {.}) 21... Kd8 22. Rxa7 {White has good compensation for the exchange. But his passed pawns are still on their initial squares, which makes it tough for him to exploit them.} Rg8 {Black finds a nice way to activate his Rook.} 23. g3 Rg5 {Our trainable ends here.} 24. Ra8+ Ke7 25. a4 {Finally, White's Pawn is set in motion.} Kf7 {Freeing the f8 -Bishop to move to squares like b4 .} 26. a5 e3 {Black flexes his own passed pawn in return.} 27. a6 {A blunder made out of inertia.} ({It was necessary to support the Bishop first with} 27. Rb8 {before continuing the pawn march. This would have avoided the tactical trick that Black got to use in the game.}) 27... Rd2+ 28. Kc1 Rxb5 {A nice tactical trick that White missed in the game. This distracts White's Knight, and now the e2 push is unstoppable.} 29. Nxb5 Bh6 30. Nc3 e2 31. Nxe2 Rd8+ {Black wins the Rook and the game.} *

