1. c4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 {This is famously called the symmetrical variation of the English Opening.} 3. Nc3 e6 4. e3 d5 5. d4 {Finally, we have arrived at a familiar position from our course, one we studied in Chapter 2.} a6 {We prepare to exchange on c4 and then follow up with ... b5 .} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. g3 {A rare move. White aims to fianchetto his Bishop, hoping to get a favourable version against the IQP on d5 . But, of course, we spoil White's dream:} c4 {Immediately gaining space on the Queenside.} 8. Bg2 Bb4 9. Bd2 O-O 10. Ne5 {White decides to centralise his Knight before castling.} Nc6 11. O-O Re8 {We force White to decide their Knight's future by threatening to capture on e5 .} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. b3 {Giving us a free hand on the Queenside would be detrimental for White. Therefore, this Pawn break is an essential plan in White's strategy.} a5 {This vacates the a6 -square for our light-squared Bishop.} 14. bxc4 Ba6 15. Qc2 Bxc4 {Black's active c4 -Bishop compensates for the weak c6 -Pawn. This is where we left our analysis in the chapter. Now let us see how the maestro GM Carlsen manages to outplay his opponent from this equal position.} 16. Rfb1 {White hopes to exploit the b -file in the near future. Their main idea now is to play Na4 , intending to cement the Knight on the c5 -square.} Bxc3 {A timely exchange! We eliminate the Knight before it starts jumping around our Queenside. The other advantage of this exchange is that we gain access to the e4 -square.} 17. Bxc3 Ne4 18. Be1 h5 {A typical Pawn advance that aims to weaken White's Kingside.} 19. Qd1 {This allows Black to induce unnecessary weaknesses on the Kingside.} (19. h4 {stopping Black's Pawn march was a safer option.}) 19... h4 20. g4 a4 {It is curious to note how GM Magnus Carlsen uses his flank Pawns to gain space on both sides of the board.} 21. a3 {This throws away the control of the b3 -square.} ({Once again, advancing his h -Pawn with} 21. h3 {was a safer alternative for White.}) 21... Bb3 22. Qe2 Re6 {Black improves the position of his Rook, which now has the option of swinging to the Kingside if required.} (22... c5 $5 {was a better choice opening up lines for Black's Pieces.} 23. dxc5 Nxc5 {Black has ideas like ... Bc4 followed by either ... Nb3 or ... Nd3 . Our active Pieces give us a clearly better position.}) 23. Rc1 Qg5 {Provoking White to play f4 , which would further weaken his Kingside.} 24. f4 {And White goes for it.} Qe7 {Now, the e3 -Pawn has become a target.} 25. Bb4 Qc7 26. f5 Ree8 {White has managed to gain space on the Kingside by marching his f2 -Pawn to the f5 -square. But that has created more weaknesses on his Kingside than before.} 27. Qe1 Qd8 28. Rxc6 {White manages to win a pawn. Objectively, the position is more or less balanced, but practically, we can feel that Black is firmly in the driver's seat.} h3 {An interesting pawn sacrifice that opens up lines on the Kingside. This also ensures that White's g4 -Pawn remains shaky for a while, as White won't be able to support it with h3 .} 29. Bxh3 Qg5 30. Qe2 Rac8 31. Rac1 {At last, White crumbles under pressure.} (31. Rcc1 {was a fine alternative, keeping control over the c -file.} Rxc1+ 32. Rxc1 Nf6 {Even though Black is two pawns down, he enjoys a strong compensation for them due to White's weak Kingside.}) 31... Bc4 {This short Bishop retreat breaks the connection between White's Rooks.} 32. Rxc8 Bxe2 33. Rxe8+ Kh7 {White has won two rooks for the Queen, which looks quite rosy on paper. But the reality is that the white King's shelter is about to collapse.} 34. Bd2 Bxg4 35. Bg2 Bf3 {And White resigned since the mate on g2 was unavoidable.} *

